(3, 1, '', 'Cochin Refineries School celebrated its 51st foundation day', 'Kochi', '900004677_2017-08-19_02-43-24.JPG', '', '', 'Cochin Refineries School established in 1966, is situated on the picturesque hill top of Jwalagiri.The school is run by Cochin Refineries Educational Aid Society and managed by Board of Governors nominated by the management of BPCL Kochi Refinery.', 'Libin Chacko Kurian', '', '2017-08-11', '<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span >On Friday, Cochin Refineries School celebrated its 51<sup>st</sup> foundation day in ><span >founded for the children of employees of erstwhile Kochi Refineries Ltd.</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span >A </span>P M<span > Mohammed Hanish IAS, Chairman &amp; MD Kerala State Civil Supplies Corporation was the chief guest of this event and congratulated both students and staffs for completing another year of success.</span><br></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span >&nbsp;He said “I had to work in tandem with the Bharat petroleum when I was the district collector of Ernakulam. I use to speak about the dedication, professionalism and the tremendous deal of commitment showed not only for the In-house activities but also the outreach activities they had for the well being of people in the society. As children of these officers sitting here, I think Cochin refineries School should be in its heights of excellence and ultimately reach the pinnacle of glory and say to the whole nation that here is an institution that did not just produce studious students but indeed produce various citizens.”</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span ></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span >“When it comes to the Cochin Refineries School this has become the collection of brilliance that is expounded by the officers and staff alike and it ultimately becomes the way for proper education. This education is complete only when the things learned in classrooms get harmoniously blended with whatever is to be provided from outside.&nbsp; Education is not about just providing what is taught in classrooms. Beyond the textbooks or any authoritative books, it is always a question of the interaction with nature and also the various give and take that an individual has with the society in which he is placed” said </span><span >Mohammed Hanish.</span><br></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span >The celebrations started with a public function where the annual report of 2016-17 was presented, school magazine was released and honoured the winners who achieved excellence in academic and non-academic fields with prizes and were followed by various entertainments.&nbsp;</span><span >The annual report was presented by Mala B Menon, Principal of the school and the School magazine was unveiled by&nbsp; M V Prabhakaran, chairman of the school board</span><span >.&nbsp;</span></p>', '1'),
(4, 1, '', 'Short film awards to be announced on August 26', 'Kaloor', '20246301_740814379451388_7815639932541499249_n.jpg', '', '', 'Screenscapes 2017 is a seven-day interschool short film challenge organised by Westford Institute of Film Technology along with Greets Public School.', 'Db Correspondent', '', '2017-08-21', '<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span >The challenge themed under ‘Fear’ was finished on August 14\nwith students of 9 to 12 classes from more than 60 schools participating. The\njury which includes eminent film directors of Malayalam film industry like\nShayamdhar, Jude Antony Joseph and&nbsp;</span><span >Dileesh&nbsp;</span><span >Nair will announce the winners August\n26 Saturday at a public event in Greets\nPublic School. 35 selected short films will be screened during the show.&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><o:p></o:p></p>', '1'),
(5, 1, '', 'Students in Kochi hit the floor in public to remind Hiroshima-Nagasaki Day', 'Kakkanad', 'NewsPhoto.jpg', '', '', 'It was on 06 and 09 August in 1945 that Hiroshima and Nagasaki were hit by nuclear bombs', 'Libin Chacko Kurian', '', '2017-08-09', '<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span >Students of Mary Matha Public School, Thrikkakara organised a flash mob on Wednesday at Kakkand open-air stage to remember the nuclear bombings of two Japanese cities and to spread the message of denuclearization of the world. Abdul Mutalib, district panchayat vice president, gave the peace message and school principal Sister Soja Maria read out a pledge for a world without war.&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>It was on 06 and 09 August in 1945 that Hiroshima and Nagasaki were hit by nuclear bombs during the second world war. It was the first ever warfare execution of this deadly weapon causing 129,000 deaths and significant casualties. The people of these two cities still bear the after-effects of these bombings even after the 72nd anniversary of the event.&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>\"This day is a reminder of the fact that we all are brothers and sisters and must work towards a peaceful world with no nuclear weapons. Let us appreciate the student\'s teachers and the school which initiated such a reminder to the society\", said Abdul Mutalib. He also released a white pigeon as a symbol of peace while inaugurating the function. A N Shaju, sub-inspector, Kakkanad Janamithri police station were also present.</span></p>', '1'),
(6, 1, '', 'Students of Bhavan\'s Girinagar won ‘Best Short Film Award’ in Screenscapes 2017.', 'Kaloor', '21231306_1934427116769417_7619829815461634124_n.jpg', '', '', 'Screenscapes 2017 is a seven-day interschool short film challenge organised by Westford Institute of Film Technology along with Greets Public School.', 'Libin Chacko Kurian', '', '2017-08-28', '<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span >Phayam</span><span > (ഫയം)</span><span >, the film made by the students of Bhavan\'s Vidya Mandir, Girinagar had won the award for ‘Best Short Film’ in a function held on August 26, 2017, at Greets Public School, Kaloor. The team was presented with a trophy, certificate and Rs.25000.</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span >Screenscapes 2017, the Inter-School Short Film Festival organized by Westford Institute of Film Technology in association with Greets Public School, was assessed by a panel of judges including Director Shyamdhar, Director and Actor Dileesh Pothen, Scriptwriter Dileesh Nair and Director Jude Anthany Joseph. The filmmakers also shared their experience of the hardships and fun they had during the making of the movies.<o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span >Jess Thaddeus of Rajagiri Christu Jayanthi Public School, Kakkanad won the award for ‘Best Director’ for the film ‘Bridge’, while ‘Best Scriptwriter’ was Susan Ben from Assisi Vidyaniketan Public School, Perumpilly writing for the film ‘Nirbhaya’</span><span > (നിർഭയ)</span><span >. <o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span >Arjun Kumar of Bhavan’s Vidhya Mandir, Elamakkara became the ‘Best Actor’ for acting in the film ‘Kochu Pustakam’ (</span><span >കൊച്ചു</span><span >&nbsp;</span><span >പുസ്തകം)</span><span > and Alina Meria Felix was selected as the ‘Best Actress’ for her performance in the film ‘Phobia’ of MGM, Kakkanad. Shooting for the seven-day challenge themed under ‘Fear’ was finished on August 14 with students of 9 to 12 classes from more than 60 schools participating.<o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span >Along with Actors Vinay Fort, Deepti Sati and singer Kumari Shreya Jayadeep, Thomas &nbsp;Vadakekut, Chairman of Bethel Foundation, P Silaskutty, Superintendent and Treasurer, Sabu Thomas Vadakekut, Director and Managing Trustee, Thomas Sabu Vadakekut, Member of School Managing Committee were present during the occasion.</span></p>', '1'),
(8, 1, '', 'Students of St. Albert’s HSS extend their hands for the hungry', 'Kacheripady', 'aid154213-v4-728px-Deal-With-Beggars-Asking-You-for-Money-Step-4-Version-2.jpg', '', '', '‘The good Samaritan’ is a project launched by the students to feed the hungry', 'Db Correspondent', '', '2017-08-30', '<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span >If you know the city well or even if you have visited it for once, you may have come across plenty of the homeless, hungry and needy people in the streets. Soon you will also start to see the uniformed school students bringing lunch packets and feeding them with delicious food at High Court Junction or Bus stands or even in railway stations. They are the students of St. Albert’s Higher Secondary School who took an initiative to open their hands and reach out to the hungry every week.</span><br></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><o:p></o:p></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\">‘The good Samaritan’, as it is called, is a unique project launched by the students in a joint venture with JRC in August 2017 and are planned to continue throughout the year. Weekly turns are given to the classes so that all students can contribute and know that these simple deeds of goodness can make changes in society. <o:p></o:p></p><p>\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n</p><p class=\"MsoNormal\">Rev. Fr. Felix Chullikal, general manager, St. Albert’s HSS inaugurated the project and appreciated the goodwill of students to helps the needy and homeless. Love and Care is a city-based organization which helps the students to distribute it in different parts of the metropolis.&nbsp;<o:p></o:p></p>', '1'),
(9, 1, 'daybreak', 'The first ‘Magic Tree’ got planted at St. Albert’s HSS', 'Kacheripady', '310807.jpg', '', '', 'The project aims to build environmental awareness and interaction among students by planting and nurturing a tree in every school.', 'Libin Chacko Kurian', '', '2017-08-31', '<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p><span >With the concept of ‘One School One Tree’, ‘The Daybreak’ has launched its first ever campaign here on Thursday. ‘Magic Tree’ has got inaugurated by Fr. Felix Chullikal, general manager of St. Alberts Higher Secondary School by planting a Banyan tree on its campus with a crowd of young minds.</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><o:p></o:p></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\">The project is an attempt to develop the culture close to nature and inculcate them into the young minds of the city by planting a tree in every school and let students travel through the entire process of its growth. <o:p></o:p></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\">While planting the tree Fr. Felix said “St. Albert’s HSS is already a great example for protecting the nature, as we could see that every tree inside the campus is flourishing ever since they are planted due to the care we give. We are also on a mission to grow more fruit trees and medicinal plants so that students can benefit from them”.<o:p></o:p></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\">“The school had encouraged all sorts of attempts to mingle with nature and we stand firmly with ‘The Daybreak’ and the team for their enthusiasm to plant trees and nurture them for good”, he continued. <o:p></o:p></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\">&nbsp;From planting to protecting, from watering to fertilising, The Daybreak ensures the student’s participation in every single step with regular inspections. The team also targets the characterization of each tree by installing a box which allows students to interact and ask questions. <o:p></o:p></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\">The manure used as the medium for the plant is purely made out of waste through natural composting methods. <o:p></o:p></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\">Amalnath, director of ‘The Daybreak’, said “Greenery is the most crucial factor that we all and the coming generations desperately need. The Daybreak is taking an initiative not to just plant a tree but to create a culture based on the tree. We want you the students, the promise of future to take care of the plant and interact with us at every stage of its development.”<o:p></o:p></p><p>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n</p><p class=\"MsoNormal\">The team is looking forward to more ‘Magic Trees’ to be planted very soon.&nbsp;<o:p></o:p></p>', '1'),
(11, 1, '', 'The Govt School that walks way ahead in digital education', '', '15202627_952728844833880_7136502180711232138_n.jpg', '', '', 'Students of Chorode Government Higher Secondary School communicate with educators and students from more than 20 different countries including United States, Japan, Greece and Pakistan.', 'Libin Chacko Kurian', '', '2017-08-12', '<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b ><u><span ><o:p><span >&nbsp;</span></o:p></span></u></b><br></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span >Much before the Government of\nKerala’s introduction of Smart Classes and its investment into the digitalization of public schools, a school\nin Kozhikode district of Kerala has travelled much deep into the world digital\neducation.</span><br></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span >&nbsp;With more than 40 sessions every year, the\nclasses through internet help them particularly\nin improving the English education and building a global identity. The school authorities encourage students to have cultural exchange and study from different\nperspectives to stimulate the process of education.</span><br></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span >The school has permanent video\nconferencing system in its classrooms and for last seven years, the students use them communicate with\neducators and pupils around the world. These activities enabled students both\nin improving the language skills with courage and also in building cultural\nbridges with foreign countries to have their perspective\non education. <o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span >Annamma Kumaran Syke who pioneered\nthe idea of English education and cultural exchange through the digital medium is teaching English in the\nschool and was supported by management and PTA.&nbsp;\nHe also conducted webinar series, for the first time in Kerala, meeting\npeople in different countries at the same\ntime.&nbsp; <o:p></o:p></span></p><p>\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n</p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span >Andru Thayyullathil, Head Master, Chorode GHSS,\nsaid “With the cooperation of people and PTA we have developed a space for\ndigital education in our school which allows our teachers to make students\nexposed to the new developments around. Every division of our 10<sup>th</sup>\nstandard have a permanent online projector system and have build facilities to\ninteract with people anywhere in the world.”</span><span ><o:p></o:p></span></p>', '1'),
(12, 19, '', 'The Gods of Mount Olympus', '', 'image.jpg', '', '', '', 'Pravar Mukkala, 6th Grade', 'mazahirharoon@gmail.com', '2017-10-23', '<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span >You might know about all of the Indian Gods,\nbut there are other gods, too. One really interesting set of gods are the Greek\nones.</span><br></p><p class=\"MsoListParagraphCxSpFirst\" ><!--[if !supportLists]--><span lang=\"EN-US\" ><img width=\"13\" height=\"13\" src=\"file:///C:/Users/DAYBRA~1/AppData/Local/Temp/msohtmlclip1/01/clip_image001.gif\" alt=\"*\"><span >&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;\n</span></span><!--[endif]--><span lang=\"EN-US\" >Zeus\nis the son of Cronus and Rhea, two of the Titans.\nHe is the god of the heavens, sky, clouds, lightning, and wields the power of\nthunder. He is the father of many of the Olympian Gods.His spouse is Hera, and\nshe is also his sister. Now that is weird. But Hera is not the mother of many\nof the Olympian Gods. Zeus married many other women and had thousands of other\nchildren. <o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoListParagraphCxSpMiddle\" ><!--[if !supportLists]--><span lang=\"EN-US\" ><img width=\"13\" height=\"13\" src=\"file:///C:/Users/DAYBRA~1/AppData/Local/Temp/msohtmlclip1/01/clip_image001.gif\" alt=\"*\"><span >&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;\n</span></span><!--[endif]--><span lang=\"EN-US\" >Hera\nis the goddess of women, marriage, and childbirth. <o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoListParagraphCxSpMiddle\" ><!--[if !supportLists]--><span lang=\"EN-US\" ><img width=\"13\" height=\"13\" src=\"file:///C:/Users/DAYBRA~1/AppData/Local/Temp/msohtmlclip1/01/clip_image001.gif\" alt=\"*\"><span >&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;\n</span></span><!--[endif]--><span lang=\"EN-US\" >Athena\nis the goddess of wisdom and strategic warfare.&nbsp;\nShe battled Poseidon, the god of the seas and horses for the city of\nAttica, and won with the creation of the olive tree. The city was proudly\nrenamed Athens. Athena was born in a rather strange way. Zeus’s wife at the\ntime was Metis, and a prophecy told him that if it was a son, he would take\nover as a king. Zeus swallowed Metis and\nAthena burst out of Zeus’s head.<o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoListParagraphCxSpMiddle\" ><!--[if !supportLists]--><span lang=\"EN-US\" ><img width=\"13\" height=\"13\" src=\"file:///C:/Users/DAYBRA~1/AppData/Local/Temp/msohtmlclip1/01/clip_image001.gif\" alt=\"*\"><span >&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;\n</span></span><!--[endif]--><span lang=\"EN-US\" >&nbsp;Apollo and Artemis were born in a strange way,\ntoo. Hera made all the lands that had roots in the earth to not accept Leto,\nApollo and Artemis’s mother, and when she was pregnant. At the time there was\nan island called Delos that floated around, occasionally bumping off other\nislands. Hera banished Eileithyia, the goddess of childbirth to go to help\nLeto. Finally, the other goddesses distracted Hera with a necklace and\nEileithyia went and helped Leto. Out came Apollo and Artemis. Apollo, god of\nthe sun, light, oracles, music, song, dance, healing, and medicine defeated the\nmighty Python, a huge snake when he was four days old, and Artemis,\ngoddess of the wilderness and forests asked her father Zeus if she could be a\nmaiden forever and not marry. These two gods are also the gods of archery. <o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoListParagraphCxSpMiddle\" ><!--[if !supportLists]--><span lang=\"EN-US\" ><img width=\"13\" height=\"13\" src=\"file:///C:/Users/DAYBRA~1/AppData/Local/Temp/msohtmlclip1/01/clip_image001.gif\" alt=\"*\"><span >&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;\n</span></span><!--[endif]--><span lang=\"EN-US\" >Ares\nwas the son of Zeus and Hera, and Aphrodite was born from the remains of\nOuranos, father of Cronus.&nbsp; So\ntechnically she would be the great-aunt\nof Ares. Aphrodite had children with Ares, even though she was married to\nHephaestus. <o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoListParagraphCxSpLast\" ><!--[if !supportLists]--><span lang=\"EN-US\" ><img width=\"13\" height=\"13\" src=\"file:///C:/Users/DAYBRA~1/AppData/Local/Temp/msohtmlclip1/01/clip_image001.gif\" alt=\"*\"><span >&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;\n</span></span><!--[endif]--><span lang=\"EN-US\" >Hades\nis the god of death and married his niece, Persephone, goddess of springtime, daughter\nof Zeus and Demeter, goddess of plants and the harvest.<o:p></o:p></span></p><p>\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n</p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" ><span lang=\"EN-US\" >I hope you learned a lot of stuff about the\nGods of Mount Olympus!&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<o:p></o:p></span></p>', '1'),
(13, 19, '', 'My Cousin Pachu', '', '20170409_132314.jpg', '', '', '', 'Gauri Santhosh', 'mazahirharoon@gmail.com', '2017-10-23', '<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><br></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span >Anyone who has a\r\nnaughty sibling or cousin can definitely relate to this article. 6-year-olds in\r\nparticular- They simply cannot keep still! They have to run haywire, darting\r\nhere and there, causing all hell to break loose.<o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span >I’m going to tell you\r\na couple of hilarious anecdotes about how I babysat my cousin Pachu during his\r\nvisit to our home.<o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span >The havoc started two\r\nyears ago when my uncle Manu, my aunty\r\nPriya and my cousin Pachu came to stay with us a day or two. When they were\r\nbeing shown around the house, the grown-ups suggested I take Pachu downstairs.\r\nI had no idea what I was getting myself into when I agreed.<o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span >Pachu was very excited\r\nto meet my best friends, Lakshmi and err…Lakshmi (Lachu and Deva). <o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span >We showed him around\r\nour flat and we introduced him to a little boy his age called…um, for my\r\nsafety, I will not be mentioning his name, due to the unacceptable events that\r\nhappened later! <o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span >My cousin has longish\r\nhair for a boy, so the little boy teased him that he looked like a girl.\r\nUnfortunately, I learnt the hard way that Pachu had a fly-away temper. He threw\r\nhimself at the little boy and it looked like he nearly killed him from our\r\npoint of view. <o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span >We saved the little\r\nboy from the wrath of my little cousin brother and we sent him back home for\r\nhis own safety. <o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span >When we tried to take\r\nPachu home, he played an annoying game of “tigers” and kept roaring at us and\r\nbit us whenever we crossed the 1-metre\r\nbarrier. <o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span >We had no success and\r\nwe were about to give up any chance that he would be budged from the bench he\r\nhad made his fortress. <o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span >Then his head jerked\r\nup abruptly. We looked in his direction. There was a lovely red Porsche driving\r\nout through the gate. Pachu jumped up as if new life had surged through him and\r\nhe ran behind the Porsche as if his life depended on it.<o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span >The Porsche drove out\r\nof the apartment and out onto the road.<o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span >I had always known he\r\nwas mad about cars but this definitely took the cake. <o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span >The security guard shouted at him and we were scared to run out\r\nonto the street. I ventured out gingerly but there was no need for that.<o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span >A cat was chasing\r\nPachu and he ran to us, curls flying, eyes bulging. <o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span >At last, the tiger had\r\nbeen overcome by a mere cat. I could see the headlines.<o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span >For some reason, we\r\nwere overcome with a wave of hysteria and I grabbed Pachu’s wrist as we ran for\r\nhome.<o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span >I was really mad at\r\nhim but it is very hard to stay that way with him, so that was forgotten.<o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span >But the next incident,\r\nwhich happened recently, really could have ended him up in hospital.<o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span >We have moved to a new\r\nflat and so my uncle Manu, my aunty Priya and Pachu came to see it. I am very\r\nproud of my new bedroom, which has been painted according to the colour theme I\r\nwanted. The prize highlight is the 7-foot-tall bunk-bed which had always been\r\nmy dream to own.<o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span >As expected, Pachu\r\nscrambled to the top as soon as he got the opportunity. I started playing with\r\nhim and soon he got a crazy notion inside his head that I was going to whack\r\nhim or something.<o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span >It was only a play and I told him so. He kept\r\nbiting me and playing tiger again. I sighed. <o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span >I decided I had had\r\nenough of standing downstairs so I started climbing up the ladder to the top\r\nbunk.<o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span >I immediately\r\nregretted my decision. He said with a wild look in his eyes, “If you’re going\r\nto come up here, I will jump!” He positioned himself. Obviously, the words\r\n“seven-feet-tall” do not intimidate him.<o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span >I was grasped with\r\nfear. I was scared he’d actually do it. I wobbled a little on the ladder so I\r\nhoisted myself firmly onto a rung to keep my balance.<o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span >Big mistake. <o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span >He must have thought I\r\nwas going to climb up and whack him or something, (I had absolutely no\r\nintention of even scratching, let alone whacking a poor, innocent little child\r\nlike him) and he did something that made my heart stop.<o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span >He jumped.<o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span >I screamed.<o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span >Everyone ran towards\r\nmy room and came to see Pachu lying on my floor, and Priya Aunty was almost in\r\ntears. Thankfully, he opened his eyes, shifted and groaned, “My leg…ouch…” <o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span >Miraculously, he had\r\nno broken bones at all, except for a few bruises here and there.<o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span >We all sighed in\r\nrelief. <o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span >And I resolved never\r\nto be left alone with him again. If I could help it, that is. You never know\r\nwhat he’s going to get up to next.<o:p></o:p></span></p><p>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n</p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span >                                                                                                                                         <o:p></o:p></span></p>', '1'),
(14, 19, '', '         Searching for paradise', '10th Grade, Model school, Abu Dhabi', 'green_paradise-wallpaper-1024x768.jpg', '', '', '', 'Khadeeja Jashim, ', 'mazahirharoon@gmail.com', '2017-10-23', '<p><span><br>\n<span >Wandering all over the paradise</span><br>\n<span >I asked them where the paradise was</span><br>\n<span >They shook their head as if they didn\'t know</span><br>\n<span >Leaving me alone in a sea of grief</span><br>\n<br>\n<span >I searched all over the land</span><br>\n<span >And dived through all water bodies</span><br>\n<span >To search for the great big paradise</span><br>\n<span >Without realizing I am in paradise!!!</span><br>\n<br>\n<span >I heard a lot about paradise</span><br>\n<span >So green with big big trees</span><br>\n<span >Where we find love, kindness and humanity</span><br>\n<span >And where our wishes come true</span><br>\n<br>\n<span >I left home in despair</span><br>\n<span >I found hell in yesterday\'s paradise</span><br>\n<span >The green paradise of earth</span><br>\n<span >Has vanished by the cruelty of man</span><br><br></span><br></p>', '1'),
(15, 1, '', 'The rhythm of 1001 hands for world peace', 'Maradu', '19961380_10211021163418499_5310202760464911386_n.jpg', '', '', 'The students were trained for “Rhythm of 1k1 hands” by Imthiyas Aboobacker, the renowned choreographer in a bid for Guinness world record for the most number of hands coming together for finger dancing.', 'Libin Chacko Kurian', '', '2017-07-15', '<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span >On Saturday, 500\nstudents of Gregorian Public School, Maradu hit their fingers on the floor to display the unique art form of finger\ndancing in the rhythm of world peace and\nunity.</span><br></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><o:p></o:p></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\">When the song Vande Mataram started playing inside the\nauditorium of the school, hands in green,\nwhite and orange colours started to move and take steps with the rhythm using\ntheir fingers. For next five minutes, it\nwas a feast of music, rhythm and dance\nfor the audience. <o:p></o:p></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\">Named as “Rhythm of\n1k1 hands” the students were trained by Imthiyas Aboobacker, the renowned\nchoreographer, for two months. It was first of its kind in India and was also been a bid for Guinness world record for the\nmost number of hands coming together for finger dancing. <o:p></o:p></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\">The event was inaugurated by Joseph Mor Gregorios\nMetropolitan, while Sunila Sibi, Chairperson of Maradu Municipality and\nJayaprabha Pradeep, Principal of Gregorian Public School spoke.<o:p></o:p></p><p>\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n</p><p class=\"MsoNormal\">The finger dance was themed and choreographed as a message\nfor world peace and harmony.&nbsp;<o:p></o:p></p>', '1'),
(16, 5, 'normal', 'Kochi Metro inaugurated by Prime Minister', 'Kochi', '1496831541_kochi-metro-rail-limited-kmrl.jpg', '', '', '', 'Db Correspondent', '', '2017-06-17', '<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span > </span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\">Prime Minister Narendra Modi inaugurated the much-awaited Kochi Metro on June 17 in a grand\r\nevent at Kaloor stadium and opened the 13km first phase from Aluva to\r\nPalarivattom for public transportation. Thus Kochi becomes the first tier –II\r\ncity to have a metro go for a commercial\r\noperation. <o:p></o:p></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\">With the arrival of Metro,\r\nthe transportation system of the city will be restructured with feeder services\r\nof buses and an ambitious 800 crore Water Metro.  The project was executed by Delhi Metro Rail\r\nCorporation and will be operated by Kochi Metro Rail Limited. Costing around Rs\r\n6000 crore, the Metro has 26 km service with\r\n22 stations, while the first phase has 13\r\nkm with 11 stations. <o:p></o:p></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\">Kochi Metro Rail Ltd (KMRL) received the crucial safety\r\ncertificate and inspection report from the Commissioner of Metro Rail Safety\r\n(CRMS) with considerable appreciation in May. The team of CRMS praised both the\r\nsuperiority of works and the theme-based\r\nstations built under KMRL.<o:p></o:p></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\">After inspecting the 13.4 km section with 11 stations of the\r\nelevated rail corridor and the depot in Muttom, they compared the quality of\r\nwork of KMRL as better than that of the making of Metros in Bangalore and\r\nHyderabad. The inspection included tracks, trains, stations, fire alarms, CCTV,\r\nsignalling, telecommunications and public information systems.  <o:p></o:p></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\">The elevated corridor was also inspected by Pinarayi\r\nVijayan, the chief minister of Kerala on June 04 prior to the visit of prime\r\nminister after which he launched the function of solar energy project at Aluva Metro\r\nstation. He travelled a 13 km journey in the train along with Metro officials. <o:p></o:p></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\">The Metro has\r\nappointed 39 loco pilots, all from Kerala, of which seven are women. Kochi\r\nMetro hired 23 transgender persons for\r\nthe project and became the first government-owned\r\ncompany to do so. <o:p></o:p></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\">Every station was designed to exhibit the artworks and images\r\nbased on a unique theme. Passengers will have an exciting entry into the\r\nnatural beauty of Kerala at Aluva station, while CUSAT station exhibits the\r\nmaritime history of the state. Edappally station is celebrating the tradition\r\nof spices, coconut, tea and coffee made in the God’s Own Country, while the\r\nstation at Nehru Stadium showcases the prideful moments of in state\'s sports heritage.<o:p></o:p></p><p>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n</p><p class=\"MsoNormal\">The stations will also display uplifting thoughts from both\r\nfrom Malayalam and International literature. Kochi was the first tier II city\r\nin India to get approval to have a metro rail in 2011. The metro service is\r\nexpected to increase the speed of movements inside the city and decrease the\r\nnumber of vehicles with fewer traffic\r\ncongestions. The next 5 km stretch from Palarivattom to Maharaja’s College is anticipated to begin its service\r\nfrom August 2017. <o:p></o:p></p>', '1'),
(17, 5, 'normal', 'City celebrates humour with CariToons Kochi 2017', 'Kochi', '0-caritoon-kochi-2017--kerala.jpg', '', '', '', 'Libin Chacko Kurian', '', '2017-05-01', '<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span > </span><br></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\">With the second season of Caritoons Kochi 2017, Kochi celebrated the comic art forms from Ottanthullal to animated drawings and hilarious skits from May 4 to 8. Started in 2016 the cartoon and caricature festival organised by Kerala Cartoon Academy is intended to transform Kochi into the humour hub of Kerala. <o:p></o:p></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\">In addition to lectures by cartoonists, caricaturists and animators of national eminence, the festival also showcased discussion and open sessions with cartoonists. <o:p></o:p></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\">Exhibited in eight different venues of Kochi, the festival had separate sessions for children which included making cartoons, caricature and attending lectures. More than 200 children participated in making their favourite cartoon characters and learned from the eminent cartoonists, came from different parts of the country, about the art of drawing for humour with social responsibility. <o:p></o:p></p><p>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n</p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><o:p> </o:p></p>', '1'),
(18, 22, '', 'Why Peacocks flocking to city is not a good news for Kochi?', 'Kochi', 'Peacock_Plumage.jpg', '', '', '', 'Libin Chacko Kurian', '', '2017-05-15', '<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><br></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" ><span >Bird watchers around Kochi are alerted with a few unusual visitors in the city’s biodiversity: Peacocks and White broad Bulbuls. The birds that can be only seen in dry climatic regions are now reportedly spotted in Edappaly and Kalamassery. <o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" ><span >The visit is considered to be very uncommon and perhaps gives a message that Kochi is changing into dry climate. Especially, Peacocks were earlier only seen in dry places like Tamil Nadu, Chinnar, Wayanad and a few pockets in Palakkad. <o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" ><span >The climate is changing, definitely, due to human irresponsibility and exploitation. It is impossible to deny that these changes also have adverse effects on the lives of animals, birds and plants. Many times there are proofs that animals do have superior abilities to recognise variations in weather.  <o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" ><span ><o:p> </o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span >Though there is no scientific confirmation of this unusual presence, due to lack of data, the bird watchers confirm with uniformity that birds which can be spotted only in dry places are flocking to Kerala. <o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span >Vishnupriyan Kartha, Secretary, Cochin Natural History Society, said “It is impossible to predict a trend right now, as we don’t scientific data available. We have to wait until 2020 to confirm such trends identified by separate bird watchers. Because data collection both in individuals level and from CNHS are in a progressing stage. Still, the spotting of Peacocks and White broad Bulbuls in Edappaly and Kalamassery are unusual and shows the weather change in Kochi to a much drier climate.” <o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span >Since 2015, CNHS is working on an ambitious Kerala Birds Atlas Project to collect the details of birds that in the state and built a scientific database. <o:p></o:p></span></p><p>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n</p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span ><o:p> </o:p></span></p>', '1'),
(19, 4, '', 'The angry birds are back with a game to teach Physics', '', '104367668-bigbanglegends_splash_screen.1910x1000.png', '', '', '', 'Libin Chacko Kurian', '', '2017-04-22', '<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span >&nbsp;</span><span >Whether you are still playing the Angry Birds or not, you know one thing for sure: how exciting it is to throw birds at the pigs to destroy their base and win. Now the same team which has created this excitement is back with a new game. This time to teach you physics with the same passion and greatness.</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" ><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\nline-height:107%;font-family:&quot;Calibri Light&quot;,sans-serif;mso-ascii-theme-font:\nmajor-latin;mso-hansi-theme-font:major-latin\">Big Bang Legends is a science-based game launched by a Finnish start-up ‘Lightnneer’ in March 2017 to help students in learning particle physics while having so much fun. The game involves solving puzzles and mazes to earn collectable rewards with 118 super-powered characters from the periodic table which makes the player familiar with their names, symbols and characteristics which students might have to learn in classrooms. <o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" ><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\nline-height:107%;font-family:&quot;Calibri Light&quot;,sans-serif;mso-ascii-theme-font:\nmajor-latin;mso-hansi-theme-font:major-latin\">“Everything that happening in the game is actually based on science”, said Lauri Järvilehto, CEO, Lightneer. <o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" ><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\nline-height:107%;font-family:&quot;Calibri Light&quot;,sans-serif;mso-ascii-theme-font:\nmajor-latin;mso-hansi-theme-font:major-latin;mso-no-proof:yes\">Lightneer</span><span > is a Finnish start-up by a team of gaming innovators who were previously working on Angry Birds, the most downloaded game in the history, for Rovio Entertainment.&nbsp; Big bang Legends is their first project which brought together the brains of CERN and Oxford. The game integrates both casual and fun gameplay with educational content and particle physics. <o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" ><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\nline-height:107%;font-family:&quot;Calibri Light&quot;,sans-serif;mso-ascii-theme-font:\nmajor-latin;mso-hansi-theme-font:major-latin\">Lauri Järvilehto, CEO of Lightneer says: “We want to make the playful and inclusive Finnish model accessible to everybody in the world to get great learning results through fun learning.” “Five years ago we’d joke that one day we’ll teach quantum physics to five-year-olds. Now we’re seeing five-year-olds playing Big Bang Legends and having conversations about quarks, protons and atoms. It’s pretty amazing.”<o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" ><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\nline-height:107%;font-family:&quot;Calibri Light&quot;,sans-serif;mso-ascii-theme-font:\nmajor-latin;mso-hansi-theme-font:major-latin\">The company also revealed their plans to expand the brand from particle physics to building games about quantum physics, chemistry and even geography. The game can be only downloaded on Apple devices, but will soon be available on Android platforms too. <o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" ><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\nline-height:107%;font-family:&quot;Calibri Light&quot;,sans-serif;mso-ascii-theme-font:\nmajor-latin;mso-hansi-theme-font:major-latin\"><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></span></p><p>\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n</p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" ><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\nline-height:107%;font-family:&quot;Calibri Light&quot;,sans-serif;mso-ascii-theme-font:\nmajor-latin;mso-hansi-theme-font:major-latin\"><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></span></p>', '1'),
(20, 1, '', 'Blue Whale: CBSE asks schools to supervise online activities of students ', '', 'Blue-Whale-Suicide-Challenge-Game-e15017525176101.jpg', '', '', 'The circular directs to educate students, comply with legislation, take disciplinary actions and install surveillance systems.', 'Libin Chacko Kurian', '', '2017-08-23', '<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span > </span><br></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span >While Blue Whale Challenge, the online suicidal game is\r\ncreating a hoax in the country, Central\r\nBoard of Secondary Education (CBSE) has produced a circular on August 18 to\r\npromote safe and secure educational environment in schools by taking measures\r\nto pre-empt wrongful activities through IT-enabled\r\ndevices in schools. </span><br></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><o:p></o:p></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\">The circular says “Increasing proliferation and\r\nsophistication of various electronic devices makes it all the more obligatory\r\nfor schools to control and monitor their use by students.”<o:p></o:p></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b>Educate:<o:p></o:p></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\">The circular directs to create awareness among students\r\nregarding the safe and effective internet usage and display rules on the\r\nacceptable use. <o:p></o:p></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b>Comply with legislation:\r\n<o:p></o:p></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\">CBSE has asked schools to comply with the legislation of copyright, theft, discrimination\r\nand obscenity in devices and only use a licensed\r\nversion of the software in them. It has\r\nalso asked institutions to draft a policy on this matter and implement it. <o:p></o:p></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b>Take strict actions: <o:p></o:p></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\">The guidelines urge to take strict disciplinary actions\r\nagainst those violate norms and access inappropriate or illegal materials on the internet\r\nusing devices in school. <o:p></o:p></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b>Deploy surveillance\r\nsystem <o:p></o:p></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\">The circular asks to install firewalls, filtering and\r\nmonitoring software mechanisms and review blocking policies of unwelcomed\r\ncontents. Students should be using the internet\r\nin visible areas and only allowed to access pre-selected websites. <o:p></o:p></p><p>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n</p><p class=\"MsoNormal\">The circular reads “if children use the internet without\r\nsafety awareness, they may fall prey to illegal activity or abuse such as cyberbullying, fraud or something even more\r\nserious. Hence, awareness of internet safety norms is absolutely indispensable\r\nto make children free to explore knowledge without feeling intimidated.”<o:p></o:p></p>', '1'),
(21, 5, 'normal', 'Prosperity Index: Kochi declared smartest among smart cities in India', 'Ernakulam', 'Cityscape_view_from_Kakkanad.jpg', '', '', '', 'Libin Chacko Kurian', '', '2017-08-12', '<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><br></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" ><span><br>Among the first 20 smart cities announced, Kochi comes first in the prosperity index study done by National Institute of Urban Affairs (NIUA), way above the national capital. The study titled \'Multi-dimensional prosperity index(MPI): Review of the first 20 cities of India\' was published on the behalf of Asian Development Bank and was released on August 5. </span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" ><span>MPI is the new index introduced to examine the developments of smart cities which comprise of four indicators in itself such as (1)physical and financial infrastructure index, (2)health and educational infrastructure index, (3)community asset index and (4)household amenities index. </span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" ><span>Though the study showcases the impressive developments in the city, thanks to the all-new Kochi Metro, the report also highlights the challenges faced by the metropolitan on the way to become a true \'Smart city\'. This also provides suggestions and guidelines for the way ahead.</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" ><span><b>The report sights the bright side of Kochi as  </b></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" ><span>1. High literacy rate<o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" ><span>2. Low slum population<o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" ><span>3. High percentage of households with tap water, toilet facilities and electricity<o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" ><span>4. Availability of health, financial and educational institutions</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" ><span><b>The challenges were listed as</b></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" ><span>1. Inadequate transport and parking infrastructure<o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" ><span>2. only a few areas in the city are linked by sewerage network,<o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" ><span>3. polluted water bodies,<o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" ><span>4. shortage of open spaces<o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" ><span>5. shortage of land for new projects</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" ><span><b>The strategies included</b></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" ><span>1. Connect Fort Kochi and the central city through an integrated water transport project.<o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" ><span>2. Uplift the central city area through redensification.<o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" ><span>3. Harness the heritage assets of Fort Kochi and Mattancherry for tourism.<o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" ><span>4. Create new housing stock in Mattancherry.<o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" ><span>5. Upgrade the basic infrastructure.<o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" ><span>6. Augment the canal system.<o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" ><span>7. Ensure 24x7 water supply services</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Read full report here: https://khub.niua.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/07/multi_dimensional.pdf<o:p></o:p></span></p><p>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n</p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span><o:p> </o:p></span></p>', '1'),
(22, 25, '', 'World Peace Day: Remembering the girl who stood between the nuclear bombs', '', '667702-AP830426033-1024x6182.jpg', '', '', 'Every year, 21 September is observed as the International Day of Peace around the globe. This year, United Nations honours the spirit of TOGETHER, a global initiative that promotes respect, safety and dignity for everyone forced to flee their homes in search of peace.', 'Libin Chacko Kurian', '', '2017-09-21', '<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span >In 1982, the cold war\r\nbetween the United States of America and Soviet Union (USSR) reached its peak,\r\nwhen Yuri Andropov became the general secretary of Communist party of Soviet\r\nUnion. Everyone was discussing a possible\r\nbreakout of war between the two countries and most importantly a chance for the\r\nnuclear attack was in the air.</span><br></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><o:p></o:p></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\">It was then Samantha Smith; a 10-year-old schoolgirl from Manchester, USA wrote a letter to\r\nAndropov about her worries on a potential nuclear war and urged him to live\r\ntogether in peace. <o:p></o:p></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\">On April 26, 1983, Yuri Andropov wrote back to Samantha by\r\nassuring that he is doing everything so that war will not break out and also invited her to visit USSR.\r\nShe with her parents flew to Moscow and spent two weeks of that summer visiting\r\nchildren’s camp near Black sea, attending conferences and making friends. <o:p></o:p></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\">She later wrote in her book that she was surprised by the\r\nkind of friendliness of Soviet people and the gifts they brought. <o:p></o:p></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\">She became a sudden sensation not just in the US and the Soviet\r\nUnion but also around the world as a symbol of peace. Samantha also\r\nbecame to known as <span >\"America\'s Youngest Ambassador\" for her peacemaking\r\nactivities in </span><span >Japan<span >, before she died at the age of 13 in a\r\nplane crash.<o:p></o:p></span></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" >\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n</p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span >Do you know: The Soviet government issued a postage stamp with her face and named a diamond and an asteroid in her honour. </span><o:p></o:p></p>', '1');
