(23, 1, '', '27,848 students get tech training in Kerala to lead digital education', '', 'SNGCE_ComputerLab.jpg', '', '', '‘Hi School Kuttikuttam’ is an NCC-model student’s IT club started in 2016 at all government-aided schools to equip them with 3-year technological training and thus to maintain, monitor and secure the Hi-tech facilities used in their classrooms.', 'Libin Chacko Kurian', '', '2017-09-15', '<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span >Kerala Infrastructure and Technology for Education (KITE), previously known as IT@School, under the Education Department of Kerala, organised e@Utsav, 2-day training camps, for two batches of ‘Kuttikuttam’ divided into five specific groups of animation, cybersecurity and the internet, electronics, hardware and Malayalam computing between September 7 and 10.</span><br></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><o:p></o:p></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\">The camp held at 1368 centres across the state gave training to 27,848 student members of ‘tech-army’ with 2736 trained faculty during this vacation. The project aims to let students discover their hidden talents by giving 2-year continues training and a project submission which will enable them to monitor the technological facilities provided by the government to elevate the status of classrooms to Hi-tech. <o:p></o:p></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\">Saju S S, master trainer, academic division, KITE, said: “The member students of the club are the ambassadors of KITE who will maintain, monitor and secure the Hi-tech classrooms and disseminate the knowledge that they have received to other students thus benefitting all.”<o:p></o:p></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\">In the academic year of 2016-17, KITE, which paves the way for Hi-tech education in the state, initiated to build a network of one lakh tech-trained students army to maintain and monitor the 45000 Hi-tech classrooms of 2000 government-aided schools. The government is providing schools with interactive boards, laptops, speaker systems and projectors to elevate the status of classrooms to Hi-tech,  but only to those completed the criteria of getting basic facilities like tiled floors, concrete roofing, and whitewashing was done. <o:p></o:p></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\">Jayadevan C S, the Ernakulam district coordinator, KITE, said: “Globally, this is for the first time that a selected group of students are trained in such diverse technological sectors. For a high school student who joined ‘Kuttikuttam’ while studying in 8<sup>th</sup> standard, the training will continue for 3 years and will be the custodians of all Hi-tech classrooms in the state. The project also targets to make students realize the hidden talents that they have in themselves.”<o:p></o:p></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\">“The training is also connected to start-ups, Technopark, Infopark and even with the companies like Google which are already scheduled. The Code to Learn contest of Google had the most number of students registered from ‘Kuttikuttam’”, he said.<o:p></o:p></p><p>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n</p><p class=\"MsoNormal\">Membership to the club is provided only after rigorous tests and is constrained to 12% of the total population of high school students or 50, whichever is less, in a particular school. <o:p></o:p></p>', '1'),
(24, 5, '', 'With more passengers and extended services, Kochi Metro is gearing up', 'Ernakulam', 'DLxHup3UIAAm1o6.jpg', '', '', '', 'Db Correspondent', '', '2017-10-03', '<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span > </span><br></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\">On Tuesday, the second section of Kochi Metro’s first phase was inaugurated by Chief minister Pinarayi Vijayan along with the presence of Hardeep Singh Puri, Union Minister for Housing & urban affairs. The extended service adds 5kms and 5 new stations of JLN Stadium, Kaloor, Lissie, MG Road and Maharajas ground. <o:p></o:p></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\">The extension has made a considerable increase in the ridership of Kochi Metro as it now connects with the business centre of Kochi and is expected to decrease the traffic congestions at Kaloor, Deshabhimani and Kacherippady junctions. <o:p></o:p></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\">It is estimated that an average of 30,000 passengers travel on metro every day with Sundays and holidays having more collection on which days the metro runs in increased frequency of trains. <o:p></o:p></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\">During the inauguration ceremony, Chief minister confirmed that the govt will ensure the economic feasibility of metro which reflects the concern that metro is not getting enough ridership due to high ticket charges. The metro service may also introduce a monthly card and a full-day ticket system in subsidised rates to attract more commuters though the fares are not confirmed yet.<o:p></o:p></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\">With the feeder services planned towards an integrated transportation system which is expected to the traffic pressure on the swiftly growing city of Kochi. KMRL is also considering the second and third extensions from Palarivattom to Kakkand and from Aluva to Angamaly with possible stations at Nedumbassery Airport after completing the first phase till Thrippunithura. <o:p></o:p></p><p>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n</p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><o:p> </o:p></p>', '1'),
(25, 1, '', 'How St. Albert\'s HSS is helping to radicalise reading in other schools? ', 'Kacheripady', 'rszimg20170925101221.jpg', '', '', '\"Book on Wheels\" is an ambitious project kickstarted by St. Albert\'s HSS to pool books, rejuvenate economically disadvantaged school libraries and innovate the concept of library outside its four walls. ', 'Libin Chacko Kurian', '', '2017-09-25', '<p class=\"MsoNormal\" >In a mission to reach out to economically backward schools, on Monday, the students of St. Albert\'s HSS gifted as much as 1200 books, collected by themselves, to eight different schools outside the metropolitan limits of Kochi. The management and the students are now engaged in a mission to pool books on a large scale to help renovate libraries both inside and outside the school throughout this academic year.<br></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\">\"Book on Wheels\", as it is named, has got inaugurated by Fr. Felix Chullikal, general manager, St Albert\'s HSS by handing over a collection of books to students and teachers of St. Mary\'s LP School, Ponnarimangalam.</p><p class=\"MsoNormal\">\"It is very important to have libraries and encourage students to read which will not only help them in academics but also in creating a better future. Let me appreciate all those students who have contributed books to this mission to help students read and grow\", he said. </p><p class=\"MsoNormal\">The school is also building shelves in its corridors to catch the eyes of students towards books and encourage them to read. Particularly, reference books are taken out of the library to reach where students are and making them comfortable with it. To build the culture, teachers encourage students to bring books and donate them to the library instead of chocolates and food items during special occasions. </p><p class=\"MsoNormal\">The management has shown their enthusiasm to continue the project for coming years and help more students to read. </p><p class=\"MsoNormal\">Baby Thadevus Cruz, Principal, St. Albert’s HSS said, “We are planning to continue the project along with the renovation of our library throughout the academic year. We also want to help other schools also in restructuring their libraries and refocus their ideas on books. We are in a need to help our younger generations find their way back to books and reading.”</p>', '1'),
(26, 3, '', 'U-17 World Cup: Football is in the Indian court while the world is gazing', '', 'Kochi_U17_WorldCup_logo.JPG', '', '', '24 national teams from six confederations are playing at six stadiums in different cities around the country, while 187 countries across the globe are watching. ', 'Db Correspondent', '', '2017-10-09', '<p><span >With the first ever Indian appearance in a football world cup, 2017 FIFA U-17 world cup, the first FIFA tournament in the country, has kick-started at Jawaharlal Nehru Stadium, Delhi on 06 October. With the final to be played on 28 October at Salt Lake stadium, Kolkata, the 22-day tournament is all set to awaken the \"sleeping giant\", as FIFA called India, to the glamour of the world\'s most popular game. </span><br></p><p><b><span>Kochi</span></b></p><p><span >As one of the most important host venue for the tournament among the six cities, Kochi is well placed to exhibit its football-crazy fan base and the tourism potential in front of the world. The government of Kerala had spent at least 17 crores before the arrival of the world cup and beautified the city with better roads, beautiful practice grounds and improved sports facilities. </span></p><p><span >Kochi metro started its final section of the first phase just 2 days before the tournament, which includes JLN stadium station to ease the transportation inside the city, while the authorities have installed strict traffic regulations in Kochi. </span></p><p><b ><span >Brazil vs Spain</span></b></p><p><span>It was with great excitement Kochi celebrated the victory of Brazil over Spaniards for 2-1 in a much-awaited match in Kochi. Even after FIFA brought down the seating capacity to 29,000 from the original 60,000 due to security reasons. </span></p><p><b ><span >India vs the USA</span></b></p><p><span>The much stronger team of USA defeated India for 3-0 in a match which saw the first Indian appearance in the world cup but also won hearts of Indian fans with strong gameplay throughout the match. </span></p><p><span >24 teams managed to qualify for the tournament through various continental tournaments. The first round of the tournament will see teams competing in round-robin groups of four teams, with the top two teams in each group moving on while the top four third-placed teams will also move forward. These 16 teams will compete in the knockout stage, where three rounds of play will resolve which teams would join in the final.</span></p><p>\r\n', '1'),
(27, 3, '', 'National Sports Day: Remembering the hockey legend; Dhyan Chand', '', 'Dhyan_Chand_with_the_ball_vs._France_in_the_1936_Olympic_semi-final.jpg', '', '', 'Every year India observes it\'s National Sports Day on August 29 which is also the birth anniversary of legendary hockey player Major Dhyan Chand.', 'Db Correspondent', '', '2017-08-29', '<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span >We celebrate the National Sports day on his birthday on\r\nAugust 29, Dhyan Chand is one of the greatest hockey players of all the time.\r\nNicknamed as ‘The Wizard’, he was a wonder-man with a stick for many of his times because of his phenomenal goal scoring\r\nabilities and the control over the ball, scoring\r\nover 400 goals in international Hockey. He played a crucial role when\r\nIndia won three consecutive Olympic gold medals\r\nin 1928, 1932 and 1936.</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"center\" ><span >The officials of Netherlands\r\nHockey once broke the stick used by Dhyan Chand to check if he was using a\r\nmagnet to keep the ball with it. To admire his importance, the hockey lovers of\r\nAustria made a statue of Dhyan Chand with four hands and four sticks to honour\r\nhis abilities to control the ball. In the heights of his glory, the German\r\nChancellor Adolf Hitler was impressed by Dhyan Chand and offered him German\r\ncitizenship and the rank of colonel in the army, which he denied politely. </span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><o:p></o:p></p>', '1'),
(28, 4, '', '6 students from Ernakulam to compete in National Robotics Championship', 'Panampilly Nagar', '22046699_1965912983690108_5029788902621844131_n.jpg', '', '', 'With the robots that showcase the sustainable way of living, two teams trained under DCS Robotics Academy in Aluva and Panampilly Nagar are travelling to New Delhi today. ', 'Libin Chacko Kurian', '', '2017-09-06', '<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span >Two teams of three students each, from Ernakulam district, is participating in ‘Sustainabots’, the national robotics championship organised by the ‘India Stem Foundation’ in New Delhi on 7 &amp; 8 October. The competition regarded as the selection process to the ‘World Robot Olympiad’ that to be held in Costa Rica in November this year has kept sustainable tourism as the theme.</span><br></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\">The first team participating in the regular competition of elementary stage had gone through a state level selection process held at Trivandrum and had won the second place. The much younger second team is participating in the open challenge competition of elementary stage and had no selection process but a direct access to the game.&nbsp;</p><p class=\"MsoNormal\">Lincy Jexy, chief instructor, DCS Robotics, said “It is with confidence and skill our students are participating in the competition. Both the regular category and open challenge are ready with their maps, robots, equipment and software. The trainers and students will use Saturday to prepare all the stuff for contest according to the space provided there as Sunday will be the final day of competition.”&nbsp;</p><p class=\"MsoNormal\">“Robotics is a space where students can practically learn the subjects that they have dealt with in their classroom rooms, particularly Physics and Mathematics. Though with great scope, robotics get very less support from our state and in form of sponsorships. Whereas many other states and the governments have understood the importance and encourage both materially and financially” she said.</p><p class=\"MsoNormal\">The regular category has a strict format and pre-designed map based on the theme, while the open challenge is a competition designed to encourage innovation and the use of imagination in the field of robotics using the same theme.&nbsp;</p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b>The Regular Elementry</b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\">Aybaq Zyed (5<sup>th</sup> standard), Gautham Krishna (7th) and Vishnu P Venmony (7th) are trained by DCS Robotics Academy in Aluva to use the robots and ‘Mindstorm EV3’ software to control the pre-designed map that represents a landscape with oceans, rainforest areas and roads with characters such as jaguars, turtles, civilians and scientists waiting to get placed in their location. The task of the robot is to rearrange the characters inside the landscape by pushing jaguar to forest and turtles to water bodies while leaving civilians and scientists only at safe places.&nbsp;</p><p class=\"MsoNormal\">While the state level competition was to complete the task within the time frame of two minutes,&nbsp;the national level is about completing the same task in the least time, where more than 100 teams are participating from different parts of the country.&nbsp;</p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b>The Open Challenge<o:p></o:p></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p><span >The competition that demands innovation and the use of imagination, Nanak Johan Varghese (4</span><sup>th</sup><span >), Rachel Aji Joseph (6</span><sup>th</sup><span >) and Abhiram Rajesh (6</span><sup>th</sup><span >) have built a \'Sustainable city\' on their table controlled by robots. The city uses automatically moving solar panels with the movement of the sun, which may improve its efficiency by 35%. The urban centre separates its waste into the material, degradable and plastic using a sorting factory of Infrared and colour sensors.&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><o:p></o:p></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p><span >While the material wastes are recycled and degradable are used in farming, the plastic wastes are sent to a power station to generate electricity by burning it. Using the sensors, the city could also identify the excess amount of carbon dioxide (co2) in its atmosphere and push them to a forest nearby.&nbsp;&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><o:p></o:p></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p><span >DCS Robotics operates their academy in Aluva and Panampilly Nagar with more than 100 hundred children learn the aspects of robot technology. The institute already has won prizes at Roboray competition held in China last year.&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><o:p></o:p></p>', '1'),
(29, 16, '', 'It’s not just avoiding the plastic, but also to bring back the old culture', '', 'interview2.jpg', '', 'Mohammed Safirulla IAS', 'The Daybreak talks to Mohammed Safirulla IAS, District Collector, Ernakulam', 'Lakshmi Omanakuttan', '', '2017-07-07', '<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b ><span lang=\"EN-US\">Pre-civil service experience and the IT Mission</span></b></p><p class=\"MsoListParagraphCxSpMiddle\"><span lang=\"EN-US\">I worked in IT for 5 years with TCS and IBM. In TCS I worked as an engineer where I was an associate for software building, coding, development and to some extent testing also and at IBM I was SAP &nbsp;financial control consultant. As far as the project management of IT mission was concerned the previous experience in IT sector was definitely helpful. Moreover, IT mission’s profile is not only general administration but its techno-managerial role. Without understanding technology, you can’t manage it effectively as hardcore technology is involved in it. The experience in the IT field helped a lot in developing new technology projects like cloud implementation in servers, integration of database etc.</span></p><p class=\"MsoListParagraphCxSpMiddle\" ><!--[if !supportLists]--><b><span lang=\"EN-US\">2.<span >&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </span></span><!--[endif]--><span lang=\"EN-US\">Working with the common man</span></b></p><p class=\"MsoListParagraphCxSpMiddle\"><span lang=\"EN-US\">Unless we know the real issue faced by the people we can’t make effective policy for them. We should reach out to the people to understand their issue. &nbsp;To get the feedback on policies made and implemented we have to be in close connection with the people for whom the policies are made other than just sitting in the living room and making policies. Many of the times the projects fail because it’s only made theoretically not practically.</span></p><p class=\"MsoListParagraphCxSpMiddle\"><span lang=\"EN-US\">&nbsp;For instance, the 100-pound renovation in 50 days project is basically touching the pulse of the people; I have myself worked close to 65 pounds. &nbsp;Another example is E Jagratha, a project for the cybersecurity, which included nearly 240 schools in the district with continuous interaction with the teachers and students and the school about developments in the project and interactive training section from experts from TCS. The perspective of an 8<sup>th</sup> standard student from a government school will be different from the perspective of an IAS officer or IT professional. To understand the perspective of the people we have to go to them. End beneficiary link and the continuous feedback loop are very important otherwise it might not actually succeed.</span></p><p class=\"MsoListParagraphCxSpMiddle\" ><!--[if !supportLists]--><b><span lang=\"EN-US\">3.<span >&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </span></span><!--[endif]--><span lang=\"EN-US\">Creating&nbsp; a safe cyber platform for children</span></b></p><p class=\"MsoListParagraphCxSpMiddle\"><span lang=\"EN-US\">E-jagratha is an initiative to establish basic IT infrastructure and internet connectivity in schools and empower the students from different school background. It aims at preventing children from falling prey to predators in the internet world. E-jagaratha is also a tool to create awareness about the online transactions like e-billing, online purchasing etc. and to digitally empower schools students. <o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoListParagraphCxSpMiddle\"><span lang=\"EN-US\">As the cyber world is expanding that the information and the entertainments that it provides are very vast. Therefore the new generation needs to be guided on a different aspect to use the internet safely and effectively. Nearly 240 schools have covered under this project now. Students and teachers from the schools are being selected to undergo training in this regard.<o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoListParagraphCxSpMiddle\"><span lang=\"EN-US\">Quality implementation in the digital platform is one aspect of the project while reminding the students about their duties and responsibilities in the cyber world.</span></p><p class=\"MsoListParagraphCxSpMiddle\"><span lang=\"EN-US\">Another aim is to make them aware of the need for responsible use of the social media platform. Parents &amp; teacher\'s associations are also involved in the program. Aided schools and CBSE schools are also considered in the program.</span></p><p class=\"MsoListParagraphCxSpMiddle\" ><!--[if !supportLists]--><b><span lang=\"EN-US\">4.<span >&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </span></span><!--[endif]--><span lang=\"EN-US\">Green protocol to bring back the old habits.</span></b></p><p class=\"MsoListParagraphCxSpMiddle\"><span lang=\"EN-US\">Like other states in India, Kerala does not have unused land or uninhabited land. The population is spread across the state and there for the waste disposal is very difficult. Due to the difficulty in effective waste disposal, there is a need for effective waste management. For this reason, the city administration in association with Haritha Kerala Mission has initiated green protocol in the district. As part of this, events are conducted which was fully based on green protocol.&nbsp; It’s not just avoiding the plastic but also to bring back the old culture of using the nature-friendly utensils. The approach the public is very positive towards this mission. Awareness classes are also given in different level of the administration about the need for green protocol.</span></p><p class=\"MsoListParagraphCxSpMiddle\" ><!--[if !supportLists]--><b><span lang=\"EN-US\">5.<span >&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </span></span><!--[endif]--><span lang=\"EN-US\">For a successful career</span></b></p><p class=\"MsoListParagraphCxSpMiddle\"><span lang=\"EN-US\">There is no career which is bad. Every job is a good job. First of all, to have a successful career you have to love your career. Understand what you are capable of doing and work for it. One must work to find out what is your interest and develop your interest in your career. Only when you are interested in your job you can do justice to the work.</span></p>', '1'),
(30, 16, '', 'Create a greener nature for next generation', 'Ernakulam', 'interview1.jpg', '', 'Leena George', 'Leena George talks to ‘The Daybreak’ about her illness and how crafting and gardening healed her. The 64-year-old transformed her land around home into a mirage of greenery and celebrates an eco-friendly existence in Kochi metropolitan.', 'Lakshmi Omanakuttan', '', '2017-06-21', '<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span >When passion heals</span><br></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-US\" >I was passionate about plants and gardening from my younger age. My hobby and passion have created a phenomenal change in me. A year ago I suffered a nervous breakdown and I was bedridden. At this age, it was very difficult to overcome stress and mental depression. To help it out I started off my crafting hobby and gardening. These activities healed me and gave self-confidence that I am capable of doing anything of my interest. They tuned my mind and motivated me to carry on my passions. &nbsp;<o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-US\" ><b>The natural way of living<o:p></o:p></b></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-US\" >Recycling and upcycling are the best ways to have an effective healthy life because trash disposal is one of the major problems that we face today. Following a specific pattern for recycling and upcycling can reduce the amount of trash we have. I recycle most of the waste materials at my home by crafting it into a beautiful home decor or a garden utensil. No plastics are used for my creative works or in the garden. All the pots are eco-friendly, while the composts are made by natural methods like biogas, vermin and bin composts here itself.<o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-US\" ><b>Nurturing the habit of green<o:p></o:p></b></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-US\" >The habit of farming or gardening must be started from the school level as this can help in creating a greener nature for next generation rather than of plastic. Gardening will help to build a meaningful relationship between life and nature. In schools, this can be a part of extracurricular activities, projects and assignments. The children will understand the process of plant development; with which the students will be able to evaluate the importance of life in every living being. <o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-US\" >It is important to teach the next generation how to manage the nature and the life with it. The only healthy way of farming is organic. Use of pesticides and insecticides are widely seen in the present agricultural industry and the vegetables we buy from the markets are mostly contaminated. All my plants have a yellow tag with applied Neem oil so that the insects are attracted to it and will not damage the plant. <o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-US\" ><b>Role of schools and parents<o:p></o:p></b></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-US\" >Waste management or trash disposal should be a part of our behaviour for which the schools and parents can play a vital role. The children should be trained about how to dispose the waste and should be taught how to maintain the public place clean. From their tender age itself, the habit of leaving the waste into a dustbin instead of throwing it in roads or public places should be inculcated as a culture.<o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-US\" ><b>Filtering and reusing water<o:p></o:p></b></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-US\" >The technique of aquaponics is used for filtering the fish tank water. Water from the fish tank will be pumped into a tub with plants, stones and other filtering substances. The excreta of fish is used as a fertiliser for plants; whereas the water gets filtered and flows back to the fish tank.<o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-US\" ><b>Upcycling<o:p></o:p></b></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-US\" >When it comes to pampering the nature; I believe in using only nature-friendly substances like stones, bamboo stakes, old broken woods etc. Water retaining is an important matter in maintaining the garden and for this, I have used the small stones for making paths. Upcycling old substances like coconut shell into pots, broken pieces of cartwheel into name board and use of old glass jars for close terrarium etc. helps to keep the garden more eco-friendly.<o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-US\" ><b>Keeping the public property clean<o:p></o:p></b></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-US\" >The major problem in our country is that people are very insensitive of their trash. They are worried only about disposing of their household waste from their area or vicinity and are least bothered about whether it’s thrown to another’s property. Even the educationally qualified does not think about maintaining the public property or the neighbour’s land.<o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-US\" ><b>From trash to living rooms<o:p></o:p></b></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-US\" >The majority</span><span lang=\"EN-US\" > of the raw materials I use for crafting are trash, but I recycle it by giving a creative touch and make it worth to be placed in our living rooms. I try to avoid plastics for my crafts as much as possible because I believe in eco-friendly living. To add more, we use solar power instead of electricity.<o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-US\" >It’s not gardening or crafting will help you relax but it’s the interest of the individual that help. For everyone, the passion and hobbies differ and one must know what their interest is and should work on it. <o:p></o:p></span></p><p>\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n</p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-US\" ><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></span></p>', '1'),
(31, 16, '', 'A life dedicated to the differently abled children of Kerala', 'Ernakulam', 'maxresdefault.jpg', 'Mary Anitha, founder, \'Centre for Empowerment and Enrichment\'', 'Mary Anitha', ' Mary Anitha, the founder of \'Centre for Empowerment and Enrichment\' (CEFEE), is a socially committed visionary who indulges herself in supporting differently abled children in Kerala for their psychological well-being.  The institution conducts several public events throughout the year to bring these children together and thus back to the public domain. Excerpts from an interview with Libin Chacko Kurian.\r\n\r\n', 'Libin Chacko Kurian', '', '2017-10-10', '<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span><span><span><span><span><span><span><span><span><span><span><span><span><span><span><span><span><span><span><span><span><span><span><span><span> </span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b>Can you introduce us to how these works started?</b></p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" >I always had an inner calling to work for the downtrodden communities in our society. It was the differently abled children that I found heavily disadvantaged and started to serve them from 2011 with the inception of&nbsp;CEFEE. While studying in Hyderabad I had such experiences in social works, which may have intrigued me to do such works.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" ><b>Why we really need an institution for differently abled children?</b></p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" >Though the central government does have a department for the persons with disabilities, the state government of Kerala doesn\'t have a separate body, but only under the social justice department with many other sections take care of disabled. Differently abled children are often left unnoticed and are disadvantaged during the allocation of funds due to several such reasons.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" >In our programs, we minimize the number of speeches and keep an extra vigil to indulge with them because what they need the most is the love to remove the rejections that they have faced in their life. You won\'t often see differently-abled children on streets and are kept out of public spaces, which shouldn’t make them foreign to democratic rights. They are in real need for a community to bring them under a single umbrella while the blind already had such federations in both central and state level.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" ><b>Can you define the ‘differently abled’ children that you deal with?</b></p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" >By children, I don\'t mean under-18 because their mental age may differ from that of the physical age. So, when I say children this may also include a person of physical age 45&nbsp;and his mental age could be around 8-9. The differently abled is a large spectrum of several categories which may include cerebral palsy, mental retardation, orthopaedic disabilities, deaf, dump or with multiple disabilities.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" ><b>What are the problems faced by these children?</b></p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" >The whole category of differently abled children is grown with very a low self-esteem and they find themselves in a difficult state to build confidence from a very young age. The first rejection came from their own parents, who cannot accept the condition into which their children are born into. Of course, parents do have their own expectation about how their children may look like or what he may do or even about what he should become. Often such parents may end up in taking care of their children without accepting the disabilities he does have which may cause severe psychological implications on children.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" ><b>The golden thousand days<o:p></o:p></b></p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" >Only if the parent accepts the fact of disability, the door of treatment opens before their children. But parents often use a defensive mechanism to reject this fact and in a way, deny several treatments that the child should be receiving. If you can start treatment on the first thousand days of a child, when most of the disabilities can be identified, many disabilities like body distortions or brain damage can be reverted. From that point of time, if parents can start treatments with an acknowledgement that his child is different, we can make him grow into a comparatively normal condition.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" ><b>Physical rejections<o:p></o:p></b></p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" >Many times children with disabilities are grown with rejections in different parts of their life and he will revert it back to the society. Even a normal kid would have done the same, but a child with disabilities also have a potential to get violent in such situations. He will not be able to accept the people around. Due to such behaviours, parents often lock them inside a house and would never consider taking him outside. They are heavily separated from the mainstream society.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" ><b>A problem with the wealthy<o:p></o:p></b></p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" >Children with disabilities born to wealthy parents also face some peculiar challenges. Such children are often gifted with advanced infrastructure facilities, drivers, and servants while denying love, which they desperately need. They want to communicate, meet more people and travel which we often reject them from. They are often tried to fix into routine or system which they may refuse to accept violently.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" ><b>Psychological rejections<o:p></o:p></b></p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" >Most of the problems that differently abled children face are rooted from the psychological rejections they face rather than the physical ones. The things we speak have a definite influence on these children and it amplifies the problems.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" ><b>The government<o:p></o:p></b></p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" >The government of Kerala is educating 20 lakh ‘so-called’ normal children in their schools whereas 8.5 lakh differently abled children are left with no consideration. On 14 November during the celebrations of Children’s day, the government gives them a treat provided with milk and banana, but through all these years and with all these schools they are never been invited to be educated.<o:p></o:p></p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><a name=\"_GoBack\"></a><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></p>', '1'),
(32, 5, '', 'Chief Minister officially launched Responsible tourism mission ', 'Kumarakom, Kottayam', 'Webp.net-resizeimage(2).jpg', '', '', '1.5 lakh jobs to be created under responsible tourism. The inauguration ceremony followed strict Green Protocol norms', 'Db Correspondent', '', '2017-10-23', '<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span >The Responsible Tourism initiatives in the state woke up to a new dawn, with the Chief Minister, Shri Pinarayi Vijayan launching the dedicated Mission for it. The world\'s first Responsible Tourism Mission is all set to lead Kerala Tourism through people-friendly, local community-friendly and environment-friendly, initiatives ensuring rural development, employment opportunities and women empowerment.</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" ><span lang=\"EN-US\">Sri Kadakampally Surendran, Minister of Tourism, presided over the function. Sri K Suresh Kurup MLA and Shri Jose K Mani were the chief guests of the function. Dr Venu V, IAS, Principal Secretary, Kerala tourism delivered the welcome speech and P Bala Kiran, IAS, Director of Tourism presented the Responsible Tourism Mission project. Sri K Rupesh Kumar, coordinator, State Responsible Tourism Mission announced the new Responsible tourism destinations.</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" ><span lang=\"EN-US\">Welcoming the gathering, Dr Venu V IAS Principal Secretary Kerala Tourism said that It’s a proud moment for all of us. Responsible Tourism that started off in Kumarakom is now a world-renowned concept and a point of discussion across the globe. It’s definitely a proud moment for us to be a pioneer in setting up this concept so effectively. Within a span of 9 years, 16 crores is the profit Kumarakom could gain through tourism. Around 1.16 crore revenue is generated by the localities. The reason behind this growth is the involvement as a group by the communities around. The aim of RT is to create 1.5 lakh jobs in the future, said Dr Venu V.</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" ><span lang=\"EN-US\">Presiding over the function, Sri Kadakampally Surendran, Honorable Minister of Tourism, said, to be the pioneer state in practising the concept of Responsible Tourism in the entire country is a proud moment. The government policy is to make Tourism more popular. Apart from improving the functioning of the elite class, the government also aims to use tourism as a tool for village development and women empowerment. Their aim is to make Responsible Tourism more beneficial to the localities. It feels proud to see the mission that started off in Kumarakom as a pilot project in 2008 and is very happy and proud about this. The Government moves forward aiming to bring in more job opportunities and income generation to the localities”</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" ><span lang=\"EN-US\">Inaugurating the Responsible Tourism Mission of the state, Speaking on the occasion, Honorable Chief Minister- Pinarayi Vijayan said, “Waste management should be a prime consideration in any development program. The tourist spots and places around the state should be kept clean at all times without asking for an additional cost. It should be a practice by itself. The tourism department should make enough arrangements to accommodate than the number of tourists coming into the state. One needs to appreciate Responsible Tourism completely for it is a source of support for the local communities. Our land is encompassed by serenity and greenery. That is why it\'s called God’s own country. Hence, more attention given to Tourism wing will only prove to be beneficial for the development of the state. There are a lot of countries around the world who has made the profit through tourism. Hence, the same level of importance should be given here. The people who come in as tourists are financially sound in many ways. However, it\'s not the financially sound people who walk in as tourists, there are a lot of people within our state who are tourists. Most of the tourists in our state are largely common and middle-class people. However, these people who hail from our state as tourists should not be exploited said Honorable Chief Minister Sri Pinarayi Vijayan. However, in today’s world, mentalities and approaches have changed slowly.  People abroad buy products from the manufacturing place itself thereby paying huge amounts for it. Hence, in order to sell these products, we have to ensure proper arrangements. We have to consider these tourists as our guests and we have to treat them well off and for this, the society will have to pay attention and equally contribute to this development. </span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" ><span lang=\"EN-US\">With a bunch of new projects under the new mission, the state aims at expanding Responsible Tourism across the state by incorporating a set of new destinations. Currently, it is carried out only in seven destinations in the state, viz. Kumarakom, Thekkady, Vythiri, Ambalavayal, Kumbalangi, Bakel and Kovalam. Kerala has bagged countless national and international awards and recognition for these projects. Sri Kadakampally Surendran, Minister for Tourism, Government of Kerala, bagged six National Tourism Awards 2015-16 from The President Shri Ram Nath Kovind, Vigyan Bhawan in New Delhi out of which one was credited for the Best Responsible Tourism Initiative for ‘Kumarakom’.</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" ><span lang=\"EN-US\">Shri P Bala Kiran IAS, Director of Kerala Tourism gave a deep insight into the Responsible Tourism mission project. 1”4 districts across the state have initiated Responsible Tourism cells. The state RT cell has been formed and has already kick-started with its functioning and as part of this, from 6 destinations, today we have almost 35 destinations on RT across Kerala\", said Bala Kiran IAS, Director of Tourism, Kerala.</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" ><span lang=\"EN-US\">Turning these baby steps into big leaps, the Mission takes Responsible Tourism to all 14 districts. The government plans to create 1,50,000 employment opportunities in the tourism sector alone through the Responsible Tourism Mission, in a span of 5 years. The selected destinations for the Responsible Tourism plan are mostly areas that are covered by backwater, sea, wildlife, heritage and diversity in areas comprising natural beauty. The scheme is being implemented with the primary objective of ensuring extra income and livelihood for agricultural labourers, traditional industrial workers and marginalized communities in these areas and to give equal importance to the social-environmental parity.</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" ><span lang=\"EN-US\">Vocational training will be provided to at least 50,000 local natives.  This year, as a part of Responsible Tourism, at least 20 Village Life Experience Packages will be opened. It has been proven that Village tourism packages attract a lot of tourists because of the conventional experience of rope-making, handloom, earthenware and toddy tapping in these packages. This project will take the responsibility of ensuring more ways of income to the local community by means of keeping traditional jobs, handicraft activities and classical art forms as part of tourism. The next 4 years will focus on the formation of widespread workshops, tourism planning with popular participation and much more.</span></p>', '1'),
(33, 20, '', 'Learn the law that safeguards children from physical attacks', '', 'child_abuse.jpg', 'Image for representation', '', 'The section 75 of juvenile justice act protects children from being assaulted in any kind.', 'Lakshmi Omanakuttan', '', '2017-06-10', '<p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"center\" ><b ><span >&nbsp;</span></b><br></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"center\" ><br></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span >On May 23, Kochi city police arrested Mini Mathew, aged 49 years, from a daycare center near Palarivattam, under section 75 of juvenile justice act and of IPC section 323 for assaulting a year and half old boy who was dropped off to the institution by his parents in the morning.<o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span >The incident came to light when a video footage of the event, shot on a mobile camera by another woman employee was telecasted in a television channel. The Victim’s parents lodged a complaint to the Kochi city police and Childline volunteers. Kochi Mayor Soumini Jain visited the institution and inspected the facilities and enquired about the incident.<o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span >Sec. 75 of juvenile justice act say that if any person who has control over or charge of the child does anything that can cause mental or physical suffering to the child, he or she shall be punished with imprisonment or fine or both.<o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span >If such act is done by biological parents of the child due to any uncontrollable circumstances, it is not punishable. Whereas if such an act is done by any person who is employed or managing an organization which is assigned to the duty of care and protection of the child and causes any mental or physical illness, then he or she shall be punished with rigorous imprisonment not less than 3 years which may extend to 10 year and fine of Rs 5 lakhs.<o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span >IPC Sec 323 explains that if any person voluntarily causes hurt to another without any provocation shall be punished with imprisonment up to 1 year or with fine up to Rs 1000 or with both.<o:p></o:p></span></p><p>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n</p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span ><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></span></p>', '1'),
(34, 20, '', 'Celebrate this Onam with the values and traditions we own', '', 'floretz-onam-01.jpg', 'Image for representation', '', '\'The Daybreak\' is looking back into all these Onam celebrations we had and reviewing its effect on the students who do it.', 'Libin Chacko Kurian', '', '2017-09-02', '<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><br></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\">Yet another Onam is here and that’s the festive season of Kerala. Most of the schools are preparing for an Onam celebration at the end of this month after all the exams are over. The students will leave for a short vacation as the month of September arrives.</p><p class=\"MsoNormal\">For all these years Onam and the culture have become the crucial part of school affairs and had a definite impact on the student life. In a recent development, the state Higher Secondary Directorate had to reschedule the exams in order to allow the students have Onam celebrations with other students.</p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span >This year most of the schools have scheduled their celebrations on August 31 as it is the last day before vacation and the only day left after exams. The beautiful floral arrangements of Pookalam, the traditionally dressed King Mahabali, the dance forms of Thiruvathira and other competitions are set to rock the schools this season.</span><br></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b>Breaks all identities</b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\">Unlike other festivals, which are religious and are confined to a particular religion, Onam has become the cultural identity of people in the state, while destroying all divisions.</p><p class=\"MsoNormal\">Though the legends and rituals belong to a single religion, the celebrations and cultural developments have crossed all boundaries of identifications. Schools and the celebrations they conduct had played a crucial role creating the secular face of Onam by encouraging students to breaks all such divisions among them.</p><p class=\"MsoNormal\">Thus Onam has also become the secular identity of our state.</p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b>Builds teams</b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\">Unlike any other festivals, Onam definitely demands a sense of teamwork among. Many of the schools have the Pookalam or the flower arrangements as their single biggest attraction. While some schools also have competitions among the classes for best arrangements.</p><p class=\"MsoNormal\">In any of these situations, a collaborative work of both students and teachers are required, which in-turn develops team sense and builds strong bonds among.</p><p class=\"MsoNormal\">This involves collecting beautiful flowers of different colours, designing the arrangements and making it into a circular arrangement of colours. The dance form Thiruvathira or competition items like Tug of war all require a great deal of teamwork.</p><p class=\"MsoNormal\">Thus Onam also makes students work in a group.</p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b>Sharing is caring</b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\">As the harvest festival, the celebrations of Onam have a great importance for the food or the Onam Sadya. Many schools had created a norm to have an Onam Sadya with both students and teachers which developed the sense of sharing.</p><p class=\"MsoNormal\">The Sadya always have the traditional nine plus vegetarian meal that we traditionally follow. To have the same food on this day has brought the sense of sharing and caring. The schools have a definite role in pushing them.</p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b>The costumes</b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\">Onam is never complete without the King Mahabali. Most of the schools have the arrangement for a traditionally dressed king-like figure to reach every student in the school. This is a reminder for the story and values he shares. Thus the celebrations of Onam also involve wearing the traditional dress. Beyond the Dhoti and saree, students are exposed to the Onam games which give a colourful twist into the costume diversity of Kerala.</p><p>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n</p><p class=\"MsoNormal\">The music and dance also take students to the rich antiquity of this state and makes it a traditional feast for children.&nbsp;</p>', '1');
