(37, 20, '', 'The South Indian declaration of independence from filth', '', '1493122674_a527AZ_waste_final.jpg', 'Image for representation', '', 'On the Independence Day of 15 August 2017, the Govt. of Kerala initiated a campaign, \'Freedom from waste\', to make Kerala free from waste with much hype and glamour.  Beyond the declarations and pledges, The Daybreak is digging deep into the world of wast', 'Libin Chacko Kurian', '', '2017-09-02', '<p><font color=\"#000000\" face=\"Times New Roman\" size=\"3\">\n</font><font color=\"#000000\" face=\"Times New Roman\" size=\"3\"><font color=\"#000000\" face=\"Times New Roman\" size=\"3\"><span ><font color=\"#000000\" face=\"Times New Roman\" size=\"3\"><span ><font color=\"#000000\" face=\"Times New Roman\" size=\"3\"><font color=\"#000000\" face=\"Times New Roman\" size=\"3\"><font color=\"#000000\" face=\"Times New Roman\" size=\"3\"><font color=\"#000000\" face=\"Times New Roman\" size=\"3\"><br></font></font></font></font></span></font></span></font></font></p><p ><span >Pinarayi Vijayan, the chief minister of Kerala, in a recent video\nconference with district collectors in the state pointed out that there has\nbeen \'no\' or \'a very little\' improvement in the state of waste management in\ncities and must look forward to a mandatory centralised processing plant in\nevery urban centre. He emphasised the importance of using both centralised and\ndecentralised methods of waste management systems as the latter is not giving\nexpects results in the state. He also asked to speed up the process of land\nidentification and acquisition suitable for these plants.&nbsp;</span></p><p><font color=\"#000000\" face=\"Times New Roman\" size=\"3\">\n\n</font><font color=\"#000000\" face=\"Times New Roman\" size=\"3\"></font></p><p ><span >The words of chief minister clearly reflect the concerns and dilemmas we\ntoday face with respect to the ever piling up filth around us.&nbsp;</span></p><p><font color=\"#000000\" face=\"Times New Roman\" size=\"3\">\n\n</font><font color=\"#000000\" face=\"Times New Roman\" size=\"3\"></font></p><p ><span >Why fear waste?</span></p><p><font color=\"#000000\" face=\"Times New Roman\" size=\"3\">\n\n</font><font color=\"#000000\" face=\"Times New Roman\" size=\"3\"></font></p><p ><span >Waste is everywhere in different forms and types. From households to\nindustrial factories, from farmlands to markets and from computers to internet\nall produce the left behind <span >stuff</span>. Be it\nin solid/liquid/gaseous form or divided as organic and non-organic, the fact of\nwaste has become a crucial part of our everyday life.&nbsp;</span></p><p><font color=\"#000000\" face=\"Times New Roman\" size=\"3\">\n</font><font color=\"#000000\" face=\"Times New Roman\" size=\"3\"></font></p><p ><span >We use several mechanisms to get rid of these waste materials using the\ntraditional methods of landfills or combustion or else by dumping them into\nwater sources.&nbsp;</span></p><p ><span >Landfills or by burying the solid and liquid waste under the <span >soil</span>, we may cause severe contamination of air\nand water. Lack of space <span >has</span> also become\na factor in discouraging this common but traditional method of waste\nmanagement.&nbsp;</span></p><p ><span >Combustion of solid waste also <span >creates</span>\npollution in air, water and soil as it has to come back <span >to like Newton\'s</span> apple. The burning in high temperatures and conversion\nof waste into residue and gaseous products also create life-threatening\npoisonous elements as shown in <span >research</span>.&nbsp;</span></p><p ><span >Throwing waste materials into water sources <span >is</span> one of the old method employed to get rid of filth when no other\nplace is available which heavily contaminates the water resources.&nbsp;</span></p><p ><span >Pollution caused by the traditional methods of waste management results\nin dangerous public health implications. Govt. of Kerala confirms that at least\n22 diseases common in the state are caused due to improper waste management.\nContamination of water resources <span >makes</span>\nthe state more vulnerable to the water-borne diseases.&nbsp;</span></p><p><font color=\"#000000\" face=\"Times New Roman\" size=\"3\">\n\n</font><font color=\"#000000\" face=\"Times New Roman\" size=\"3\"></font></p><p ><span >Freedom from waste</span></p><p ><span >Along with the Independence Day celebrations of this year, the\ngovernment of Kerala introduced an ambitious but a herculean task to make the\nstate free of waste. Freedom from waste is a campaign based on comprehensive\naction plan jointly led by Suchitwa mission and Haritha Keralam mission to\nprocess garbage at their sources like households, gated colonies, markets and\nindustrial units in a decentralised method. The local bodies are held\nresponsible for the implementations and ensure the community participation from\ngrass root level.&nbsp;</span></p><p><font color=\"#000000\" face=\"Times New Roman\" size=\"3\">\n\n</font><font color=\"#000000\" face=\"Times New Roman\" size=\"3\"></font></p><p ><span >Ordinance to stop throwing waste into water sources</span></p><p ><span >In a recent development, an ordinance was produced by the state\ngovernment against dumping garbage or any other form of waste into water\nsources may now attract a jail term of two years and a fine up to Rs 3\nlakh.&nbsp;</span></p><p ><span >E-waste from schools</span></p><p ><span >Schools, colleges and educational institutions play a huge role in\ncreating electronic wastes, which may release heavily poisonous substances into\nnature and cause severe contaminations. So, it is of paramount importance to\nmake sure the scientific disposal of <span >e-waste</span>.\nFor last two decades, schools are using several <span >types\nof equipment</span> in their labs to teach children, but wonder about what to\ndo with those left behind.&nbsp;</span></p><p ><span >Kerala Infrastructure and Technology for Education (KITE) along with a\nprivate institution is now engaged in a mission to collect, recycle and\nrefurbish the e-waste produced by schools in different districts of Kerala. The\nmaterials include computers, monitors, drives, printers, cameras, ups,\nprojectors, speaker systems, television, generators and various network\nequipment.&nbsp;</span></p><p ><span >Recycling</span></p><p ><span >Recycling is an <span >important</span>\ntechnique with tremendous potential for innovation used in waste <span >management</span> and comes third in the process of\nReduce Reuse Recycle. The practice involves converting waste materials into\nnew, usable products and reducing the filth and making things reusable.\nEncouraging the use of recyclable products can further take the scope this\nmethod by creating a cycle of production and waste management.&nbsp;</span></p><p ><span >Composting is one of the easiest and natural <span >methods</span> used in the decomposition of <span >biodegradable</span> organic substances in waste management. Aerobic\nmethods like a <span >pit compost</span>, pot composting,\nring composting or <span >vermicomposting</span> use\nmicroorganisms that require oxygen to decompose organic matter, while\nmicroorganisms that do not require oxygen are used in anaerobic methods like\nbiogas, <span >mose</span> pit or pedestal composting.\n&nbsp;</span></p><p ><span >Successful waste management has never been an accident. Coordinated\nactivities of both government and civil society required in the healthy\nimplementation of such ambitious projects. All the campaigns above mentioned\nare asking for more responsible citizens accepting the truth of filth against\nthe conveniences that we opt for many times.&nbsp;</span></p><p ><font face=\"Calibri\" size=\"3\">&nbsp;</font></p><p><font color=\"#000000\" face=\"Times New Roman\" size=\"3\">\n\n</font><br></p>', '1'),
(38, 21, '', 'Nurturing the youth', 'Ernakulam', '85509-004-6514E1B8.jpg', '', '', '', 'Dr Ajeesh Ramachandaran', '', '2017-05-19', '<p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"center\" ><span>&nbsp;</span><br></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" ><span>&nbsp;</span><br></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" ><span><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" ><span><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" ><span>In the past, the adolescent period\nwas wrongly described as a time of severe turmoil and anger. It was a period\nassociated with conflicts, intense\ndepression and mood instability. But this is not always the situation. For most\nadolescents and youth, this is a time of\nhappiness and discovery.&nbsp;This is when they successfully adapt to the\nvarious inherent changes that occur physically, mentally and emotionally. It is\na point of independent thinking, helping to mould their future careers and\npersonal frontiers.&nbsp;<o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" ><span><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" ><span>Youth too, like adults, face distress\nand have emotional outbursts.&nbsp; With the support and guidance of parents,\nteachers and counsellors, such events can be successfully conquered by\nadolescents without affecting their academic or social life negatively.<o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" ><span><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" ><span>It is imperative that the importance\nof social values and good lifestyle is instilled\ninto the youth. Parents, teachers and\nschools play an important role in enlightening the youth and moulding them\naccordingly. Adolescents seek inspirations and hence reach out to idols&nbsp;like on-screen personalities,\nsportsmen, politicians, and even family and close family friends &nbsp;What\'s\nimportant to note is taking inspiration is\nacceptable as long as this doesn\'t hamper with the emergence of the youth \'s\nindividual identity, personality and tastes.<o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" ><span><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" ><span>Adolescence is the time of strong\nfriendships, the emergence of new beliefs\nand exploring new frontiers. If given the\nwings and the right guidance, the sky is\nthe limit!<o:p></o:p></span></p><p>\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n</p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></p>', '1'),
(39, 21, '', 'How good are we as parents?', 'Ernakulam', 'bec6da30a20beb87640c1f1a0c492b29.jpg', '', '', '', 'Vinitha Prabhakar Patil', '', '2017-09-01', '<p class=\"MsoNormal\" ><span >&nbsp;</span><br></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" ><span \">We always hear about the attitude of\ntoday\'s youngsters. Are they really care less?\nAre they born stubborn? </span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" ><span><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" ><span>Any child who comes to this world is\ninnocent and pure. Their attitudes and character are cultivated by the family and\nthe society they live in. The very first time a parent gives in to the unduly\ncry of a baby is the first lesson learned by\nthe child. Cry, show tantrums and you are going to get things done. From the\nvery beginning, there should be definite\nand clear \'no’ and \'yes’. While the baby\ngrows, make it a point to explain why it is a \'no’.&nbsp; Even while growing\nup, they should be made aware of what is right for them and what is not. And\nwhy is something not right for them or not being provided to them immediately\non demand.&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" ><span>&nbsp; </span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" ><span>&nbsp; We always hear about spending\nquality time with the kids. It\'s not only about having dinner together, going out together, sitting together and talking to each other a few minutes\nevery day. That also is necessary. But it would be better if the time is used\nto create awareness about nature, about their lives as social beings. Take them\nout to a lawn, walk barefoot. Take them to the beach,\npick up beautiful shells with them. Do a bit of gardening with them.\nTake them to an orphanage at times. Clean the roadside near to your house with\nthem. </span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" ><span><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" ><span>Help them grow up as socially\nresponsible citizens, also as persons who can enjoy,\ncherish and love the beautiful nature. We are many\ntimes nostalgic about those little things we have seen, done and enjoyed\nin our childhood. But how many of us,\nparents have given our children a chance to jump in a shallow stream? How many\nhad the chance to play in the sand? How\nmany know about little joys like collecting Manjadikkuru\n(</span><span >Red\nLucky Seed)</span><span ;mso-no-proof:yes\"> or</span><span > Kunnikkuru (Jequirity) as we did in our\nchildhood. Such things that might seem to be silly to us now are those which\ncreate beautiful memories of childhood.\nLet them live like children.</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" ><span><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" ><span>&nbsp; &nbsp;The pressures of the\npresent academic system are immense. From\nthe very heavy backpacks to the coaching sessions, kids undergo lots of\ntensions. Instead of further pressure, let them have an understanding\nsupportive home front. Learn \'about’ your child. Learn about his/her weakness,\ndifficulties they face at their tender age, understand their talents, nurture\nthem. It\'s not just about making them an engineer or a doctor. It\'s all about\nmaking them successful persons. There are umpteen career options in front of\ntoday\'s kids. Try to understand about various options. The help of career\nconsultants can also be sought. It\'s not about doing what we wish them to do. </span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" ><span><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" ><span>It\'s about selecting what suits them.\nIt\'s about excelling in what one does. Children,\nespecially those in their teens need emotional support many times. Lacking it at home may make them vulnerable to the\ninfluence of anti-social elements who may\nexploit the situation. As there are no longer joint families, parents should\ntake extra care to give them space and time to open up. That should be done\nwithout nagging and irritating the teen who thinks of himself/herself as an\nadult. Never judge them comparing their acts and ></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" ><span>&nbsp; &nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" ><span>The kids are like diamonds...the care\ngiven in shaping and polishing the diamond makes it shine forever. Give the\nchildren your love and support. Understand them. Let them grow up to be bright\ngems that shine brightly.</span></p><p>\n</p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span ><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></span></p>', '1'),
(40, 21, '', 'Laws to make children stay protected from the vulture eyes', '', 'child-sexual-abuse-802-x-460.jpg', '', '', '', 'Adv. Jomon Vargheese', '', '2017-05-31', '<p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"center\" ><b ><span><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></span></b><br></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" ><br></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" ><span>Children, irrespective of gender and age are at a risk of sexual abuse\nat any point in time. It is the greatest\nof all concerns among parents to make sure that their children stay protected\nfrom the vulture eyes of abusers.&nbsp;<o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" ><span><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" ><span>The governments from time tried to implement\nstringent laws to protect the children and women from acts of sexual abuse. The\nlast among them is the POCSO Act &nbsp;2012(Protection of children from sexual\noffences act) which is formulated and brought into force from 14/11/2012. The occurrence\nif notorious Nirbhaya case which happened at Delhi and shook the entire country\npaved the way for such an immediate enactment.&nbsp;<o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" ><span><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" ><span>New offences, special courts, special public prosecutors, mandatory\nreporting, punishment for false reporting, special procedures, in-camera trials, compensation etc are the\nsalient features of this Act.&nbsp;<o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" ><span><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" ><span>The major sections of this Act are sections 3,5,7,9 and 11 which are\nrespectively Penetrative sexual assault, Aggravated penetrative sexual assault,\nsexual assault, Aggravated sexual assault and sexual harassment.<o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" ><span><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" ><span>Even though the governments are\ntrying hard to curb any sort of abuse in\nchildren, it is the paramount duty of each and every parent to make sure that\ntheir child remains safe. It is a\ndisgrace to the entire country, that one out of every 10 women reported some\nkind of child sexual abuse during childhood, chiefly by known persons.<o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" ><span><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" ><span>Two million child commercial sex workers between age 5 to 15 lives in\nIndia. Proper awareness and stringent laws alone is a practical remedy against\nthese odds. Let\'s March towards a better and beautiful India.<o:p></o:p></span></p><p>\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n</p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></p>', '1'),
(45, 21, '', 'Decoding education: How the curriculums are separated from life itself?', '', 'AZ0_8925web.jpg', 'Image for representation', '', 'Proper sex education is yet to be a part of the curriculum. Biology lessons cover the topics about puberty, reproduction etc. Teachers, especially in co-ed schools, just cover the portion fast without many explanations so as to avoid embarrassment.', 'Vinitha Prabhakar Patil', '', '2017-10-07', '<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span> </span><span >Tini tots who join kindergarten at the age of three or four are\r\npure souls who can be shaped into beautiful personalities by the end of their\r\neducation. The school education, including the K.G section, consists of fourteen years as per Indian curriculum. Can\r\nwe say that the students who pass the 12th standard are educated in all aspects\r\naccording to their age? They learn a lot of subjects in school, earn high\r\nmarks, yet remain unable to face the real world. The school syllabus in India\r\nis really tough and takes entire working hours of the year to be taught. But\r\nthere are certainly other areas of wisdom\r\nto be shared with children according to their age. These include sex education,\r\nenvironmental awareness, general awareness about society etc.</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><o:p></o:p></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\">How many of the\r\nhigher secondary students of present-day\r\nknow about the functioning of services such as\r\npostal service, banking service,\r\nelectricity or drinking water supply services and the ways in which the\r\npayments are made or faults reported? The school syllabus is made in such a way\r\nthat a lot of academic knowledge is imparted to the child and the child learns\r\nthem without knowing their real applications in real life. It is high time to\r\nrethink whether all these things are to be taught to a child without considering\r\nthe aptitude and ability of the child.<o:p></o:p></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\">Proper sex\r\neducation is yet to be a part of the curriculum. Biology lessons cover the\r\ntopics about puberty, reproduction etc.\r\nTeachers, especially in co-ed schools, just cover the portion fast without many explanations so as to avoid embarrassment. Children often resort to internet and\r\nfriends and acquire incorrect and dangerous information. Time should be allowed in the curriculum\r\nfor sessions by doctors, child psychologists and counsellors.  Adolescent children should be made aware of\r\ntheir growth, changing bodies and,\r\npsychological aspects related to these changes. They should be made aware of\r\nthese aspects of the opposite sex too in a teenage-friendly\r\nmanner.<o:p></o:p></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\">It is also seen\r\nthat gender discrimination is embalmed in their minds from a very young age. In\r\nsmall classes itself, they learn that mom\r\nis supposed to do this and dad is supposed to that. More about gender\r\ndiscrimination at school level can be discussed in\r\na separate article as there is a lot to write about it. There is no time\r\nfor kids even to interact properly or play together. In some schools, the lunchtime\r\nis just 25 minutes. Students hardly get enough time to have the hot lunch\r\nserved in the canteen. Let alone playing at school, kids don\'t get enough time\r\nto play at home too. The syllabus needs extra tuitions to learn and acquire\r\ngood marks. The competitive exams which await them make it necessary to undergo\r\nrigorous coaching classes. Coaching for IIT-JEE\r\nnowadays starts from class VI.<o:p></o:p></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\">No extra reading is\r\nencouraged in most of the schools. Of course,\r\nthere are exceptions. Schools which do not encourage extra reading cannot be\r\nblamed completely. The teachers barely have time to finish the prescribed\r\nportions and revise prior to exams. It is often seen that kids are asked to\r\nkeep away from gadgets like computers and concentrate only on studies. Instead\r\nof banning and evoking unnecessary interest and curiosity, these gadgets can be\r\nused as tools for education, moving with the times. There are certain schools\r\nin India which have adopted different curriculum, mostly international, where\r\nthe children of the privileged class only can study. A change from the grass\r\nroot level only can change the nation. A unified syllabus for the entire\r\ncountry is the need of the hour. Else it will help only in creating more class\r\ndiscrimination.</p>', '1'),
(56, 1, '', '10 Facts You Must Know About Kerala State School Sports and Games 2017', '', '22730056_855379104631661_1394992416019561766_n.jpg', 'St Joseph\'s HSS, Pullurampara secured 2nd position in the meet with just 32 participants.', '', 'The four-day sports meet, concluded on Monday, witnessed 2800 students competing in 95 different events at Pala Municipal Stadium. Chief minister, Pinarayi Vijayan, inaugurated the 61st sports meet along with the new synthetic tracks in the stadium.', 'Db Correspondent', '', '2017-10-24', '<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b>1.<span >       </span>The 12th champion title for Ernakulam<br></b></p><p class=\"MsoListParagraphCxSpMiddle\">Ernakulam district secured the top position and lifted their 12th title of the overall championship in the meet defeating Palakkad, the defending champions, for as much as 73 points. The district had a total of 258 points with 34 gold and 16 silver medals.</p><p class=\"MsoListParagraphCxSpMiddle\" ><b>2.<span >       </span>Once again, Palakkad had to step down</b></p><p class=\"MsoListParagraphCxSpMiddle\">Palakkad was the crowned champion district in the 60th sports meet held at Malappuram last year defeating Ernakulam for mere 8 points ending its many years of domination. But once again the district had to sit in the second position after the results of this year came out. The district secured 185 points with 22 gold and 4 silver medals.</p><p class=\"MsoListParagraphCxSpMiddle\" ><b>3.<span >       </span>Kothamanglam Mar Basil made a hat-trick</b></p><p class=\"MsoListParagraphCxSpMiddle\">It was the 5th title of champion school clinched by Mar Basil HSS, Kothamangalam and the 3rd in a row, giving a significant contribution to the victory of Ernakulam district. The school has secured 75 points with 13 gold medals.</p><p class=\"MsoListParagraphCxSpMiddle\" ><b>4.<span >       </span>Pullurampara St Joseph\'s HSS emerge as black horses of the event</b></p><p class=\"MsoListParagraphCxSpMiddle\">It was with great surprise that St Joseph\'s HSS, Pullurampara secured 2nd position in the meet with just 32 participants. The school finished only 12 points behind Mar Basil for champion school title and made crucial contributions to Kozhikode’s point table. The school got 63 points with 7 gold and 9 silver medals, while Kozhikode district secured 109 points with 8 gold and 20 silver medals.</p><p class=\"MsoListParagraphCxSpMiddle\" ><b>5.<span >       </span>15 new state records and 7 performances crossed national records</b></p><p class=\"MsoListParagraphCxSpMiddle\">It was literally showers of records at Pala, as the state school sports meet witnessed a total of 15 new state records, while seven performances crossed the national records.</p><p class=\"MsoListParagraphCxSpMiddle\" ><b>6.<span >       </span>7 individual champions were honoured</b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\">Senior(Under-19) Girls</p><p class=\"MsoListParagraphCxSpFirst\" >1.<span >       </span>Anumol Thampi, Mar Basil HSS, Kothamangalam(3 Gold)</p><p class=\"MsoListParagraphCxSpLast\" >2.<span >       </span>Aparna Roy, St Joseph’s HSS, Pallurampara(3 Gold)</p><p class=\"MsoNormal\">Senior(Under-19) Boys</p><p class=\"MsoListParagraph\" ><span >         </span>Adarsh Gopi, Mar Basil HSS, Kothamangalam(2 Gold, 1 Silver)</p><p class=\"MsoNormal\">Junior(Under-16) Girls</p><p class=\"MsoListParagraph\" ><span >         </span>Ancy Sojan, Nattika Fisheries School, Thrissur(2 Gold, 1 Silver)</p><p class=\"MsoNormal\">Junior(Under-16) Boys</p><p class=\"MsoListParagraph\" ><span >         </span>Abhishek Mathew, Mar Basil HSS, Kothamangalam(3 Gold)</p><p class=\"MsoNormal\">Sub-Junior(Under-14) Girls</p><p class=\"MsoListParagraph\" ><span >         </span>P Abhisha, Mar Basil HSS, Kothamangalam(3 Gold)</p><p class=\"MsoNormal\">Sub-Junior(Under-14) Boys</p><p class=\"MsoListParagraphCxSpFirst\">\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n</p><p class=\"MsoListParagraph\" ><span >         </span><span >Tangjam</span><span > Aletson Singh, St George HSS, Kothamangalam(3 Gold)</span></p><p class=\"MsoListParagraphCxSpMiddle\" ><b>7.<span >       </span>For the first time, criteria were changed from class to age</b></p><p class=\"MsoListParagraphCxSpMiddle\"><span >The 61st school sports meet of Kerala has made history by revamping the criteria of participants from sub-junior, junior and senior to Under-14, Under-16 and Under-19 to avoid older participants playing with the younger ones of the same class. Schools used to fail students deliberately to make them play with younger participants to secure points. </span></p><p class=\"MsoListParagraphCxSpMiddle\" ><b>8.<span >      New </span>Synthetic tracks of international standards inaugurated </b></p><p class=\"MsoListParagraphCxSpMiddle\"><span >Chief minister, Pinarayi Vijayan, inaugurated the new synthetic tracks prepared in the Pala municipal stadium along with the 61st sports meet on 20 October. It is for the first time that the sports meet is happening on synthetic tracks and is praised by experts for keeping international standards. </span></p><p class=\"MsoListParagraphCxSpMiddle\" ><b>9.<span >       Held o</span>n the banks of Meenachil River</b></p><p class=\"MsoListParagraphCxSpMiddle\"><span >After a long gap of 25 years, state school sports meet had come back to Pala, on the banks of Meenachil river, as the municipal stadium is hosting it for the third time. 2800 participants in three different categories competed in 95 sporting events here. Pala is all set to become the athletic centre of Kerala as sports meets of State CBSE, MG University and Medical University are soon coming to these tracks. </span></p><p class=\"MsoListParagraphCxSpMiddle\" ><b>10.<span >   </span>The meet happened under green protocol</b></p><p class=\"MsoListParagraphCxSpMiddle\"><span >The sports meet took place under the strict green protocol by avoiding plastic and disposable materials completely. Plastic bottles and bags were strictly banned from the stadium.</span></p><p>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n</p><p class=\"MsoListParagraphCxSpLast\"><span >The meet has also arranged yoga for participants with high stress and NADA (National Anti Doping Agency)  to prevent doping among participants.</span></p>', '1'),
(58, 1, 'daybreak', 'Students of Santa Cruz Higher Secondary School Learn Food Safety Lessons', 'Fort Kochi', 'IMG201711031405241.jpeg', 'Left to right: Sophiya T P, Headmistress, Santa Cruz HSS, Sanjitha Saleem, CEO, Amalnath N, Director and Arjun J V, Marketing & Promotions Manager, The Daybreak with students. ', '', 'In the midst of rising food safety concerns, \'The Daybreak\' conducts training sessions at Fort Kochi on safe food practices and personal hygiene.', 'Libin Chacko Kurian', '', '2017-11-04', '<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b ><span >The plot</span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span >In an attempt to create awareness regarding food poisoning and risk factors, ‘The DayBreak team’ took featured classes for students at Santa Cruz Higher Secondary School on Friday. Sanjitha Saleem, CEO, The Daybreak enlightened the students with concepts like safe food, bacterial infections, temperature level, acute illness and methods to avoid food poisoning. The session also introduced students to the opportunities if food safety management is chosen as a career option and encouraged them to be stay alert about the food items they eat every day. She is certified by many international agencies to conduct classes on food safety management.<o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span >Sophiya TP, Headmistress, Santa Cruz HSS, said \"Let us appreciate the team for organising such an informative training class for our children educating them about the safety measures to be adopted while choosing and handling food items. It is very useful for students to know about such practices to avoid illness which may cause due to carelessness and ignorance.\"<o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span >The background <o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span >The cases of food poisoning and acute illness are increasingly reported from different parts of Kerala as revealed by the office of State Food Safety Commissioner. This should be read closely with the increasing number of street food vendors and the new food practices gaining ground. In a press release published on 30 October, 2017 by the commissioner\'s office reveals that several cases of food poisoning are reported throughout the state, particularly in connection with schools, colleges, hospitals and hostels which initiated various inspection drives in the same. And within a week of inspections in more than 1300 institutions, the commissioner\'s office received a fine of Rs. 18,7500 and sent improvement notice to 858 establishments while 5 were forced to shut down. <o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span >The essence <o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span >\'The Daybreak\' took an initiative with a sense of responsibility to hit at the heart of the fire instead of covering it with a lid. The team aims to build awareness among the young minds, who also are the end consumers of tomorrow and arm them with the solutions to this issue. The training session included, what is a safe food?, How food get contaminated?, Who is bacteria and how they mould and destroy our food?, What are the different levels of risks involved with various food items?, How temperature levels affect the food materials?, Who are the most vulnerable groups for food poisoning and how to avoid it?, What are the methods to maintain personal hygiene? and what are the career opportunities available in food safety management?<o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span >The curiosity factor<o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span >The Daybreak team is determined to reach out to more students and schools to adopt a healthy life></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span >The review<o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span >It is the responsibility of every citizen to look into the matter of food hygiene as it directly affects the health of the whole nation. Let us come together to help ourselves by keeping unsafe food away and maintaining the cleanliness that we all must opt for. Let us know if you wish to conduct food safety management training in your organisation. We are happy to help you. </span></p>', '1'),
(59, 23, 'normal', 'Children\'s Day: when Nehru gifted a female elephant to Japanese children!', '', 'd5ac328ec5e845dc8baae47a118cb062.jpg', 'Happy Children\'s Day', '', 'Every year we celebrate Children\'s Day or Bal Divas on November 14, the birthday of our first prime minister, Jawaharlal Nehru, to show reverence to his love and affection to kids not only from this country but around the globe. This November, \'The Daybreak\' is rediscovering his affection to children through an unusual gift and a letter he wrote that proves his passion for writing letters.  ', 'Libin Chacko Kurian ', '', '2017-11-14', '<p class=\"MsoNormal\">Jawaharlal Nehru loved the art of writing letters especially, for\r\nchildren. He used to find time even in his busy schedule to read, write and\r\nreply to the letters that he had received every day.\r\nThe letters he wrote to his daughter, Indira, while still he was in jail during\r\nthe freedom struggle later became very\r\nfamous and are popular even today in form of a book, due to the wisdom he\r\nexpressed in those.</p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><o:p></o:p></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\">On October 2, 1949, Nehru was having his usual time in reading the\r\nletters that he received on that particular day\r\nuntil he was stumbled upon a letter written by some children in Japan. He was\r\nextremely happy to read that letter but was amused by their request to have an\r\nIndian elephant in a zoo of their country. It was not because they never had an\r\nelephant that the children want to see, but because the elephants they so loved\r\nwere killed during the second world war. <o:p></o:p></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\">A 15-year old female elephant called Indira -named after his daughter- was immediately sent to Japan as a\r\ngift to the children of that country. And so was his love to children that he\r\nwrote a letter addressing them and presenting the elephant as a gift from\r\nchildren of his country. For 34 years, Indira\r\nlived in Japan and cherished the lives of Japanese children before she died in\r\n1983.&nbsp; <o:p></o:p></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\">Just two months after this incident, Nehru had to write another letter,\r\nthis time to the children of his own country, when K Shankar Pillai, the father\r\nof political cartooning in India, started competitions for children, which was\r\naddressed through his publication. The letter which brings out Nehru\'s endless\r\nfeeling towards children and his extraordinary wisdom about the world we are\r\nliving in also talks about the Japanese\r\nincident and his vision about how children should grow up. <o:p></o:p></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\">What better to read on Children\'s Day than the words of Chacha-Ji himself, that even a letter to children,\r\nparticularly.<o:p></o:p></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><i>Dear Children,<o:p></o:p></i></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><i>I like being\r\nwith children and talking to them and, even more, playing with them. For the\r\nmoment I forget that I am terribly old and it is very long ago since I was a\r\nchild. But when I sit down to write, I cannot forget my age and the distance that\r\nseparates you from me. Old people have a habit of delivering sermons and good\r\nadvice to the young.<o:p></o:p></i></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><i>I remember that I disliked this very much long ago when I was a boy. So\r\nI suppose you do not like it very much either. Grown-ups also have a habit of\r\nappearing to be very wise, even though very few of them possess much wisdom. I\r\nhave not yet quite made up my mind whether I am wise or not. Sometimes\r\nlistening to others I feel that I must be wise and brilliant and important.\r\nThen, looking at myself, I begin to doubt this. In any event, people who are\r\nwise do not talk about their wisdom and do not behave as if they were very\r\nsuperior persons...<o:p></o:p></i></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><i>What then shall I write about? If you were with me, I would love to talk\r\nto you about this beautiful world of ours, about flowers, trees, birds,\r\nanimals, stars, mountains, glaciers and all the other beautiful things that\r\nsurround us in the world. We have all this beauty all around us and yet we, who\r\nare grown-ups, often forget about it and lose ourselves in our arguments or in\r\nour quarrels. We sit in our offices and imagine that we are doing very\r\nimportant work. <o:p></o:p></i></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><i><span>I hope you will be more sensible and open your eyes\r\nand ears to this beauty and life that surrounds you. Can you recognise the\r\nflowers by their names and the birds by their singing? How easy it is to make\r\nfriends with them and with everything in nature\r\nif you go to them affectionately and with friendship. You must have read many\r\nfairy tales and stories of long ago. But the world itself is the greatest fairy\r\ntale and story of adventure that was ever written. Only we must have eyes to\r\nsee and ears to hear and a mind that opens out to the life and beauty of the\r\nworld.</span> <o:p></o:p></i></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><i><span>Grown-ups have a strange way of putting themselves\r\nin compartments and groups. They build barriers... of religion, caste, colour,\r\nparty, nation, province, language, customs and of rich and poor. Thus they live\r\nin prisons of their own making. Fortunately, children do not know much about\r\nthese barriers, which separate. They play and work with each other and it is\r\nonly when they grow up that they begin to learn about these barriers from their\r\nelders. I hope you will take a long time in growing up...</span> <o:p></o:p></i></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><i><span>Some months ago, the children of Japan wrote to me\r\nand asked me to send them an elephant. I sent them a beautiful elephant on\r\nbehalf of the children of India... This noble animal became a symbol of India\r\nto them and a link between them and the children of India. I was very happy\r\nthat this gift of ours gave so much joy to so many children of Japan, and made\r\nthem think of our country... remember that everywhere there are children like\r\nyou going to school and work and play, and sometimes quarrelling but always\r\nmaking friends again. You can read about these countries in your books, and\r\nwhen you grow up many of you will visit them. Go there as friends and you will\r\nfind friends to greet you.</span><o:p></o:p></i></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span><i>You know we had a very great man amongst us. He was\r\ncalled Mahatma Gandhi. But we used to call him affectionately Bapuji. He was\r\nwise, but he did not show off his wisdom. He was simple and childlike in many\r\nways and he loved children... he taught us to face the world cheerfully and\r\nwith laughter.<o:p></o:p></i></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span><i>Our country is a very big country and there is a\r\ngreat deal to be done by all of us. If each one of us does his or her little\r\nbit, then all this mounts up and the country prospers and goes ahead fast.<o:p></o:p></i></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><i><span>I have tried to talk to you in this letter as if\r\nyou were sitting near me, and I have written more than I intended.</span><o:p></o:p></i></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><i><span>Jawaharlal\r\nNehru December 3, 1949</span></i></p>', '1'),
(60, 5, 'normal', '5 Reasons To Celebrate The 61st \'Formation Day\' Of Kerala This November', '', 'rsz1prp825201710274.jpg', 'Chief Minister Pinarayi Vijayan receiving the President of India, Ram Nath Kovind in Thiruvananthapuram.', '', 'Kerala Piravi or the formation day marks the birth of the state of Kerala on November 1, 1959, when the three Malayalam speaking princely states of Malabar, Cochin and Travancore were merged together. ‘The Daybreak’ is bringing you some unique developments that took place in November 2017 to celebrate and cherish about the state that crossed its 61st birthday.\r\n\r\n', 'Db Correspondent', '', '2017-11-13', '<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span><b>1. President of India hails Keralites as the ambassadors of India.</b></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>On his second visit to India after assuming office, Ram Nath Kovind, President of India praised the presence of Keralites in different countries around the world and their role in shaping values for those societies and thus becoming the excellent ambassadors for India. <o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>\"Kerala\'s fame as educated and enlighted society goes far and wide\", he said. <o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>On 27 October 2017, he was launching the Technocity project, the fourth phase of Technopark in Thiruvananthapuram, where he also hailed the advantages of Kerala in IT, tourism and healthcare sectors. <o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span><b>2. Kerala and Goa listed as the safest states for women in India<o:p></o:p></b></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>In the first-ever Gender Vulnerability Index (GVI) provided by Plan India and revealed by the women and child development ministry declared Kerala and Goa as the safest among Indian states while Bihar, Jharkhand and UP came last in the list. The Index released on November 2 is prepared against four parameters of education, health, poverty and protection against violence. <o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span><b>3. Kerala to provide 48-hour free treatment for accident victims<o:p></o:p></b></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>For the first time ever in India, the state is all set to introduce the trauma care scheme which will give free emergency care and treatment for road accident victims for the first 48 hours. The medical expenses for such cases will be paid by the state government through Road Safety fund which can be retrieved from insurance companies. This is to avoid any situation that may deny treatment to victims due to the lack of capacity to pay. The scheme also plans to pool ambulances to a centralized call centre system for the swift evacuation of victims from the site<o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span><b>4. Kerala to give free medical care and insurance to migrant workers. <o:p></o:p></b></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>In a yet another first in the country, Kerala has launched the scheme, Aavaz, to give the free medical care of Rs.15000 and an insurance cover worth Rs. 2 lakhs for migrant workers in the state. The benefits are expected to initiate from January 1, 2018. <o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span><b>5. Kerala is offering free sanitary napkins for govt schools <o:p></o:p></b></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>After a series of pilot test in govt schools, the government of Kerala has launched the scheme, \'She Pad\', to make sanitary napkins available free of cost in 300 govt for both teachers and students. The scheme that not only provides free napkins but also gives storage facilities and environment-friendly spaces, is also an attempt to encourage menstrual hygiene.<o:p></o:p></span></p><p>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n</p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span> </span></p>', '1'),
(61, 23, 'normal', 'Central government to introduce a ‘national education policy’ by year-end', '', 'rszimg0429.jpg', 'Prakash Javadekar, Union Minister for HRD, Government of India', '', 'Around five million students move around the globe for education.  India is a nation with high outflow of students and there is a need to make India the centre of education as discussed by union ministers, officials and industry leaders in New Delhi. \r\n', 'Db correspondent', '', '2017-11-10', '<p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"center\" ><br></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" ><span >A\r\nnew policy on education formulated by the central government of India is\r\nexpected to be released by December end. The new development is anticipated to\r\nliberalise the highly regulated education sector and encourage the private\r\nsector participation to acquire global\r\ncitizenship of India in education. Peculiarities\r\nof the policy were discussed by the\r\nministers and high-rank officials in the\r\ncountry at the 13th FICCI Higher\r\nEducation Summit 2017, a global conference and exhibition on education held in New Delhi on Thursday.</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" >Prakash Javadekar, Union Minister for HRD, in his video message, said that the government had come\r\nout with learning outcomes and was providing greater autonomy to the institutes\r\nto pursue research and development and innovation. The government has initiated\r\nseveral programs such as ‘Swayam’ to promote online learning and introduced\r\nquality benchmarking of institutes to make them competitive globally. </p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" >“The\r\ngovernment is in the process of finalizing the new national education policy\r\nwhich will focus on making India’s education system learner-centric instead of\r\nteacher-centric. Also, the highly regulated education sector is being\r\nliberalized and private sector participation is being encouraged for India to\r\nacquire global citizenship in education” said N. Saravana Kumar, Joint Secretary, Ministry of Human Resource Development.</p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" >Suresh Prabhu, Union Minister for Commerce &\r\nIndustry, urged\r\nthe stakeholders including industry and academic to recommend ideas to promote\r\nthe business of education globally. With the internet,\r\nnew business opportunities have emerged and India must take advantage of it.</p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" >Sudhanshu Pandey, Joint Secretary, MoCI, said “In the wake of protectionism,\r\nknowledge sharing and student exchange programmes become critical and give a new hope for tomorrow. India was among\r\none of the nations with a high outflow of\r\nstudents, the country spends more than $20 billion on students studying abroad\r\nand there was a need to make India the centre of education.”</p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" >“The\r\nstudent has been at the core of education and shall remain at its epicentre in future as well. The need is to\r\ncreate and facilitate an ecosystem where students can attain excellence in\r\ntheir chosen domains. He added that a bridge of understanding needed to be\r\ncreated between industry and academia so that both can move forward together”,\r\nhe said.</p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" >Nina Vaskunlahti, Ambassador of Finland to\r\nIndia, said\r\nthat Finland’s education system stands on four pillars of equality, efficiency,\r\nquality and internationalism. Finland’s education system is rated among the\r\nbest in the world and the country would be forthcoming in sharing its\r\nknowledge, technology and best practices in the education domain with India.</p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" >Sangeeta Godbole, Director General, Services Export\r\nPromotion Council (SEPC), said\r\nthat SEPC,  set up by the Ministry of Commerce & Industry,\r\nGovernment of India, facilitates service exporters of India which includes\r\neducation sector as well. Going forward, SEPC would bridge the gap between\r\nacademia and industry while pushing for greater autonomy in the education\r\nsector, policy reforms and internationalization of education.</p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" >The\r\ntheme for the summit was <span >‘Leapfrogging to Education 4.0: Student at the Core’</span>.\r\n67 countries, 1000 delegates of which more than 247 are foreign delegates\r\npredominantly from Africa, SAARC, Middle East, CIS, Finland, New Zealand, Malaysia,\r\nAustralia, USA participated in the summit.</p>', '1');
