(81, 1, 'normal', '51st Kerala State School Science Fair crowns Palakkad as champions', 'Kozhikode', '54654.jpg', '', '', 'Organised by the State Education Department, the meet saw students of lower primary, upper primary, high school, higher secondary and vocational higher secondary sections participating. The first phase of the meet has been conducted in the schools well before the winter season in their respective subject wise clubs including science club or maths club and went into the sub-district and district level of competitions and eventually qualifies for the state level contests. \r\n', 'Db correspondent', '', '2017-11-28', '<div class=\"gmail_default\" ><span >Claiming supremacy over the endeavours in scientific passion, Palakkad district (46586 points) clinches the champion title of state schools science fair concluded on Sunday at  Malabar Christian Ground, Kozhikode. The 51st edition of Kerala State School Sasthorolsavam has been conducted as a massive 4-day event which saw 6800 participants from different parts of the state exhibiting their experiments and findings under 217 competition items on 7 stages. Inaugurated on November 23, the event was well managed with 30 buses running to make contestants travel, 12 schools and colleges prepared to stay over and food arranged in buffet system for more than 26,000 people.</span></div><div class=\"gmail_default\" ><br></div><div class=\"gmail_default\" >While completing on Sunday, the event had already made an impact by the explosion of inventions and findings that focus on solving the problems and hurdles we face every day. Students went to create innovations from robotics to farming techniques and share a huge concern about the need to conserve the environment around us. The products with particular focus on reducing the burden on the environment and that can be used for energy conservation were the crowd puller of this event. `</div><div class=\"gmail_default\" ><br></div><div class=\"gmail_default\" ><b>From robots to agriculture</b></div><div class=\"gmail_default\" ><br></div><div class=\"gmail_default\" >Students had left their mark in opting for sustainable development as they developed biodegradable sanitary napkins and plastics, types of equipment for systemised farmings, methods to reduce electricity wastage, easier, affordable and profitable ways to do agriculture, multi-purpose wheelchair for bedridden and findings such as antibiotic qualities in drumstick seeds. </div><div class=\"gmail_default\" ><br></div><div class=\"gmail_default\" ><b>Green protocol for science</b></div><div class=\"gmail_default\" ><br></div><div class=\"gmail_default\" >Under the District Swchitwa Mission, the event maintained strong green protocol instructions with thorough inspections of a group of designated students. The team was trained to instruct the public and contestants about the use of materials that may harm the environment in which we live. Bucket made of coconut leaves were prepared for collecting wastes from around all the seven stages. Steel plates were used for serving food. Aluminium foils and other material wastes are sent for recycling after the event. </div><div class=\"gmail_default\" ><br></div><div class=\"gmail_default\" ><b>Science of special schools</b></div><div class=\"gmail_default\" ><br></div><div class=\"gmail_default\" >895 differently abled students also participated in 37 different competition items designated for them. Under the category of \'visually impaired,\' Kanjirapally Kalaketty Assisi School for the Blind came first, while Manickamangalam St. Clare Oral School for the Deaf clinch top position in the category of \'hearing impaired\'. </div><div class=\"gmail_default\" ><br></div><div class=\"gmail_default\" >Boasted as the largest student\'s science fair in Asia region, Sasthrolsavam is also a combination of five variants with separate champions for each including Science fair (Ernakulam), Mathematics fair (Kannur), Social Science fair (Trivandrum, Kasargod), work experience fair (Kollam) and IT fair (Kannur), which gives a glimpse of the talents of students in all these areas. </div><div class=\"gmail_default\" ><br></div><div class=\"gmail_default\" >Organised by the State Education Department, the meet saw students of lower primary, upper primary, high school, higher secondary and vocational higher secondary sections participating. The first phase of the meet has been conducted in the schools well before the winter season in their respective subject wise clubs including science club or maths club and went into the sub-district and district level of competitions and eventually qualifies for the state level contests. </div><div class=\"gmail_default\" ><br></div><div class=\"gmail_default\" >Ministers Kadannappally Ramachandran and TP Ramakrishnan honoured the winners with trophies, while A Pradeep Kumar Mla, A Farooq, VHSE President, M Radhakrishnan, Nambidi Narayanan, Kamaal Varadoor, Jimmy K Jose and Suresh Kumar spoke in the event. </div><div><br></div>', '1'),
(82, 1, 'normal', 'NCC Day: Chief Minister want cadets to save students from drug addiction  ', 'Trivandrum', '26nldc5.jpg', '', '', 'Every year, November 27 is observed as the National Cadet Corps Day to honour its members and celebrate the services they had. The origin of NCC can be traced back to the pre-independence era, while the official inauguration happened on 15 July 1948 with 20,000 cadets, which now became the largest uniformed youth organisation in the world with 13 lakh cadets all over the country.', 'Db correspondent', '', '2017-11-29', '<div dir=\"auto\"><span id=\"docs-internal-guid-a37d4ba9-45e0-56ce-37f9-022864804949\"><p dir=\"ltr\" ><span >On Monday, while inaugurating the National Cadet Corps (NCC) Day celebrations at Central Stadium, Trivandrum, Chief Minister Pinarayi Vijayan lauded the contributions and services that it makes towards the society. On a future note, chief minister urged NCC to organise new and more intensive campaigns to stop students from using drugs and save the youth from its addiction, while praising the efforts it has already made. </span>He emphasised the potential if NCC to cope up with challenges of modern world posed in form of internet and social media while enabling the youth to have visionary insights. He also noted with appreciation about the fact that 42% of NCC cadets in Kerala are girls and the need to push for more lady officers in the organisation.</p><br><p dir=\"ltr\" ><span >Headquartered in New Delhi, NCC is a voluntary Tri-Services(Army, Navy and Air Force) Organization, recruiting cadets from high schools, colleges and universities all over the country to engage in grooming the youth into discipline. While military training in small arms and parades are provided, the cadets have no liability for active military service once they complete their course but are given preference over normal candidates during selections based on the achievements in the corps. </span>The origin of NCC can be traced back to the pre-independence era, while the official inauguration happened on 15 July 1948 with 20,000 cadets, which now became the largest uniformed youth organisation in the world with 13 lakh cadets all over the country.</p><div><span ><br></span></div></span></div>', '1'),
(83, 23, 'normal', 'National Education Day: 7 things you must know about Maulana Abdul Kalam Azad', '', 'MaulanaAbulKalamAzad1.jpg', '', '', 'Since 2008, our nation celebrates the National Education Day on November 11, the birth anniversary of Maulana Abdul Kalam Azad, the first education minister of Independent India served from 15 August 1947 until 2 February 1958.\r\n', 'Libin Chacko Kurian', '', '2017-11-11', '<p dir=\"ltr\"><span><b>1. He was born in Mecca (now in Saudi Arabia) </b></span></p><p dir=\"ltr\"><span>Originally from Calcutta, Maulana Azad’s father was a scholar with thousands of disciples and an author of twelve books who left Delhi during the Sepoy Mutiny in 1857 and was settled in Mecca, a part of Ottoman Empire then, while his mother was the daughter of a world-renowned scholar from Madina. Azad was born on 11 November 1888 in Mecca (now in Saudi Arabia). In 1890 his family came back to India and was settled in Calcutta. </span></p><p dir=\"ltr\"><span><b>2. At the age of twelve, he was running a library, a debating society and even publishing a poetical journal</b></span></p><p dir=\"ltr\"><span>Azad had been an intelligent student with a tremendous amount of energy and enthusiasm which made him a master of several languages and had a deep understanding about mathematics, philosophy, world history and Islamic theology from a very young age. He was homeschooled by the tutors hired by his family and went to become an expert in Urdu, Hindi, Persian, Bengali, Arabic and English. </span><span>In 1900, at the age of twelve, he was running a library, had a reading room, conducted a debating society and even published a poetical journal, while also being an editor for a weekly.</span></p><p dir=\"ltr\"><span>In 1902, when he was fourteen, he started contributing to the literary magazine Makhzan and was teaching a number of students with twice of his age. By 1904, when he was just sixteen years old, he completed the whole course of his studies, nine years before his peers and even started publishing a new monthly magazine Lissan-us-S</span>idq<span>, which soon went to become very famous. </span></p><p dir=\"ltr\"><span><b>3. He became the youngest president of Indian National Congress at the age of 35 </b></span></p><p dir=\"ltr\"><span>Azad was deeply involved in the Khilafat Movement, a pan-Islamic protest started in 1919 against the British to protect Ottoman Caliphate, which exposed him to the larger frame of Indian politics and finally to meet Mahatma Gandhi himself. The meeting was proved to be a real game changer for Azad, as in 1923, the age of 35, he went to become the youngest president of Indian National Congress. He also became a dedicated supporter of Gandhian ideals such as nonviolence and civil disobedience. </span></p><p dir=\"ltr\"><span>Devoted himself to the cause of freedom movement, he published magazines and wrote articles criticizing the British rule in India its racial discriminatory activities while igniting nationalism. In 1919, he was working intensely to organise non-cooperation movements and committed himself to promote indigenous products and the self-rule of India. He was the Congress president during the rebellion of Quit India and was imprisoned for four years (1942-46) with other leaders inside Ahmednagar jail. </span></p><p dir=\"ltr\"><span><b>4. He was one of the greatest Urdu writers of 20th century </b></span></p><p dir=\"ltr\"><span>Throughout his 69 years of his eventful life, he wrote many essays, poems, published newspapers, magazines and books in several languages which makes him a literary genius of his time. He had a deep conviction to the language of Urdu and renowned as one of the greatest writers of the century. Azad had his formal education in  Persian and Arabic languages, while he learned Urdu by himself. His book, India wins freedom is an autobiographical account of his political life, while Ghubar-e-K</span>hatir<span>, which he wrote as letters during his four years of imprisonment in Ahmednagar Jail. he also wrote books like Tazkirah and Tarjumanul.</span></p><p><span><b>5. He was one of the few who stood against partition</b></span></p><p><span>In 1946, when all the leaders of Congress were released and British agreed to transfer power, a major proposal was to divide the subcontinent based on two major religions, which is how Pakistan was formed. Azad was one of the few who along with Mahatma Gandhi to their raise voice in disagreement with the proposal. While communal violence was raging across the nation, he travelled throughout the country giving speeches and talking to people about the importance of unity and communal harmony. But in contrast to his ideas, the land was divided into two different countries India and Pakistan.</span></p><p><span><b>6. He was the first education minister of independent India </b></span></p><p><span>Azad was very close to the Jawaharlal Nehru, the first prime minister of India, as a supporter and advisor while playing a crucial role in framing the policies of this new nation. As the first education minister, he spearheaded making of the new education policy building the network of schools and colleges across the country and enrollment of children and young adults to them. During his tenure in the ministry, he gave importance to educating the poor in rural areas and girls who are disadvantaged to promote adult literacy, free and compulsory universal primary education. He took initiatives to set up research institutes to solve issues that grip education in the country which includes Indian Institute of Technology, Indian Institute of Science and the University Grants Commission. </span></p><p><span><b>7. He used to spin his own cloth </b></span></p><p><span>Azad’s friendship with Gandhi was deep-rooted in his passion for religions, philosophy, ahimsa and convictions to change society through education, which also made him adopt a much simpler life></span></p><p><br></p>', '1'),
(84, 22, 'normal', 'Thailand to Gujarat: The Incredible Journey of Super Cyclone Ockhi ', '', '1200pxOckhi2017track.png', 'Map plotting the track and intensity of the storm, according to the Saffir–Simpson scale', '', 'With a top speed of 160 km/h and by travelling 4000 nautical miles in just 15 days, Cyclone Ockhi was one of the most intense tropical cyclones happened in the Arabian Sea ever. Within 24 hours after Indian Meteorological Department (IMD) issued a warning on November 29, 2017 about the tropical storm, the cyclone entered the sea near Kanyakumari to cause heavy rainfall, super strong winds, landfalls, floods and ingress of water which resulted in an estimated damage of Rs 1843 crore, 50 deaths and with many more missing.\r\n', 'Libin Chacko Kurian', '', '2017-12-12', '<p dir=\"ltr\"><span><b>1. She was born in Thailand</b></span></p><p dir=\"ltr\"><span>On November 20, 2017, in the Gulf of Thailand, a new air gap was formed when the warm moist air above the sea went up to form clouds. Within no time, air from the surrounding areas rushed into the low-pressure field to fill the gap. The new air also became hot, wet and rose above to form a new gap, beginning a continuous cycle of cloud formation. As the clouds also started circulating in the clockwise direction due to earth’s rotation, a storm was born. For next nine days, the storm travelled in the western direction into the Bay of Bengal but was too weak to cause any panic.</span></p><p dir=\"ltr\"><span><b>2. Showed her true colour in Srilanka</b></span></p><p dir=\"ltr\"><span>On November 29, when the storm reached the south-eastern coast of Sri Lanka, the Indian Meteorological Department issued a warning as the storm rapidly increased its intensity and speed due to favourable conditions. The agency had to identify the system as a depression, deep depression, then as a tropical cyclone and finally as the cyclone Ockhi, which already caused severe damages in Sri Lanka and Maldives by uprooting trees and electric poles, floods in lowlands, disturbing electricity, air traffic and road transportation.</span></p><p dir=\"ltr\"><span><b>3. She was named by Bangladesh</b></span></p><p dir=\"ltr\"><span>For the ease of communication regarding forecasts and warnings, each cyclone in Indian seas is named commonly by eight contributing nations of South Asia. This time the cyclone was named by Bangladesh as Ockhi, which means ‘Eye’ in the Bengali language. In fact, every cyclone does have an eye in its centre, a much calmer place inside the eyewall around which the most intensive storm happens. As it is India’s turn, the next cyclone will be named as ‘Sagar’.</span></p><p dir=\"ltr\"><span><b>4. The giant spiral superstorm of South India</b></span></p><p dir=\"ltr\"><span>On November 30, the very next day after the warning, Ockhi entered the sea near Kanyakumari and transformed herself into a giant spiral super cyclone with the top speed of 160 km/h to cause heavy rainfall, super strong winds, sudden ingress of water and violent waves in southern districts of Kerala and Tamil Nadu. Although she changed her route towards Lakshadweep Islands, she inflicted damages to structures and properties, at least 64 deaths and many went missing before she left the shores.</span></p><p dir=\"ltr\"><span><b>5. She turned the Indian Ocean into a battleground</b></span></p><p dir=\"ltr\"><span>It was the fishermen community that mostly bore the brunt of Ockhi fury. While the sudden ingress of water destroyed many houses, boats and structures close to shores, the violent ocean claimed the lives of fishermen who went in search of fishes and left many stranded in the sea. The combined operation of Coastal Guard, Navy and Airforce with 16 ships, five aircrafts and four choppers have rescued at least 690 stranded fishermen from the deep sea. As the rescue operations go tough during the night, the Navy used Boeing P8i aircrafts, sensors, radar, infrared cameras, magnetic detection, surveillance camera and advanced lightweight helicopters turning the Indian Ocean into nothing less than a battleground.</span></p><p dir=\"ltr\"><span><b>6. Through Lakshadweep and Mumbai, Ockhi ended her journey near Gujarat</b></span></p><p dir=\"ltr\"><span>On December 2, the cyclone went to disrupt  Lakshadweep islands with major damages. Due to the calamity, around 500 houses damaged, uprooted coconut trees and electric poles and disturbed communication lines. On December 4, Ockhi left the islands and travelled parallel to the western coast of India to cause heavy rainfall in Maharashtra and Gujarat. Though she dumped an 8000 kg waste in Mumbai coasts, the cyclone was deeply weakened and had to end her journey near the coast of Gujarat by December 6.</span></p>', '1'),
(85, 1, 'normal', 'Tarang 2k17 marks the 30th annual day celebrations of Crescent Public School', 'Thottamugham, Aluva', 'Tarang.jpg', '', '', '', 'Libin Chacko Kurian ', '', '2017-12-26', '<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span >With much\r\nglamour and grandeur, Crescent Public School celebrated ‘Tarang 2K17’, its 30<span >th\r\nannual day celebration on Friday, December 22 at the open stage inside campus featuring unique entertaining acts by\r\nstudents that kept the audience spellbound. Kerala High Court Judge Justice B\r\nKemal Pasha was the chief guest and inaugurated the formal event occupied by\r\nmany educationalists and experts in the state. Kinder garden students performed\r\na mesmerizing entertainment program on ‘Save the Earth’, while the music show\r\nperformed by the school band added spice to the celebratory night. <o:p></o:p></span></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span >Justice B\r\nKemal Pasha, said “The ability to communicate is one of the most important\r\nfunction played out by education, as the schools enable their students not only\r\nwith languages but also with the wisdom and confidence to interact with the\r\nsociety. The true foundation of a good education must start within the family\r\nas it is in my case, which gave me the culture and habit to know our neighbours\r\nand respect other people.”<o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span >“Parents\r\nshould be in a proper communication with the school and teachers to develop\r\nsuch skills in their children. It is not only for the grown-up, the children also have their right to freedom and\r\nexpression and how many of us are willing to accept that and let them\r\ncommunicate. We should allow them to travel more, as they should meet new\r\npeople and observe different circumstances to mould their character for good”,\r\nhe said.<o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span >While delivering the keynote address: P S Abdul\r\nNazer, Manager, Crescent Public School & Secretary, Crescent Educational\r\nTrust said </span><span >“With the 30th\r\nannual day of Crescent Public School, we are also celebrating the 32nd\r\nannual day of Crescent Educational Trust, which has transformed the educational\r\nlandscape of Aluva forever. The achievements awarded to the prestigious\r\neducational institution range from arts, sports, academics and science and has\r\nshown our talents even in international stages. We are blessed with a group of\r\ncommitted educationalists and teachers to make best out of every child admitted\r\nhere.” <o:p></o:p></span></p><p>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n</p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span >M M Abdul Rahiman, Chairman,\r\nCrescent Educational Trust presided over the event while Rani John, Principal,\r\nCPS, T. P. M. Ibrahim Khan, President, Kerala CBSE School Managements Association and Zakkir Hussain, President, PTC spoke in the\r\nevent. </span><span ><o:p></o:p></span></p>', '1'),
(86, 1, 'daybreak', '‘The Daybreak’ collab with ‘Mind Mojo’ to conduct Teacher\'s Training at Crescent Public School', 'Thottamugham, Aluva', 'rsz1img201801xdlojhj6104051.jpg', '', '', 'Sajitha Rasheed, the founder and chief mentor of Mind Mojo is a life skill and soft skill mentor with 21 years of experience in training and service industry. She helps corporate companies and educational institutions with skill development and personal growth of their staffs and students. She makes sure that she imparts only those lessons that she has tested, tried and found successful.', 'Libin Chacko Kurian', '', '2018-01-06', '<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>On Saturday, 52 teachers of Crescent Public School, Aluva had a training session on how to communicate with students effectively and make positive changes in their behaviour, jointly organised by ‘The Daybreak’ and ‘Mind Mojo’. Sajitha Rasheed, founder and chief mentor of Mind Mojo took the three-hour interactive session which addressed many of the daily life challenges faced by teachers in their teaching career. <o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>The training included self-reflection, understanding the process of communication, improving the verbal and non-verbal mode of communication and reframing the behaviour-correction methods. Sajitha Rasheed, chief mentor, Mind Mojo, said \"self-reflection allows us to understand ourselves and know why we respond to a particular situation in a certain way. This also enables us to nurture the desirable characteristics and replace the undesirable ones.”<o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>“The effective methods of communication can only be adopted by understanding the verbal and non-verbal systems which share a 30:70 ratio in our daily engagements. While verbal communication includes volume, rate, pitch and tone, the non-verbal system takes care of posture, gesture, eye contact and facial expressions. It is also important for teachers to learn how to convey both negative and positive feedback to their students for an effective system of schooling. Our culture often includes questions in feedback which may tend to push the listener into a defensive mode. This can be effectively replaced by statements and specificness for better communication. The effectiveness of the training can only be completed in a triangular approach to counselling with students and parents along with the teachers attending the sessions separately”, she said. <o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Rani John, Principal, Crescent Public School, said \"Crescent Public School is very keen to improve the schooling experience and the wellbeing of our students. We want our teachers to be better trained and skilled to deal with the challenges they face in classrooms and outside. It is certainly a fact to admit that children of our times are extremely unpredictable and often leave parents and teachers in confusion to deal them.\"<o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span>Sanjitha Saleem, CEO, The Daybreak, said \"The way we communicate and express ourselves on the life stage is largely influenced by the school and the teachers who taught us in the classrooms. They play a crucial role in the character development and behaviour moulding of the students they take care of. It is important not only for teachers but also for students and parents to attend such sessions to influence the life positively\". </span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\">The training session also took specific questions and feedbacks regarding teaching methods and correction techniques from teachers and addressed them accordingly. </p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span> </span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\">\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n</p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span> </span></p>', '1'),
(87, 19, '', 'boglog', 'dffs', '89.php', 'dsfs', '', 'asdsaas', 'adad', 'ada', '0000-00-00', '<p>asdsa<br></p>', '0'),
(88, 23, 'normal', 'Dr E Sreedharan wants reforms in the state’s engineering education: Governor ', 'Kalamassery', 'PRE15183.jpg', 'Governor P Sathasivam addressing the audience at CUSAT', '', 'While speaking at a function to present Chancellor’s Award at CUSAT, recently, the Kerala Governor Justice P Sadasivam recalled his meeting with Dr E Sreedharan at Raj Bhavan last week during which the latter stressed the need for necessary reforms in the state’s engineering education.', 'Libin Chacko Kurian', '', '2018-01-17', '<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-GB\">India’s ‘Metro Man’ Dr E. Sreedharan has\r\ncalled for necessary reforms in Kerala’s engineering education on account of\r\nits poor quality. This was disclosed by none other than the Kerala Governor\r\nJustice P. Sadasivam while speaking at a function organised to present\r\nChancellor’s Award at the Cochin University of Science and Technology (CUSAT)\r\nrecently.</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-GB\">Dr Sreedharan had met him at Raj Bhavan and\r\nhanded over a representation highlighting the poor quality of technical\r\neducation in Kerala, the Governor said adding “he had listed three reasons for\r\nthis kind of performance our engineering colleges had, which includes dilution\r\nin the standards of entrance exams, dilution in the grading system and the\r\nliberal examination conducted by universities. I have already forwarded a copy\r\nof the same to the chief minister\'s office and believe that engineering education\r\nin the state will improve in future\".</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-GB\">“Every University operates in a\r\ngeographical context and society expects a University\'s intervention in times\r\nof crisis or need. The recent Cyclone Ockhi was a case in point when people had\r\nquestioned the efficiency of our facilities for weather prediction. I\r\nunderstand that the Cochin University of Science and Technology also has a\r\npowerful radar facility, but very little powers to intervene in the process of\r\nprediction.  I think institutions must\r\ntake up such issues with the appropriate authority so as to enable themselves\r\nto carry out more meaningful extension activities that would connect them to\r\npeople\", the Governor further said.</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-GB\">The Governor along with Chief Minister\r\nPinarayi Vijayan presented the 3rd Chancellor\'s Award for the best university\r\nin Kerala to Cochin University of Science and Technology (CUSAT) and the first\r\naward for best Emerging Young University to Kerala Veterinary and Animal\r\nSciences University (KVASU) at CUSAT campus. The Chancellor\'s Award of Rs five\r\ncrore to the best university in Kerala was established in 2015 to nurture a\r\nspirit of healthy competition among the universities for improving the quality\r\nof Higher Education, while it was in 2017, a separate award of Rs one crore for\r\nthe best Emerging Young University in Kerala to create competition among newly\r\nestablished universities was instituted.</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-GB\">Speaking after presenting the awards, the\r\nGovernor said he is happy that the institution of these two awards has brought\r\nin some positive changes, which will continue to enrich the state’s higher\r\neducation sector in the years to come. \"This year, the selection committee\r\nhad prepared the application for the Chancellor’s Award with 47 components\r\nhaving a critical role in the quality of higher education such as academics,\r\nteaching and pedagogy methods, students profile and achievements, academic\r\ngovernance and other achievements from 12 universities across the state. The\r\ntotal score was fixed as 750. It was decided that the same yardstick of\r\nevaluation shall be followed for Emerging Young Universities also\" he\r\nsaid.</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-GB\">Speaking on the occasion, the Chief\r\nMinister said that Universities must make sure that exams, evaluations and\r\nresult announcements are conducted within the prescribed time limit. “Falling\r\nshort in the time-bound completion of academic activities may affect the\r\nefforts of students to go for higher education and destroy the reputation of\r\nthe whole state and its education sector. And this criterion should be\r\nconsidered while determining the merits and excellences of universities for\r\nsuch awards. Activities and excellence of CUSAT cannot be confined to the\r\nboundaries of the state, as it should be working towards becoming an\r\ninstitution listed among the best in the world” he said.</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-GB\">Dr J. Letha, Vice-Chancellor, CUSAT\r\nreceived the cash award along with the trophy and citation, while Anil Xavier\r\nIAS, Vice-Chancellor-in-charge accepted the award for KVASU. Local MLA V.K.\r\nEbrahim Kunju, Dr Davendra Kumar Dhodawat IAS, Secretary to the Governor and Dr\r\nJ. Letha, Vice-Chancellor, CUSAT also spoke.</span></p>', '1'),
(89, 1, 'normal', 'Ranjini who saved the dying man in Kochi honoured by Greets Public School', 'Kaloor, Kochi', 'rszp20180202194039.jpg', '', '', '', 'Libin Chacko Kurian', '', '2018-02-03', '<p class=\"MsoNormal\" align=\"center\" ><span >&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><o:p></o:p></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\">Rajini Ramachandran, the Kochi based lawyer rose to fame when she helped an accident victim to reach hospital after lying on a busy road in Kochi for more than fifteen minutes. On Saturday, Ranjini was honoured by Greets Public School during the annual day celebrations of this institution in its campus. The event had triggered an uproar in the society against people who chose not to help the dying man, while the Chief Minister and State Assembly along with many celebrities came to appreciate Ranjini. <o:p></o:p></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\">Rajini Ramachandran said that it is important to have a mindset to help people. “Life is the most beautiful gift we all have and we all have the responsibility to save and nurture it. The beauty of this gift has to be preserved and enhanced by each individual. The act of enhancement comes out of the realisation that all living creatures are equally important, precious and priceless. It is our moral responsibility and duty to act and enhance the beauty of the life of our fellow beings”, she said.<o:p></o:p></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\">C N Mohanan, chairman, Greater Cochin Development Authority, who had been the chief guest for this event said that the presence of Ranjini on this stage is giving a message to our students to be more courageous and compassionate towards the living beings around. “The moral reason behind the glory of this institution along with its inception of Greets Acadamy and its development as the Greets Public School is none other than Ms Edith Virginia Greet. The life of geet aunty, the social worker who came to Kochi and lived her entire life here in Kochi, is the biggest message that the institution gives to the society.”<o:p></o:p></p><p>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n</p><p class=\"MsoNormal\">The formal function which saw people from various sectors speaking, charity donations, awards and felicitations were continued by entertainment programs by students of Greets Public School. &nbsp;<o:p></o:p></p>', '1'),
(90, 1, 'normal', 'Kakkanad Bhavan’s Adarsha Vidyalaya Celebrated Annual Day            ', 'Kakkanad, Kochi', 'P20180111150919.jpg', '', '', '', 'Libin Chacko Kurian', '', '2018-01-12', '<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span >On Thursday, Bhavan’s Adarsha Vidyalaya, Kakkanad celebrated its 29th annual day at school premises with a formal function and variety of entertainments followed. </span><span >Dr</span><span > C N Ravishankar, Director, ICAR, CIFT, Kochi has been the chief guest and addressed the gathering about the importance of education and striving towards success. </span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span >Kochi</span><span > Bharatiya Vidya </span>Bhavan<span > Director E Ramankutty and </span><span >Thrikkakara Municipal Councillor K P Sivan spoke in the event and felicitated the educational institutions, while Principal K Suresh read the school report and PTA President P V Sajeev explained the current functioning and the coming functions of parents get together, sports activities and games organised for vacation.</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span >Dr C N Ravishankar, ICAR, CIFT, Kochi appreciated the efforts of Bhavan’s to transform the society through education and cherished in his association with the educational institution. </span>He said “Students must know that they are in one of the most beautiful stages of life and are blessed with the service and staff members of this esteemed institution. Success not the mere result of luck but it cause years of hard work and commitment. It is very crucial to enjoy the studies and at the same time have a focus on the future. We have ample amount of opportunities in front of us and it is not just engineering and medical. We must explore such fields to ignite our true passions.”</p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span >E Ramankutty, Director, Kochi</span><span > Bharatiya Vidya </span><span >Bhavan, said “Education must result in the sense of oneness among the students in spite of all differences to facilitate the meaningful growth of our nation and a secular society. Education must also ignite the sense of cleanliness both inside and outside our homes with a due respect to the parents and teachers help them.” </span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\">The event also felicitated the senior teachers of the school and distributed awards to students who had won in various activities.</p><p class=\"MsoNormal\">\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n</p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span > </span></p>', '1'),
(91, 1, 'normal', 'Don’t humiliate, students must be excited to reach schools: Rishi Raj Singh IPS', 'Perumpadappu, Kochi', 'rishiraj.png', '', '', '', 'Libin Chacko Kurian', '', '2018-01-13', '<p class=\"MsoNormal\">While speaking during the 14th Anniversary celebrations of\r\nSt. Juliana Senior Secondary School in\r\nPerumpadappu, Excise Commissioner Rishi Raj Singh IPS envisioned his ideas on\r\nchildren and shared his experiences in parenting on Friday. The event presided by Fr. Antony Jelson Velassery, Priest-in-charge of Santa Maria Church also had felicitations, prize distributions and\r\nvariety of entertainments. <o:p></o:p></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\">Rishi Raj Singh IPS, Excise Commissioner,\r\nsaid “We must allow our children to enjoy studies and to get involved outdoor activities so that they will be enthused to\r\nreach schools. We often humiliate our children for no reason at all instead we\r\nshould take time to appreciate their efforts and good intentions. All the time we are asking them to study and putting\r\nthem under tremendous pressure. Which is why many of them are fleeing away or\r\ngetting addicted to drugs. Students should feel comfortable in their home as\r\nwell as in the schools. Encourage them to involve more in sports, extracurricular\r\nactivities and to find their own passions. Parents and teachers must focus on\r\nthe complete personality development of a student and not just the academics”. <o:p></o:p></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\">\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n</p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span >Fr. Antony Jelson Velassery, </span>Priest-in-charge of Santa<span >\r\nMaria Church derived the meaning of a student from the word itself. He said “Self-discipline and simplicity are the two things education must aim to\r\ndevelop in a student. A life of devoid of luxury and strict sense of control on\r\noneself. They also must have a thirst for wisdom which will guide them throughout\r\ntheir life and will give an understanding\r\nof what is good and bad. The teachers\r\nmust help them to have a devotion and enthusiasm towards knowledge and to keep\r\ntruthfulness in life.”</span><o:p></o:p></p>', '1'),
(92, 4, 'normal', 'The Wonders from the Chair- The legend bids adieu...', '', 'i609157.jpg', '', '', '\"Remember to look up to the stars and not down at your feet. Try to make sense of what you see and wonder about what makes the universe exist. Be curious, And however difficult life may seem, there is always something you can do and succeed at. It matters that you don\'t just give up.\" \r\n-Stephen Hawkings\r\n', 'Anuja Susan Varghese', '', '2018-03-16', '<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-GB\" >One of the legendary cosmologists, scientists and physicists of our times</span><span lang=\"EN-GB\" >, </span><span lang=\"EN-GB\" >Prof. </span><span lang=\"EN-GB\" >Stephen William Hawkings is no more. </span><span lang=\"EN-GB\" >Having a lot of labels to his credit,</span><span lang=\"EN-GB\" > he was truly a man who has shown the world the real meaning of the existence of life. </span><span lang=\"EN-GB\" >Prof.</span><span lang=\"EN-GB\" > Hawkins has always taught us to dream beyond our potential, as dreams and hopes are those guide us in our life. </span><span lang=\"EN-GB\" >A great scholar who chalked out</span><span lang=\"EN-GB\" > an entirely new realm for academics. His study and discovery on the theory of \'The Black Holes of the Universe\' have brought </span><span lang=\"EN-GB\" >him great acclaim and recognition.</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-GB\" >His life is truly an inspirational one without any doubt. Diagnosed with ALS, a form of Motor Neurone Disease at the age of 21 and the life after that is quite a story. It </span><span lang=\"EN-GB\" >has been</span><span lang=\"EN-GB\" > a battle with life </span><span lang=\"EN-GB\" >ever since and he was a winner always.</span><span lang=\"EN-GB\" > Nothing stopped him from dreaming, he dreamt about doing wonders </span><span lang=\"EN-GB\" >and strived</span><span lang=\"EN-GB\" > towards it. Though he was confined to a wheelchair, his vision was far-reaching. He had made the impossible possible and has performed wonders from his wheelchair.</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-GB\" >Prof.</span><span lang=\"EN-GB\" > Hawkings has always taught the world, \"The greatest enemy of knowledge is not ignorance, it is the illusion of knowledge\". \"I\'m fairly human and normal. At least I try to be\", is what his response to all those who </span><span lang=\"EN-GB\" >viewed</span><span lang=\"EN-GB\" > him with questioning eyes. </span><span lang=\"EN-GB\" >As students, your </span><span lang=\"EN-GB\" >physics syllabus will always have a space reserved for him and so will our hearts because this man is a legend who has taught the world to smile despite all odds.    </span></p>', '1'),
(95, 5, 'normal', 'Know more about Jackfruit, just crowned as Kerala’s official fruit', '', 'rszjackfruitflesh.jpg', '', '', 'Jackfruit is already revered around the world as the King of fruits and is honoured by the Bangladesh government as their National fruit due to the contributions it had to the culinary traditions of the country. In Tamil Nadu, Jackfruit is declared as the state fruit and is also one of the auspicious fruits along with Mango and Banana.\r\n\r\n', 'Db correspondent', '', '2018-03-27', '<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-GB\" >Bright days are ahead for the good old jackfruit with the Government of Kerala declaring it as the state’s official fruit recently</span><span lang=\"EN-GB\" >. This decision is certain to help increase the production and open up immense opportunities for this exotic fruit. The annual production of Jackfruits in the state is valued at around Rs 60 crore. Minister for Agriculture V S Sunil Kumar, while making the announcement told the state assembly that value-added products from jackfruits can fetch an additional revenue of  Rs 30,000 crore. Let’s us have look at some of the interesting facts about this nutritious fruit variety</span></p><ul >\r\n <li class=\"MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-GB\">The name “Jackfruit” originated from the Malayalam language<o:p></o:p></span></li>\r\n</ul><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-GB\">The English word, “Jack” in jackfruit came from the Portuguese word “Jaca” which in turn was derived from the Malayalam term for the same fruit “Chakka”. Hendrick Van Rheede, the Dutch naturalist and author of ‘Hortus Malabaricus’ was the first to record this name in 1678 and then translated into different languages. The commonly used name ‘Jackfruit’ was first used by British Naturalist Garcia De Orta in 1563.</span></p><ul >\r\n <li class=\"MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-GB\">Jackfruit cultivation is 6000 years old<o:p></o:p></span></li>\r\n</ul><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-GB\">Jackfruit is native to South West India and was cultivated here even around 6000 years back, according to the archaeological evidence available. It has played a crucial role in the agricultural history of Indian Subcontinent, due to the nutritive quality of the fruit and minimal effort required to cultivate it.</span></p><ul >\r\n <li class=\"MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-GB\">National fruit of Bangladesh and state fruit of Tamil Nadu<o:p></o:p></span></li>\r\n</ul><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-GB\">Jackfruit is already revered around the world as the King of fruits and is honoured by the Bangladesh government as their National fruit due to the contributions it had to the culinary traditions of the country. In Tamil Nadu, Jackfruit is declared as the state fruit and is also one of the auspicious fruits along with Mango and Banana.</span></p><ul >\r\n <li class=\"MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-GB\">Jackfruit is a collection of flowers with fleshy petals<o:p></o:p></span></li>\r\n</ul><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-GB\">More than a fruit, Jackfruit is considered as a cluster of flowers with thick flesh which is edible. Hundreds of such bulbs are closely arranged inside the thorny skin so that to look like a fruit.</span></p><ul >\r\n <li class=\"MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-GB\">Indonesia have palaces built by Jackwood<o:p></o:p></span></li>\r\n</ul><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-GB\">The wood of Jackfruit tree is in high demand due to the termite and fungus-resistant properties. It is used in the manufacturing of furniture, musical instruments like Veena or Mrithangam and even in house construction. Bali, the Indonesian Island, has palaces made of Jackwood. It is also used to make priest’s seat in Hindu ceremonies, Buddhist statues and is even worshipped in many parts of India.</span></p><ul >\r\n <li class=\"MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-GB\">Jackfruit is a nutritious food with medicinal properties<o:p></o:p></span></li>\r\n</ul><p>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n</p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-GB\">While the root of a Jackfruit tree can provide medicine for treating fever, asthma and diarrhoea, it is also widely accepted as a very nutritious food and is believed to be a solution to food scarcity in many parts of the world. The unripe Jackfruit is often treated and prepared as a vegetable. <o:p></o:p></span></p>', '1'),
(96, 5, 'normal', 'Nick Ut, the world-renowned photographer, in town. ', 'Kochi', 'PRD7823.JPG', '', '', 'The famous photojournalist Nick Ut visited Kochi on March 15 and interacted with journalists and photographers', 'Db Correspondent', '', '2018-03-22', '<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-GB\">The photograph of a wounded girl fleeing naked to escape from a Napalm bomb blast during the infamous Vietnam war of the 70s was one of the most acclaimed war photographs that shook the world consciousness.</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-GB\">The Vietnamese-American photojournalist Nick Ut who shot into fame with this single photograph was recently in Kerala, the land of endless charms, bringing back memories of that bygone dark era of the Vietnam War, which culminated in the unconditional withdrawal of the mighty US forces in the face of the die-hard resistance of the Viet Congs.</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-GB\">In 1972, Vietnam was burning under the ruthless air and land attacks</span><span lang=\"EN-GB\">. It was on June 8, 1972, photojournalist Nick Ut who was in the town of Trang Bang in South Vietnam, covering War for Associated Press (AP) </span><span lang=\"EN-GB\">captured the eye-opening visual of a local girl fleeing to escape from the fumes of a Napalm bomb blast with other children following her. This single picture portrayed the horror and ruthlessness of war in the most shocking manner than a thousand words could.</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-GB\">Napalm is a highly flammable sticky jelly that is used in these bombs. And the girl Kim Phuc (the nude girl in the picture) was fully covered with this substance and </span><span lang=\"EN-GB\">hence </span><span lang=\"EN-GB\">the picture got its name, the \'Napalm Girl\'. People were struggling to run away from the affected areas and as Nick spotted the girl and took her to the hospital for proper treatment. With that single photograph, Nick Ut gained world recognition and he was honoured with the famous Pulitzer Prize in 1973 for this photograph. </span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-GB\">He was in Kerala to attend the second edition of the two-day ‘International Press Photography Festival’ jointly organised by Kerala Media Academy and the Government of Kerala in Thiruvananthapuram. He was felicitated by Chief Minister Pinarayi Vijayan, with the first ‘World Photographer Prize’ instituted by the Kerala Media Academy at the festival. His journey started from Thiruvananthapuram </span><span lang=\"EN-GB\">covered </span><span lang=\"EN-GB\">Kollam, Alappuzha, Kottayam and Kochi where he was welcomed by renowned poets and artists.</span></p><p></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-GB\">Actor Mammootty </span><span lang=\"EN-GB\">was among those who received him in Kochi</span><span lang=\"EN-GB\"> where he visited the Archives Department and </span><span lang=\"EN-GB\">the historic township</span><span lang=\"EN-GB\"> of Fort Kochi.  At Palakkad, he surprised actor Mohanlal by visiting him on the sets of his upcoming movie \'Odiyan\'. Nick took leave of the state with a promise of returning with the \'Napalm Girl\' next time.</span></p>', '1'),
(97, 5, 'normal', 'In Mattancherry, yet another green lung for Kochi', 'Mattancherry, Kochi', 'PRD8599.JPG', '', '', '', 'Db correspondent', '', '2018-03-22', '<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span >Waking up in the morning, rushing to schools or workplace and going back home dead tired! In our busy daily routine, we do require more public spaces to strengthen our social interactions and friendships. The Minister of Local Administration, K.T Jaleel inaugurated the newly renovated Karippalam Ground in Mattancherry on Saturday, highlighting the importance of this.</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-GB\" >“Public spaces assume more importance today especially as our social interactions are now growingly getting confined to</span><span lang=\"EN-GB\"> smartphones and social media” the Minister pointed out on the occasion.</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-GB\">Well! Social media like Facebook, Whatsapp, Twitter are those social platforms through which one expresses his/her opinions and thoughts about anything and everything under the sun. Of course, it helps our interactions, but sadly these days we are increasingly limiting ourselves to these virtual social platforms.</span></p><p>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n</p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-GB\">In Kochi, it is heartening that we still do have a few green lungs like Marine Drive, Subhash Park, Fort Kochi beach and the new Karippalam ground is a welcome addition to this list. MLAS, K. J Maxi and John Fernandez were also present on the occasion.<o:p></o:p></span></p>', '1');
