(98, 4, 'normal', 'Dawn  of the Digital Era at a mouse click', 'Le Meridien, Kochi', 'IMG07831.jpg', '', '', ' ‘#FUTURE’ global summit just concluded in the emerging metropolis of Kochi unfolded the prospects of an innovative digital future of great expectations\r\n\r\n\r\n', 'Anuja Susan Varghese', '', '2018-03-24', '<p><span >Kochi: </span><span ><span >“We believe that knowledge is the future and that, the future is knowledge”, said the Chief Minister, Pinarayi Vijayan inaugurating ‘#Future’, the global digital summit organised by the Kerala </span><span >gov</span></span><span >﻿</span><span ><span >ernment</span><span > and the industrial bodies in Kochi on March 22. More importantly</span></span><span >, </span><span >it is the first global futuristic</span><span > </span><span >summit organised under the auspices of the state</span><span > </span><span ><span >government</span>.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-GB\" ><span >The </span><span >event</span><span > with the theme ‘Towards a Digital Future’ addressed six topics covering health, education, banking, retail, travel and tourism and information technology. ‘In the last 30 years much has changed and in every two years, a lot of innovations are happening in the digital world, said S. D Shibulal, Chairman, High Power IT of the state government. The social media like Facebook, Instagram, Whatsapp, Uber, Dropbox have brought technological waves all across the world.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span lang=\"EN-GB\" >Emerging Kerala</span></b><span lang=\"EN-GB\" ><o:p></o:p></span></p><span > </span><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-GB\" ><span >Kerala is fast</span><span > </span><span >transforming into an information technology and </span><span >knowledge-based</span><span > society. The importance must be given to education on both primary and secondary levels to equip them for the emerging economy. In a pioneering initiative, one thousand public hotspots with free Wi-Fi facility are being provided by the state government said the Chief Minister adding ‘Kerala is the first state to declare internet as a right of the citizens. The Chief Minister also inaugurated M Keralam app, which is meant to digitalising the online government transactions making it easier and user-friendly.</span></span></p><span > </span><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span lang=\"EN-GB\" ><span >The relevance of Education</span><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><span > </span><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-GB\" ><span >“Students are simply mugging up everything without even knowing its implications”, said Byju Raveendran, founder and CEO of BYJU’S app., an innovative learning app. He pointed out that 80% of learning takes place outside the classrooms adding: “Today most of the classes are not interactive in our schools, organic way of teaching has to be adopted to make the students fall in love with learning”.</span><o:p></o:p></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-GB\"> </span></p>', '1'),
(109, 3, 'normal', 'India’s Triumph at Commonwealth Games 2018', '', 'Commonwealth.jpg', 'The Indian saga at Gold Coast', '', ' the Indian feat at latest Commonwealth games will definitely be sung for years ahead by the sports world. Watch out for the next games in Birmingham, the venue for the 2022 edition!', 'Db Correspondent', '', '2018-04-19', '<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-GB\" >Indian teams have done pride to the nation at the just concluded Commonwealth Games in Gold Coast when</span><span lang=\"EN-GB\" > the action, fun and excitement have come to an end at the grand finale of the games at Carrara Stadium. The games that take place every four years manifest the friendship between nations and share the common values for the good of humanity and peace of the world.</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-GB\">The triumph of Saina Nehwal marked the grand finale of India’s remarkable performance at the 2018 Commonwealth Games when she became the first Indian to win two singles Gold by defeating the celebrated Olympian P. V Sindhu. Overall, India clinched the third position by gaining 66 medals with 26 gold, 20 silver and 20 bronze. The first and the second position went to Australia (80) and England (45) respectively.</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-GB\" >However,</span><span lang=\"EN-GB\" > </span><span lang=\"EN-GB\">India’s best performance was registered way back in 2010 edition of the games in New Delhi where we bagged 101 medals comprising 38 gold, followed by 69 medals in Manchester (2002).</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-GB\" >Stand out achievements<o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-GB\">Amongst the medals won there were a lot of standouts including that of Manika Batra, who made history by becoming the first Indian woman to win an individual table tennis event at the Games. In the women’s table tennis event, the Indian team won its first ever Commonwealth Gold. Neeraj Chopra from Haryana became the first Indian Javelin thrower to claim a Gold medal at Games. The Gold medal won by India’s mixed badminton team is the country’s first in that category at the Games.</span></p><p>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n</p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-GB\">Altogether the Indian feat at latest Commonwealth games will definitely be sung for years ahead by the sports world. Watch out for the next games in Birmingham, the venue for the 2022 edition!<o:p></o:p></span></p>', '1'),
(111, 1, 'daybreak', '‘The Daybreak’, Kerala’s Pioneer Students Fortnightly Launched', 'Willingdon Island, Kochi', 'daybreak1.jpg', '', '', '', 'Libin Chacko Kurian', '', '2018-07-09', '<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-GB\">Posh Publications, Kerala has launched ‘The Daybreak’, t</span><span lang=\"EN-GB\">he state’s first-ever student’s fortnightly newspaper in a well-attended function organised at the campus of Kendriya Vidayala, Port Trust, Kochi. S M Saleem, Deputy Commissioner, </span><span lang=\"EN-GB\">Kendriya Vidayala </span><span lang=\"EN-GB\">released the first copy of the fortnightly at the function in the presence of </span><span lang=\"EN-GB\">a cheerful young audience on July 04, 2018.</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-GB\">‘The Daybreak’ which targets the student\'s community </span><span lang=\"EN-GB\">aims to bridge academics with the daily life </span><span lang=\"EN-GB\">and reinstate the original vision and mission of education</span><span lang=\"EN-GB\">. The 16-page publication </span><span lang=\"EN-GB\">will have </span><span lang=\"EN-GB\">20 issues in a year with a unique blend of news, features, columns and entertainment to help students </span><span lang=\"EN-GB\">scale new heights in academics </span><span lang=\"EN-GB\">and lead a meaningful life.</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-GB\">The function was followed by \'I Read\', a training session on reading, led by R Narayanan, Director, Teampace Sales Academy. Dr Ajeesh Ramachandran, Consultant Psychiatrist of Government Mental Health Centre, Thrissur </span><span lang=\"EN-GB\">made a special presentation</span><span lang=\"EN-GB\"> to students regarding the psychological benefits of quality reading.</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-GB\">Shemi Saleem, managing director, Posh Advertisers, Sanjitha Saleem, CEO and managing editor, of ‘The Daybreak’ and </span><span lang=\"EN-GB\">PM</span><span lang=\"EN-GB\"> Prabhakaran</span><span lang=\"EN-GB\">, Kendriya Vidayala Port Trust, Kochi were also present on the occasion.</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-GB\"><span >Reading influences character<o:p></o:p></span></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-GB\">Speaking on the occasion, S M Saleem said, \"Reading helps us to travel to new places every time we read a new book and experience a culture unknown to us before. My own personal reading </span><span lang=\"EN-GB\">habit started </span><span lang=\"EN-GB\">when my father brought </span><span lang=\"EN-GB\">home the ‘Illustrated Weekly of India’</span><span lang=\"EN-GB\"> from his office. Over the years my reading got evolved from comics to mystery novels and from thrillers to serious research into biology, a subject that is close to my heart and became my career.\"</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-GB\">\"Reading has a direct influence on the <a name=\"__DdeLink__1037_1853816025\">character</a> and behaviour of an individual which may reflect in the societal level. A society that reads will be more peaceful in nature. I hope \'The Daybreak\' can induce reading habit among school children and develop reading as a culture. I appreciate Sanjitha Saleem and her team for their efforts to reach children and influence them for good\", </span><span lang=\"EN-GB\">he added.</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span ><span lang=\"EN-GB\">Quality of reading matters</span><span lang=\"EN-GB\"><o:p></o:p></span></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-GB\">Dr Ajeesh Ramachandran </span><span lang=\"EN-GB\">in his address said</span><span lang=\"EN-GB\">, \"reading also comes with tremendous psychological effects and on that basis, the process can be divided into content reading and pleasure reading. While content reading helps us to find information and acquire knowledge, pleasure reading is reading what you love reading. As these processes are carried out by two different sections of the brain, left and right; combining both will have a positive psychological effect on a human being. So it\'s great if you love what </span><span lang=\"EN-GB\">you have </span><span lang=\"EN-GB\">to read.\"</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-GB\">\"We can observe the negative effects of disconnection in children with learning disabilities. And a simple change in learning methods with more engaging modes can solve the problems. It is also important to find a balance in everything we do including reading, as too much of it can cause addiction. Quality of reading is what matters and movements like \'The Daybreak\' will make our children more wise and sensitive\" he added.</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-GB\">Sanjitha Saleem </span><span lang=\"EN-GB\">in her speech</span><span lang=\"EN-GB\"> said \"The Daybreak is a dream venture of Posh Publications which aims to serve the next generation student population. </span><span lang=\"EN-GB\">The fortnightly is conceived </span><span lang=\"EN-GB\">as a bridge between the academics and the life outside. The whole </span><span lang=\"EN-GB\">thrust is on</span><span lang=\"EN-GB\"> the real purpose of education i.e. To live well and die well.\"</span></p>', '1'),
(112, 1, 'normal', 'Safety cover for school kids with the new academic year', 'Ernakulam', 'Schoolbuskerala1.JPG', '', '', '', 'Db correspondent', '', '2018-06-06', '<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-GB\" >On the commencement of the new academic year, </span><span lang=\"EN-GB\" >Kochi city police have issued a notification to the school management and parents to ensure the safety of children both inside the school and while travelling. Nodal officers are assigned to each school in the city along with two other officers, who are designated to ensure the safety of children while boarding and de-boarding the bus during the busy school hours. The police have also warned parents against sending their children in over-crowded buses to schools.</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-GB\"> </span>“Police officers are assigned at all school gates to help children cross the road, board the bus safely, regulate vehicle speed at school premises and to look into misbehaving against children. People violating the order will be punished,” said MP Dinesh IPS, City Police Commissioner. School authorities have been strictly warned of running a background check of the person commuting the children to avoid misbehaviour with children and made it mandatory that each member of the bus should possess a police clearance certificate. In case of violation, parents and the students are free to lodge a complaint with the nearest police station.</p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-GB\"> </span>Also, a private bus running in the city should allow students to board and de-board at the specific stops designated. Timely inspection of the school buses, school-owned or private, will be conducted from day one. Those running on LPG gas are expected to meet all the necessary safety measures for transporting school students. Over-speeding vehicles and drunken drivers will face stern action from the force.</p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-GB\"> </span>Further, strict orders have been given to punish those found selling tobacco products within a 100-metre radius of all educational institutions. Additionally, school management has been ordered to set up a complaint box and maintain a visitor’s register. Police have also advised the authorities to install CCTV cameras in the school premises. Strict action will be taken against unauthorised parking in front of schools, while also acting against illegally installed advertisement boards. For any queries, students can directly contact the SP on 9497996979. The notification has also asked parents to advise their children, to obey the instructions of the officer stationed in front of the school.</p><p class=\"MsoNormal\">In 2017, soon after re-opening, 92 school drivers were booked for drunk driving and the police force are expected to remain extra vigil to avoid repetition of the same.</p><p>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n</p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-GB\"> </span></p>', '1'),
(113, 22, 'normal', 'In Ernakulam, 313 ponds get a fresh lease of life', 'Ernakulam', 'Webp.netcompressimage2.jpg', '', '', '', 'Db correspondent', '', '2018-06-07', '<p class=\"MsoNormal\">Under the celebrated ‘Harithakerlam’ Project, Ernakulam district sets an example in terms of protecting and preserving water sources by cleaning and renovating 313 public ponds across 46 panchayats and 3 municipalities under its jurisdiction till May 2018. Led by District Collector, Muhammed Y Safirulla, the project that enjoyed public support in huge numbers were completed in three phases since 2016. Under the banner of ‘Ente Kullam Ernakulam’ 55 public ponds in 2016,</p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-GB\">Funds for the renovation of ponds comes from Cochin Shipyard’s public funding share and minor irrigation department’s ‘Harithakeralam’ project. <o:p></o:p></span></p><p>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n</p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-GB\"> </span></p>', '1'),
(114, 5, 'normal', 'Half marathon on July 15 to fight drug abuse', 'Kochi, Ernakulam', '111.JPG', '', '', '', 'Db correspondent', '', '2018-06-08', '<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span >With an aim to make the public aware of the ill-effects of drug use, Kerala State Mission for Drug De-addiction, ‘Vimukthi’ has decided to organise a half marathon in Kochi on July 15, 2018, few days after the International Day Against Drug Abuse and Illicit Trafficking </span><span >falling on </span><span >June 26.  P T Thomas MLA and excise commissioner Rishiraj Singh released the logo of the event on June 2, 2018, at Kakkanad.</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-GB\"> </span><span >Starting from Maharaja’s college, the half marathon with over 1000 participants divided into different groups based on age and sex, will end at Fort Kochi. The half-marathon named “Cochin Monsoon Marathon Run Against Drugs” will flag off at 6 am on July 15th. Before the event, there will be awareness programmes at different educational institutions throughout the state where the public can also attend.</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span >The half marathon also expects involvement of high schools, higher secondary schools, colleges, NSS, NCC, YMCA, resident associations, members of governmental, non-governmental organisations and religious organisations</span><span > in the city</span><span >.</span></p><p>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n</p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-GB\"> </span></p>', '1'),
(115, 1, 'normal', 'A Green Take-Off of the New Academic Year', 'Maneed near Pirvaom', 'PravesanolsavamDistLevelManeed31.jpg', '', '', '', 'Db correspondent', '', '2018-06-02', '<p class=\"MsoNormal\">Commencement of the new academic year this in Ernakulam district was noted for its focus on green living. The Ernakulam Revenue District-level ‘Praveshanolsavam’ (School opening ceremony) was inaugurated by Anoop Jacob MLA on June 01, 2018 at Government LP School Maneed near Pirvaom. All the festive preparations organised by the general education department and the ‘Sarva Shiksha Abhiyan’ in the district were strictly adhering to the green protocol. The students of Vennala Government LP School in the district took a pledge saying ‘no’ to plastics and the organisers decorated the venue with palm leaves, paper flowers. </p>', '1'),
(116, 23, 'normal', 'NCERT for a Complete Syllabus Revamp ', 'New Delhi', 'rsz10yearsolddipaand12yearsoldlabonistudyinclass2atuniquechildlearningcentermirmurdhakabangladesh.jpg', '', '', 'It’s good news that NCERT is planning to revise the existing syllabus with a view to adding more value to the content. ', 'Db Correspondent', '', '2018-06-07', '<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-GB\" >The</span><span lang=\"EN-GB\" > National Council of Educational Research and Training (NCERT) is on a mission to drastically update their existing syllabus for the new academic year focussing more on life skills, sports and values. According to the Union Ministry of Human Resource Development (HRD) in the first week of June, </span><span lang=\"EN-GB\" >the new syllabus will have its size reduced to half. There will be more on scientific achievements of ancient India with toned down political commentaries.</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-GB\">Prakash Javadekar, Minister of HRD, said “Education is not just memorising and putting it down on the answer sheet. Education is comprehensive. To put to use one’s cognitive and analytical abilities—that is true education. The NCERT syllabus is so cramped. Hence we have decided to reduce the syllabus by half”.</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-GB\" >Value Addition<o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-GB\">The NCERT has so far made 1,334 changes, which include additions, corrections and data update, in its 182 textbooks. Of these, 573 changes have been made to Science books, followed by 316 changes in Social Science and 163 changes in Sanskrit textbooks. NCERT is also is considering a proposal named </span><span lang=\"EN-GB\" >‘Energised Textbooks’</span><span lang=\"EN-GB\"> with digital links to multimedia material where concepts will be explained through diagrams, charts and data.<o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-GB\" >The academic body had earlier dropped several “offensive” cartoons from its Political Science textbooks and has gone a step further and toned down the commentary on Indian politics and politicians in its Class 10 </span><span lang=\"EN-GB\" >text</span><span lang=\"EN-GB\" >book</span><span lang=\"EN-GB\" >. Looking forward to a major change, the ministry has already received 37,000 suggestions on how classes, subjects and lessons can be improved to teach students about life skills, value education, and physical education.</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-GB\" >NCERT will also be adding </span><span lang=\"EN-GB\" >contents on</span><span lang=\"EN-GB\" > the glorious ancient past of India ranging from Yoga and Upanishads to scientific achievements and topics like Ayurveda.</span></p><p>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n</p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-GB\"> </span></p>', '1'),
(117, 4, 'normal', 'Chennai Developer Bags the Apple Design Award', '', 'appledesignaward.jpg', '', '', '', 'Db correspondent', '', '2018-06-12', '<p class=\"MsoNormal\">Little did Raja Vijayaram from Chennai know while packing his bag to attend the Apple Worldwide Developers Conference (WWDC) that he would be awarded the prestigious Apple awards for his elegantly designed calculator app, Calzy 3. Raja was flown to San Jose, USA to receive the Apple Design Award, on June 04, 2018, the first day of the Developer’s Annual Conference of Apple.Inc without being told he was the winner!</p><p class=\"MsoNormal\">The Calzy 3 app is as simple as a calculator can be. You can view each and every step you are following to get the answer. There is a scientific calculator too hidden inside which can be pulled up with a 3D touch. The interesting part of Raja’s Calzy is that there is a bookmark option for any earlier calculations. The app is completely customisable and you can protect all your tax amounts away with a password.</p><p class=\"MsoNormal\">Calzy 3 was first launched by the one army man in 2014. The latest one is the revamped version of the earlier. The app is only available for iOS priced at Rs. 159. Being a mechanical engineer from Theni, Raja moved into VFX some years ago and worked for a few movies in Chennai. He bought his first iPhone to use and learn about the apps, later he began coding the apps. Though flooded with requests for more features, Raja wants to keep his calculations with Calzy as simple as possible.&nbsp;</p><p class=\"MsoNormal\">Apple Design Awards, also known as the ADA is a special event hosted by Apple Inc. at its annual Worldwide Developers Conference to recognize the best and most innovative Macintosh and iOS software and hardware produced by independent developers. This year 10 apps were awarded the Apple Design Award.&nbsp;</p><p class=\"MsoNormal\">They are the Finnish Bandimal from Yatatoy, a composing app for children which is sensational, Agenda, the note-taking app for Mac and iOS that focuses on dates, iTranslate Converse, a speedy and efficient translator designed for conversations, Alto’s Odyssey, an app teaching gamers how to play, Calzy 3, Frost, puzzle game, Triton Sponge, an app used in medical operating rooms to measure blood loss collected by surgical sponges and suction canisters, Oddmar, another game.</p><p>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n</p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-GB\">&nbsp;</span></p>', '1'),
(118, 1, 'normal', 'BIKOS: A Project to Ensure Cyber Safety in Campus', 'Ernakulam', 'SecurityInternetSocialMediaPoliceChildren1727458.jpg', '', '', '', 'Megha Thomas', '', '2018-06-26', '<p class=\"MsoNormal\">In a commendable initiative aimed at providing a safe cyber world for the students in the campus, several CBSE schools in Ernakulam district have joined to adopt \'Better Internet for Kids Online Security\' (Bikos), a project launched by Cochin Refinery School.</p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-GB\" >Bikos is a project focusing on training and sensitizing school children, with the ultimate </span><span lang=\"EN-GB\" >objective of creating a</span><span lang=\"EN-GB\" > </span><span lang=\"EN-GB\" >safe cyber policy.</span><span lang=\"EN-GB\" > CBSE has mandated a cyber policy in every school to ensure safe browsing world for the children.</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-GB\" >“The project works under various phases. In the first phase, there </span><span lang=\"EN-GB\" >will be</span><span lang=\"EN-GB\" > a brainstorming session with the principals where the problems of cybersecurity at schools are</span><span lang=\"EN-GB\" > discussed</span><span lang=\"EN-GB\" >. The second phase </span><span lang=\"EN-GB\" >involves handing over</span><span lang=\"EN-GB\" > the output of the brainstorming session to school councillors, where solutions </span><span lang=\"EN-GB\" >are found to the</span><span lang=\"EN-GB\" > problems. In the next phase, we</span><span lang=\"EN-GB\" > get </span><span lang=\"EN-GB\" >experts from Kerala Police and cyber lawyers to help us out,” Premalatha Shaji, coordinator of BIKOS project told </span><span lang=\"EN-GB\" >The Daybreak.</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-GB\" >Bikos was initially launched last year, </span><span lang=\"EN-GB\" >organising training sessions and awareness campaigns for both students and parents.</span><span lang=\"EN-GB\" > This year, the Kerala Police, cyber experts and lawyers</span><span lang=\"EN-GB\" > are being involved in these programmes</span><span lang=\"EN-GB\" >. The training programmes are conducted in association with </span><span lang=\"EN-GB\" >Amrita Institute of Medical Sciences.</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-GB\" >As part </span><span lang=\"EN-GB\" >of the project, </span><span lang=\"EN-GB\" >the schools have approached Kerala High Court lawyer, Prem Kamath to formulate</span><span lang=\"EN-GB\" > a campus-specific </span><span lang=\"EN-GB\" >cyber policy that would go hand in hand with the internet laws of the country.</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-GB\" >Talking to ‘</span><span lang=\"EN-GB\" >The Daybreak’,</span><span lang=\"EN-GB\" > Kamath said, “The policy will be formulated based on the guidelines given by CBSE which requires that schools affiliated to them </span><span lang=\"EN-GB\" >need</span><span lang=\"EN-GB\" > to have mandatory cyber policies for themselves to protect children in the online environment and also to look into the usage of electronic gadgets at school.”</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-GB\" >With 30 CBSE schools working under the project, Bikos also </span><span lang=\"EN-GB\" >organises</span><span lang=\"EN-GB\" > courses to students </span><span lang=\"EN-GB\" >as well as </span><span lang=\"EN-GB\" >awareness programmes and projects for teachers</span></p>', '1'),
(119, 1, 'normal', 'Kerala Kalolsavam sans pomp to be held in Alappuzha', 'undefined', 'rszrszgroupdancehss92.jpg', '', '', 'undefined', 'Db correspondent', '', '2018-09-19', '<p class=\"MsoNormal\">Despite the woes of Kerala in the backdrop of the recent natural calamity, the government has decided to conduct the annual school youth festival without any fanfare or frills in December at Alappuzha.</p><p class=\"MsoNormal\">The decision taken at the special initiative of Chief Minister, Pinarayi Vijayan is to see that the students do not miss grace marks that could be earned on account of their performance at Kalolsavam.</p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-GB\" >It may be noted that the government had cancelled most of the regular festivities</span><span lang=\"EN-GB\" > this year including the youth festival and International Film Festival in view of the widespread damage caused by the recent floods that devastated entire Kerala. The government has also decided to donate all the funds allotted for these festivals to be transferred to the Chief Minister’s relief fund and imposed a year-long ban on any state-sponsored programmes or celebrations.</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-GB\" >Meanwhile,</span><span lang=\"EN-GB\" > the sports fest will be held in Thiruvananthapuram in October while the science fair will be held in Kannur in December. The special school festival will be held in October at Kollam.</span></p>', '0'),
(120, 1, 'normal', 'Kerala Kalolsavam sans pomp to be held in Alappuzha', '', 'rszrszgroupdancehss92.jpg', '', '', '', 'Db correspondent', '', '2018-09-19', '<p class=\"MsoNormal\">Despite the woes of Kerala in the backdrop of the recent natural calamity, the government has decided to conduct the annual school youth festival without any fanfare or frills in December at Alappuzha. The decision taken at the special initiative of Chief Minister, Pinarayi Vijayan is to see that the students do not miss grace marks that could be earned on account of their performance at Kalolsavam.</p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-GB\" >It may be noted that the government had cancelled most of the regular festivities</span><span lang=\"EN-GB\" > this year including the youth festival and International Film Festival in view of the widespread damage caused by the recent floods that devastated entire Kerala. The government has also decided to donate all the funds allotted for these festivals to be transferred to the Chief Minister’s relief fund and imposed a year-long ban on any state-sponsored programmes or celebrations.</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-GB\" >Meanwhile,</span><span lang=\"EN-GB\" > the sports fest will be held in Thiruvananthapuram in October while the science fair will be held in Kannur in December. The special school festival will be held in October at Kollam.</span></p>', '1'),
(121, 23, 'normal', 'Centre’s flagship schemes enter NCERT textbooks', '', 'book168824960720.jpg', '', '', '', 'Db correspondent', '', '2018-06-05', '<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-GB\" >The</span><span lang=\"EN-GB\" > Union government’s innovative projects like Namami Gange, Digital India, Beti Bachao Beti Padhao and Pradhan Mantri Kaushal Vikas Yojana have made their entry into the new NCERT textbooks for students of Class 6 to 10.</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\">There is a whole chapter dedicated to demonetisation titled ‘Money and Credit’. Swachh Bharat appears in a chapter titled ‘Garbage In, Garbage Out’ of the Class 6 Science book, a&nbsp; chapter on urban administration in the Political Science book for Class 6 and a chapter on wastewater treatment in the Class 7 Science textbook.</p><p class=\"MsoNormal\">In the first revision after 2007, NCERT has revamped their syllabus with the latest changes in Geography, Science, Political Science, Economics and English textbooks. But however, this is not the first time NCERT has included government schemes in their textbooks. During UPA’s regime, NCERT had included MNREGA, National Food Security Act 2013 and the Right to Information Act in textbooks.&nbsp;</p>', '1'),
(122, 1, 'normal', 'Kerala’s new academic calendar has 201 working days', '', 'calendar2497192960720.png', '', '', '', 'Db correspondent', '', '2018-06-07', '<p class=\"MsoNormal\">The Education Department of Kerala state has allotted 201 working days on the new academic calendar of 2018-19 aimed at bringing out the best results from SSLC students. According to the calendar, the new academic year will have eight working Saturdays compared to that of six in last years.</p><p class=\"MsoNormal\">Special focus will be on SSLC students to secure A+ in all subjects. As part of this, schools have been directed to scrutinise the performance of the students in the coming model examination of February 2019 with a view to providing special attention to students facing difficulty in any subjects.</p><p class=\"MsoNormal\">Based on the performance students, special training will be provided to the selected students from February 15 -28. All non-curricular activities will be completed by Dec 31st so that students can focus on studies thereafter. The State School Kalolsavam will be held on December 5,6,7,8 and 9 at Alappuzha. The school-level art festivals will be completed by September. The sub-district and district- level festivals will be completed by October and November, respectively.</p><p class=\"MsoNormal\">The State Science Festival will be held from November 9- 11. Only high school and higher secondary school level students will take part in the State level science fair. The state-level ‘Sargotsavam’ will be held from December 27-30.</p><p class=\"MsoNormal\">The annual examinations for classes 1 to 9 will take place in the third week of February and the SSLC, Higher Secondary and Vocational Higher Secondary examinations will take place between March 6 and 25.&nbsp;</p>', '1'),
(123, 1, 'normal', 'Kerala’s new academic calendar has 201 working days', '', 'calendar2497192960720.png', '', '', '', 'Db correspondent', '', '2018-06-07', '<p class=\"MsoNormal\">The Education Department of Kerala state has allotted 201 working days on the new academic calendar of 2018-19 aimed at bringing out the best results from SSLC students. According to the calendar, the new academic year will have eight working Saturdays compared to that of six in last years.</p><p class=\"MsoNormal\">Special focus will be on SSLC students to secure A+ in all subjects. As part of this, schools have been directed to scrutinise the performance of the students in the coming model examination of February 2019 with a view to providing special attention to students facing difficulty in any subjects.</p><p class=\"MsoNormal\">Based on the performance students, special training will be provided to the selected students from February 15 -28. All non-curricular activities will be completed by Dec 31st so that students can focus on studies thereafter. The State School Kalolsavam will be held on December 5,6,7,8 and 9 at Alappuzha. The school-level art festivals will be completed by September. The sub-district and district- level festivals will be completed by October and November, respectively.</p><p class=\"MsoNormal\">The State Science Festival will be held from November 9- 11. Only high school and higher secondary school level students will take part in the State level science fair. The state-level ‘Sargotsavam’ will be held from December 27-30.</p><p class=\"MsoNormal\">The annual examinations for classes 1 to 9 will take place in the third week of February and the SSLC, Higher Secondary and Vocational Higher Secondary examinations will take place between March 6 and 25. </p>', '0'),
(124, 5, 'normal', 'Dengue is Back, Beware!', 'Kochi, Ernakulam', '1495455281744a2a9ecf7b.jpg', '', '', '', 'Db correspondent', '', '2018-06-21', '<p class=\"MsoNormal\">As monsoon is gathering momentum, Dr Sreedevi, the Ernakulam district Medical Officer has warned against yet another spell of dengue outbreak. According to the notice issued by the Medical Officer, people are advised to keep their houses and the surroundings clean to prevent water stagnation which is vulnerable to Aedes mosquitoes, the carriers of Dengue.</p><p class=\"MsoNormal\">Water collected inside disposed of containers, plastic bottles, tyres, house suspension, and construction sites should be regularly cleaned. In order to follow these precautionary measures, once a week should be marked as ‘Red Day’, the notice says. Health officials, in association with associations of city residents, launched a campaign to remove non-biodegradable waste from house compounds. Civic bodies have also assigned lorries to collect the refuse.</p><p class=\"MsoNormal\">As of now, dengue has claimed 2 lives in the district and 19 cases have been confirmed in June. Twenty-six cases were confirmed in the district last month. The suspected cases were mainly reported from Angamaly, Malayattoor, Puthencruz, Ayyampuzha and Keezhmad.</p><p class=\"MsoNormal\">Fever accompanied by a headache, pain behind the eyes, pain in the limbs could be dengue. Though dengue is curable if detected in the initial stage, it can even be fatal if not detected early. Dengue haemorrhagic fever and dengue shock syndrome are the ones that can cause death. In the case of haemorrhagic fever, there will be blood discharge from the nose, mouth and the gums, low pulse, normal than usual thirst, trouble with breathing, dizziness and black faeces.</p><p>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n</p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-GB\"> </span></p>', '1'),
(125, 1, 'normal', 'School Van Accident Claims the Life 3 Kids and Caretaker ', 'Maradu, Ernakulam', 'school60.jpg', '', '', '', 'Db correspondent', '', '2018-06-21', '<p class=\"MsoNormal\">In yet another tragedy involving a school van, three children and the caretaker of ‘Kidz World’ play school, Maradu in the outskirts of Kochi after the school van accidentally fell into a temple pond in the area on June 11 afternoon. While two children died on the spot, one succumbed to injuries at a private hospital in Kochi. The deceased children are Adithyan, Carol Joby and Vidyalakshmi and the caretaker Latha Unni. The van was carrying a total of eight children of ‘Kidz World’ at the time of the accident.</p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-GB\" >The road in the area is very narrow and has no wall or divider separating it from the small but&nbsp;</span>deep temple pond, filled with weeds and water hyacinths. The driver who is reported to be continuing in a critical condition in hospital is charged, for unintentional homicide.</p><p class=\"MsoNormal\">This is the first accident in the new academic year involving school children. Last year in March 2017, two UKG students and a driver were killed, when the vehicle they were travelling, rammed against a mud wall at Koothattukulam. In June 2015, a tree crushed a school bus at Kothamangalam in which five children were killed. In September 2011 five children were killed when a van carrying around 25 school students plunged into a canal at Channankara near Thiruvananthapuram.</p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-GB\">&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\">\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n</p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-GB\">&nbsp;</span></p>', '1'),
(126, 1, 'normal', 'Kindergarten school registration made mandatory', 'Kochi, Ernakulam', 'pre1272291960720.jpg', '', '', '', 'Db correspondent', '', '2018-06-23', '<p class=\"MsoNormal\">In the wake of the tragic school van accident that killed 3 kids and a caretaker, all kindergarten schools in the state are required to get themselves registered before July 13 according to an order of the district collector. The pre-schools are required to submit information on the staff working, number of children studying, working hours, mode of transportation and basic facilities provided to the children.</p><p class=\"MsoNormal\">As part of Disaster Management law, the registration has been made mandatory to ensure the safety of children while linking parents, teachers and the pre-school during an accident. All vehicles transporting children to school are required to have a safety sticker provided by the Motor Vehicles Department before June 20. The department is authorised to issue clearance to the vehicles based on driver’s experience and the vehicle’s fitness after examining all the related documents.</p><p class=\"MsoNormal\">Vehicles found without the sticker after the scheduled date will be severely punished. The vehicle safety sticker is mandatory for all vehicles of educational institutions from kindergarten school to professional colleges and special schools.</p><p class=\"MsoNormal\">Motor Vehicles Department and the Police will club with all educational institutions to spread awareness among parents and teachers about the need for safe transportation of the school children. As of now, under Muvattupuzha RTO, 640 vehicles have been certified with the safety sticker. Under Ernakulam RTO, 2123 school vehicles have been certified.</p>', '1'),
(127, 4, 'normal', 'Kochi gearing up to change the face of India', 'Kochi, Ernakulam', 'rszfortkochisea.jpg', '', '', '', 'Db correspondent', '', '2018-06-25', '<p class=\"MsoNormal\">The recent discovery of abundant hydrate gas resources in coastal Kochi, ‘Queen of the Arabian Sea’ is likely to change the face of India in the coming years.&nbsp;A recent survey conducted by the American Geological Survey found that the Indian coasts of Kochi, Krishna-Godavari basin and Cauvery basin have almost 130 million cubic feet hydrate gas reserves which would be sufficient enough to meet the energy requirements of the country for the next 300 years.</p><p class=\"MsoNormal\">The survey also noted that, of the total gas accumulation, one-third of the reserve is found in the waters of Kochi, which is claimed to be the largest ‘Natural Gas Reserve’ till date. But the depressing fact is that India does not have the required advanced technology to extract the hydrate gas.</p><p class=\"MsoNormal\">Natural gas hydrates are a naturally occurring, an ice-like combination of natural gas and water found in oceans and polar regions, which can be used as a&nbsp; fuel. Growing energy demand, climate concerns, and a desire to shift towards cleaner fossil fuels have pushed the need for Natural Gas Hydrate as a potential energy resource for the future. However, producing it and effectively converting the same into energy in an environmentally safe manner continues to be a significant challenge.</p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-GB\">&nbsp;</span></p><p>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n</p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-GB\">&nbsp;</span></p>', '1'),
(128, 1, 'normal', '‘Hello English’ to improve communication skills', 'Ernakulam, Kerala', 'school298680960720.jpg', '', '', '', 'Db correspondent', '', '2018-06-25', '<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-GB\" >With the aim of helping students improve their </span><span lang=\"EN-GB\" >English communicative skills, the </span><span lang=\"EN-GB\" >Education</span><span lang=\"EN-GB\" > Department </span><span lang=\"EN-GB\" >has</span><span lang=\"EN-GB\" > rolled out “Hello English” programme for students of class 1 to 7 across Ernakulam.</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-GB\" >Concerned teachers </span><span lang=\"EN-GB\" >are being </span><span lang=\"EN-GB\" >given proper training </span><span lang=\"EN-GB\" >under </span><span lang=\"EN-GB\" >the programme started </span><span lang=\"EN-GB\" >on</span><span lang=\"EN-GB\" > June 20. With the </span><span lang=\"EN-GB\" >aid </span><span lang=\"EN-GB\" >of advanced technology, the trainers </span><span lang=\"EN-GB\" >help</span><span lang=\"EN-GB\" > students </span><span lang=\"EN-GB\" >to develop </span><span lang=\"EN-GB\" >their creative writing skills. Classroom libraries </span><span lang=\"EN-GB\" >are being </span><span lang=\"EN-GB\" >developed to help children </span><span lang=\"EN-GB\" >to improve their</span><span lang=\"EN-GB\" > reading skills. Special focus is being given to physically-challenged students. Two periods in a week of the regular school timetable are dedicated to ‘Hello English’ programme.</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-GB\" >A district-level monitoring committee headed by a programme coordinator for each district </span><span lang=\"EN-GB\" >is in charge</span><span lang=\"EN-GB\" > of the programme. </span><span lang=\"EN-GB\" >The committee will coordinate and monitor the effective conduct</span><span lang=\"EN-GB\" > of the programme.</span></p><p>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n</p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-GB\"> </span></p>', '1'),
(129, 23, 'normal', 'Malayalam Learning Programme for Migrant Labourers', 'Perumbavoor, Ernakulam', '80696856171f9c1fb111b.jpg', '', '', '', 'Db correspondent', '', '2018-06-20', '<p class=\"MsoNormal\">‘Changathi’ the state government’s Malayalam literacy programme aimed at helping the migrant labourers integrate and communicate with the local public, proved to be a hit as 469 labourers passed the literacy examination held on May 13.</p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-GB\" >When Due to the highest concentration of migrant workers 604 people attended the programme, 503 candidates appeared for the exam and 469 people passed the test. T</span><span lang=\"EN-GB\" >he programme was launched in Perumbavoor on August 15, 2017, due to the highest concentration of migrant worker there</span><span lang=\"EN-GB\" >. </span><span lang=\"EN-GB\" >The programme was inaugurated by the state education Minister C Raveendranath.</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\">A textbook called \'Hamari Malayalam\' was brought out to teach the migrant labourers. The 25 chapters of the book cover various topics such as health, hygiene, banking, human rights and ethical values.</p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-GB\" >Initially,</span><span lang=\"EN-GB\" > a survey was conducted in 27 wards of Perumbavoor to identify the recipients. Five social workers and students from MES College, Marampally were assigned as instructors. The classes were held on all Sundays at 10 factories, a madrassa and the Perumbavoor municipality’s cultural centre.</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-GB\">&nbsp;</span></p><p>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n</p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-GB\">&nbsp;</span></p>', '1'),
(130, 27, 'normal', 'Child helpline desk at Ernakulam South Railway Station', 'Kochi, Ernakulam', 'indian3535631960720.jpg', '', '', '', 'Db correspondent', '', '2018-06-21', '<p class=\"MsoNormal\">The Ernakulam south railway station has set up a child helpline desk to help innocent children from unwanted exploitation. The helpline desk was inaugurated the Ernakulam district collector, Mohammed Y Safirulla on Thursday, June 7. On the occasion, he hoped that the desk will be helpful in nabbing people who exploit children for their benefits.</p><p class=\"MsoNormal\">Helpline desk was launched at the railway station to help lost or children travelling alone on board trains. They are usually the victims of child trafficking or child labour. The desk will ensure that the children are protected by providing them with legal help.</p><p class=\"MsoNormal\">Under the leadership of the collector, the District administration along with Women and Child Development authority and the Railways will ensure the safety of children. Child helpline will ensure lost children are found, apart from providing the necessary legal protection to children arriving at the station being part of child labour from across the country.</p><p class=\"MsoNormal\">Since the district has the highest number of <span >migrant workers from other states, there is an increasing number of child labour cases. The helpline desk hopes to join with the common public to protect these children and provide basic education to these children. The collector, during his inaugural speech, expressed his wish to launch a booth at North station as well. Anyone can contact the helpline desk at 1098 or report directly to the helpline booth.</span></p><p>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n</p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-GB\"> </span></p>', '1'),
(131, 3, 'normal', 'Kabaddi Masters Dubai 2018: All you need to know', '', 'ProKabaddiplayedinIndia.jpg', '', '', '', 'Db correspondent', '', '2018-07-13', '<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-GB\" >Kabaddi Masters tournament hosted by Kabaddi Masters Dubai was a nine-day action-</span><span lang=\"EN-GB\" >packed</span><span lang=\"EN-GB\" > sports event from June 22-June 30, showcasing this game of Indian origin</span><span lang=\"EN-GB\" > to foreign lands. Though the game got its first exposure beyond the Indian borders in the 1963 Berlin Olympics, the Dubai tournament provided a wider arena for the game to spread its wings further.</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-GB\">Besides India and Pakistan, the tournament had participants from South Korea, Iran, Argentina and Kenya. The six teams were divided into two groups of three. The teams in each group played two matches against every other team in their respective group, with the top two teams from each group qualifying for the semi-finals.<o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-GB\">Group A:&nbsp;</span>India, Pakistan, Kenya</p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-GB\">Group B:&nbsp;</span>Iran, South Korea, Argentina</p><p class=\"MsoNormal\">The opening encounter of the tournament was<span lang=\"EN-GB\" > between</span><span lang=\"EN-GB\"> arch-rivals India and Pakistan, the first </span><span lang=\"EN-GB\" >tussle</span><span lang=\"EN-GB\"> between these two teams since the 2016 Kabaddi World cup. India thrashed Pakistan 36-20 in the opening match. The inaugural edition of the Dubai Kabaddi Masters was organised by the International Kabaddi Federation along with the Dubai Sports Council and with Star India network.&nbsp;</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-GB\" >The game is said to </span><span lang=\"EN-GB\" >have its </span><span lang=\"EN-GB\" >inception in the southern state of Tamil Nadu, India. Kabaddi is played between two teams of seven players; the object of the game is for a single player on offence, referred to as a \"raider\", </span><span lang=\"EN-GB\" >to run into the half area of the opposing team\'s court</span><span lang=\"EN-GB\" >, tag out as many of their defenders as possible, and return to their own half of the court, all without being tackled by the defenders. Points are scored for each player tagged by the raider, while the opposing team earns a point for stopping the raider.</span></p><p>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n</p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-GB\">&nbsp;</span></p>', '1');
