(132, 4, 'normal', 'Celebrity Gorilla Well-versed in Sign Language Dies', '', '292720156119ef179b6c0b.jpg', '', '', '', 'Db correspondent', '', '2018-06-26', '<div class=\"WordSection1\">\r\n\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-GB\" >Do </span><span lang=\"EN-GB\" >you know Koko? If you don’t, do know her. But by the time you start\r\nto love her, you would be </span><span lang=\"EN-GB\" >shocked\r\nto know that she is no more</span><span lang=\"EN-GB\" >. The gorilla who found a\r\nway into </span><span lang=\"EN-GB\" >people’s heart on account\r\nof her unique ability to communicate in sign\r\nlanguage</span><span lang=\"EN-GB\" > died on June 20 in California at the age of 46.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-GB\">The ‘celebrity’ gorilla, who learnt sign\r\nlanguage to communicate with humans died in her sleep, confirmed The Gorilla\r\nFoundation, </span><span lang=\"EN-GB\" >a</span><span lang=\"EN-GB\"> non-profit organization responsible for taking care of the primate.\r\nInitially named Hanabi-ko meaning fireworks, </span><span lang=\"EN-GB\" >she </span><span lang=\"EN-GB\">was taught sign language by a\r\nresearcher, Dr Francine Patterson. Koko understood almost 2,000 words of\r\nEnglish. The first symbols that Patterson taught Koko were signs for\r\n\"eat,\" \"drink\" and \"more,\" and over the years,\r\nKoko accumulated hundreds of words that she could combine into phrases using\r\nsigns</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-GB\">Of the English language taught to her, Koko\r\nhad a few choices of words which were incorporated into a song about climate\r\nchange titled \"Man Stupid,\" created in collaboration with the Laurel\r\nCanyon Animal Company and posted</span><span lang=\"EN-GB\" > on</span><span lang=\"EN-GB\"> YouTube in January\r\n2017.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-GB\">Koko also had many celebrity friends who </span><span lang=\"EN-GB\" >used</span><span lang=\"EN-GB\"> visited her </span><span lang=\"EN-GB\" >in </span><span lang=\"EN-GB\">her captivity. Koko\r\nmet Flea, the bassist in the Red Hot Chill Peppers, and the actor Betty White.\r\nShe was quite close to actor and comedian Robin Williams. </span><span lang=\"EN-GB\" >It was reported that </span><span lang=\"EN-GB\">Koko\r\nwas “quiet and very thoughtful” when told of Williams’ death.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-GB\">Koko was so popular that she appeared on\r\nthe cover of National Geographic with a picture that the </span><span lang=\"EN-GB\" >female primate took of herself </span><span lang=\"EN-GB\">in a mirror. She is survived by her </span><span lang=\"EN-GB\" >partner</span><span lang=\"EN-GB\">, a male named Ndume. <o:p></o:p></span></p>\r\n\r\n</div><p>\r\n\r\n<span lang=\"EN-GB\" ><br clear=\"all\" >\r\n</span>\r\n\r\n</p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-GB\">&nbsp;</span></p>', '1'),
(133, 4, 'normal', 'NASA Plans to keep Earth Safe from Asteroids', '', 'asteroidalamy.jpg', '', '', '', 'Db correspondent', '', '2018-06-27', '<div class=\"WordSection1\">\r\n\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\">Stop worrying that an asteroid hit would wipe out all life from Earth. The good news is that NASA, White House and the Federal Emergency Management Agency (FEMA) are at your rescue.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-GB\">The \"National Near-Earth Object Preparedness Strategy and Action Plan (NEO)\" outlines the steps that the team would take over the next decade to prevent and prepare for </span><span lang=\"EN-GB\" >any dangerous asteroid strikes on Earth.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-GB\">The </span><span lang=\"EN-GB\" >plan</span><span lang=\"EN-GB\"> details out five ways to prepare for a hit. It includes detecting, tracking, and more effective decision-making, </span><span lang=\"EN-GB\" >increasing</span><span lang=\"EN-GB\"> international cooperation </span><span lang=\"EN-GB\" >with the objective of</span><span lang=\"EN-GB\"> preparing the rest of the world, and coming up with a plan of emergency procedures if they found an asteroid </span><span lang=\"EN-GB\" >heading </span><span lang=\"EN-GB\">towards </span><span lang=\"EN-GB\" >the</span><span lang=\"EN-GB\"> Earth.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-GB\">Goals</span><span lang=\"EN-GB\"><o:p></o:p></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-GB\">The first goal is to enhance Near-Earth Object (NEO) detection, tracking, and characterization capabilities, in order to increase the response time </span><span lang=\"EN-GB\" >in the US. and all of Earth. </span><span lang=\"EN-GB\">Though asteroid pieces, more than 100 tonnes, bombard the Earth daily, most disintegrate before hitting the surface of our planet.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-GB\">The NASA dreams to develop technologies for future deflection and disruption missions and the NASA team visions to “increase international cooperation on NEO preparation.”&nbsp; It also plans to routinely run through NEO impact procedures, including </span><span lang=\"EN-GB\" >practising </span><span lang=\"EN-GB\">the action steps with foreign governments.<o:p></o:p></span></p>\r\n\r\n</div><p>\r\n\r\n<span lang=\"EN-GB\" ><br clear=\"all\" >\r\n</span>\r\n\r\n</p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-GB\">&nbsp;</span></p>', '1'),
(134, 4, 'normal', 'Were Humans at the Verge of Extinction once?', '', '800pxBoxersPanathenaicMet06.1021.51.jpg', '', '', '', 'Db correspondent', '', '2018-06-27', '<div class=\"WordSection1\">\r\n\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-GB\" >Genetic variations in human population not\r\nonly arises from genetic variations, but also from cultural or social changes.\r\nA recent study in the world of genetics reveals\r\nthat </span><span lang=\"EN-GB\" >humans</span><span lang=\"EN-GB\" > nearly caused the extinction of </span><span lang=\"EN-GB\" >mankind </span><span lang=\"EN-GB\" >in the Neolithic Age.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-GB\">Researchers believe 7,000 years ago\r\nfighting </span><span lang=\"EN-GB\" >among</span><span lang=\"EN-GB\"> patrilineal (father’s line) clans led to the sudden choke </span><span lang=\"EN-GB\" >in human </span><span lang=\"EN-GB\">diversity. The\r\nNeolithic Y-chromosome bottleneck, as it is called, has puzzled anthropologists\r\nand biologists since it was first discovered in 2015. Across Africa, Europe and\r\nAsia, the Y chromosome passed on from father to son, collapsed, such that there\r\nwas only one man for every 17 women.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-GB\">Stanford University </span><span lang=\"EN-GB\" >researchers</span><span lang=\"EN-GB\"> argue that\r\n“competition between patrilineal kin groups” also called tribalism, led to this\r\ngene collapse. They point out that, within a clan, women could have married\r\ninto new clans, while men stayed with their own clans their entire lives. This\r\nwould mean that, within the clan, Y chromosome variation is limited.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-GB\">Later on,\r\nbrutal warfare between clans could have wiped out many clans, along with their\r\nparticular type of Y-chromosome. Those clans successful in warfare grew wealthy\r\nand powerful. The monarch and his sons had exclusive mating rights as they\r\ncould have many wives and mistresses thus diminishing the genetic diversity of\r\nour species.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-GB\" >According to the\r\nresearcher’s data, the warfare would have been brutal that it killed one-twentieth\r\nof the entire male population. So it is believed that the first civilization\r\nrose from ashes.<a name=\"_GoBack3\"></a>?<o:p></o:p></span></p>\r\n\r\n</div><p>\r\n\r\n<span lang=\"EN-GB\" ><br clear=\"all\" >\r\n</span>\r\n\r\n</p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-GB\">&nbsp;</span></p>', '1'),
(135, 5, 'normal', 'KSRTC Launches Electric Buses', 'Vytilla Mobility Hub, Ernakulam', 'rszuntitled.png', '', '', '', 'Db correspondent', '', '2018-06-28', '<div class=\"WordSection1\">\r\n\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-GB\" >Kerala’s public transport system, KSRTC, has launched electric buses in the state on June 18 thereby Kerala becoming the sixth state in the to have such with the public service. The trial service lasted for 15 days, starting with </span><span lang=\"EN-GB\" >eight </span><span lang=\"EN-GB\" >days in Thiruvananthapuram and following seven days in Ernakulam.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-GB\">Education Minister C Raveendranath flagged off the e-bus after a function held at Vytilla Mobility Hub on June 23. C Raveendranath, MLA,&nbsp; PT Thomas and MP K V Thomas also travelled in the electric bus </span><span lang=\"EN-GB\" >on its maiden trip.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-GB\">In Kochi, eight services </span><span lang=\"EN-GB\" >are</span><span lang=\"EN-GB\"> scheduled for the electric bus starting from Aluva at 6.30 am and ending at the same place by 8.35 pm. The bus will be plying to Fort Kochi, Infopark, Paravoor, Nedumbassery Airport and Aroor covering 292 km daily.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-GB\">On June 27, the bus will move to Kozhikode </span><span lang=\"EN-GB\" >for its trial run there</span><span lang=\"EN-GB\">. The bus </span><span lang=\"EN-GB\" >is </span><span lang=\"EN-GB\">built by Hyderabad-based Gold Stone Infratech which is providing it free of cost for the trial run. </span><span lang=\"EN-GB\" >Low-floored</span><span lang=\"EN-GB\"> and air-conditioned, the bus can seat up to 35 passengers and has a wheel-chair facility. It has a wall-mounted lithium-iron BYD Goldstone FE battery which gets fully-charged in about four hours and can travel up to 350 kilometres.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-GB\">For the trial run, the KSRTC has priced its tickets </span><span lang=\"EN-GB\" >on par with</span><span lang=\"EN-GB\"> what is being charged in its air-conditioned Volvo buses.&nbsp; As of 2016, the state-run corporation has more than 600 low-floor A/C and non-A/C buses in its fleet.<o:p></o:p></span></p>\r\n\r\n</div><p>\r\n\r\n<span lang=\"EN-GB\" ><br clear=\"all\" >\r\n</span>\r\n\r\n</p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-GB\">&nbsp;</span></p>', '1'),
(136, 3, 'normal', 'Kerala Blasters Gearing up to Challenge European Clubs', '', 'football3595406960720.jpg', '', '', '', 'Db correspondent', '', '2018-06-23', '<div class=\"WordSection1\">\r\n\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-GB\" >Indian Super League’s (ISL) strong team, Kerala Blasters will be seen playing a pre-season friendly match against A-League club Melbourne City FC and La Liga club Girona in July at the </span><span lang=\"EN-GB\" >Kochi’s own famed Jawaharlal Nehru stadium.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-GB\">After the Delhi based franchise</span><span lang=\"EN-GB\" >?</span><span lang=\"EN-GB\"> had played a friendly match against Premier League club West Bromwich Albion in 2016, Kochi Blasters will be the second team of ISL to play against European Club.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-GB\">The club coached under David James ended ISL 2018 coming 6th, thus missing out on a chance to participate in the finals. The Kerala Blasters also participated in the Super Cup, being eliminated in the first round by NEROCA.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-GB\">Kerala Blasters FC had strengthened their defences with the signing of young defender Abdul Hakku Nediyodath. The youngster follows Anas Edathodika as Kerala second defensive signing in the last ten days. So far, Kerala Blasters have brought in Indian internationals such as Holicharan Narzary and Anas Edathodika, while signing young prospects such as Dheeraj Singh and now, Abdul Hakku Nediyodath.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-GB\">Girona FC had qualified for the La Liga last season for the very first time in their 87-year-old history. In their maiden season, they finished 10th in the league. Their biggest achievement last year was beating Champions League winners Real Madrid 2-1.<o:p></o:p></span></p>\r\n\r\n</div><p>\r\n\r\n<span lang=\"EN-GB\" >\r\n</span>\r\n\r\n</p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-GB\">&nbsp;</span></p>', '1'),
(137, 5, 'normal', 'Reading day celebrated with books and colour', 'Ernakulam, Kerala', '63339846377d08596f9eb.jpg', '', '', '', 'Db correspondent', '', '2018-06-21', '<div class=\"WordSection1\">\r\n\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-GB\" >As part of</span><span lang=\"EN-GB\" > this year’s</span><span lang=\"EN-GB\" > Vaayanadinam</span><span lang=\"EN-GB\" > </span><span lang=\"EN-GB\" >(Day of Reading) celebrated every year on June 19, </span><span lang=\"EN-GB\" >various events </span><span lang=\"EN-GB\" >were conducted in different parts of the state </span><span lang=\"EN-GB\" >commemorating the contributions of late P N Panicker who devoted his life to the cause of encouraging reading habit</span><span lang=\"EN-GB\" >. Ernakulam district level celebration was </span><span lang=\"EN-GB\" >inaugurated at </span><span lang=\"EN-GB\" >SNV HSS, Paravoor.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-GB\" >The program was organized jointly by the Information and Public Relations Department and the District Library Council and Public Education Departments. Students took part in a book procession organised as part of the inaugural ceremony. Books were gifted to the guests who attended the program in cloth bags.&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-GB\" >The Aluva Taluk Staff Welfare Committee conducted an event, ‘Smaranika Dhyuthi’ to honour the contributions of P N Panicker. The event was inaugurated by district collector Mohammed Y Safirullah.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-GB\">‘PN Panicker who </span><span lang=\"EN-GB\" >initiated universal literacy movement in the state is considered as ‘the one man soldier of the reading world’ said Sethu. “Kerala was able to achieve 100% literacy rate due to the increase. In terms of </span><span lang=\"EN-GB\" >reading,</span><span lang=\"EN-GB\" > the state is a role model to the world as no other state or country has village libraries. There are 7000 libraries in the state. The government gives salary to all the librarians. Some of the libraries are 60 or 50 years old. PN Panicker is the man who initiated this reading trend,” </span><span lang=\"EN-GB\" >recalled</span><span lang=\"EN-GB\" > Sethu.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-GB\" >PN Panicker is the one who formed Thiruvithaamkoor Granthasala Sangham (Travancore Library Association) in 1945 with 47 rural libraries, encouraging everyone to \'Read and Grow\'. He travelled through the villages of Kerala proclaiming the value of reading. He succeeded in bringing some 6,000 libraries into this network. Grandhasala Sangham won the prestigious ‘Krupsakaya Award’ from UNESCO in 1975.</span><span lang=\"EN-GB\"><o:p></o:p></span></p>\r\n\r\n</div><p>\r\n\r\n<span lang=\"EN-GB\" >', '1'),
(138, 22, 'normal', 'Kerala Floods 2018: Kuttanad struggles to pick up pace after floods', 'Kuttanad, Kerala', '9.jpg', '', '', '', 'Db correspondent', '', '2018-09-25', '<p class=\"MsoNormal\">Though floods are not new to Kuttanad, as it lies 2.2 metres below sea level, this year’s monsoon along with the heavy inflow from the rivers of the highlands resulted in a massive deluge in ‘Kerala’s granary’. The floodwaters from the mountain ranges in the East resulting in overflowing of the rivers, Pampa, Achankovil, Manimala, Meenachal and Muvattupuzha displaced around two lakh people from their houses, presenting a nightmare to Kuttanad.</p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-GB\">Kainakiri panchayath of Kuttanad was worst affected. Even when the water level in the rivers began receding, water from other areas flowed into Kainakiri as it is the lowest lying area. There are 5,579 houses in the panchayat, and people of the 15 wards in the panchayat had to be housed in 10 relief camps.</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-GB\">For several days, Kuttanad remained in the dark, with its residents continuing in camps set up in Allapuzha and Kottayam even as people in many other affected areas moved to their battered homes. As most houses in Kuttanad are situated amid paddy fields and backwaters, everyone had to be evacuated when the waters began rising.</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-GB\">Official statistics state that 8,500 hectares of paddy cultivation and 80% of livestock has perished. Kuttanad’s major source of income is dependent on backwater fishing, paddy cultivation and tourism. The devastating floods had hit the houseboat and resort tourism as well. Top rated resorts in the area were completely inundated in this monsoon.</span></p><p>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n</p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-GB\">After the flood-induced vacation, 116 schools in Kuttanad reopened on September 3. The education department had made arrangements to provide study materials lost in the flood.<o:p></o:p></span></p>', '1'),
(139, 23, 'normal', 'Move to integrate school education under a single agency', '', '7127903885c66b2c2971b.jpg', '', '', '', 'Db correspondent', '', '2018-06-25', '<div class=\"Section1\">\r\n\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\">Union Human Resource Development Minister\r\nPrakash Javedkar has launched SamagraShiksha scheme with a view to improving the quality and focus of education by\r\nunifying all existing projects under one umbrella and instructed all state\r\ngovernment to follow the same.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-GB\">Samagra Shiksha</span><span lang=\"EN-GB\"> is a school education project introduced by the central government\r\nof India to absorb&nbsp; SarvaShikshaAbhiyan\r\n(SSA), RashtriyaMadhyamikShikshaAbhiyan (RMSA) and Teacher Education under one\r\numbrella. The scheme aims to provide a holistic development of education and\r\ninculcate digital technology into education through smart classrooms and\r\ndigital boards by unifying all levels of education pre-school to Class 12.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-GB\" ><b>Radical changes<o:p></o:p></b></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-GB\">The scheme will be in effect from the\r\ncurrent academic year and is mutually undertaken by the central and state\r\ngovernments with plans to radically improve the infrastructure and quality of\r\nteaching.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-GB\">State Council of Educational Research and\r\nTraining (SCERT), the state agency responsible for the educational programs in\r\nKerala has also announced the plans to integrate SSLC and Higher Secondary\r\nexaminations under a unified system following SamagraShiksha.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\">The project will also merge the Directorate\r\nof Public Instruction, Higher Secondary Directorate and VHSE to transform the educational system in the state. As all\r\nagencies follow different systems of administration, the state government has\r\nappointed a committee for the smooth integration of management from different\r\ndirectorates.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-GB\">As a centrally sponsored scheme implemented\r\nthrough a single State Implementation Society (SIS) at the State/UT level. At\r\nthe national level, there would be a governing council headed by Minister of\r\nHuman Resource Development and a Project Approval Board (PAB) headed by\r\nSecretary, Department of School Education and Literacy.</span></p>\r\n\r\n</div><p>\r\n\r\n<span lang=\"EN-GB\" ><br clear=\"all\" >\r\n</span>\r\n\r\n</p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><a name=\"_GoBack\"></a><span lang=\"EN-GB\">&nbsp;</span></p>', '1'),
(140, 3, 'normal', 'Why Abhilash Tomy is the talk of the town?', '', 'abhilashweb.jpg', '', '', '', 'Db correspondent', '', '2018-10-03', '<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-GB\" >Abhilash Tomy</span><span lang=\"EN-GB\" > is a celebrated sailor from India who is also a pilot in the Indian Navy. As part of the International solo circumnavigation Golden Globe Race, he set sail on July 1. While taking part in the competition, his yacht, ‘Thuriya’ mast collapsed in a rough storm in the remote southern Indian Ocean on September 21.</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-GB\">Due to rough weather, Thuriyagot tossed in the face of high tides before stabilising. Tomy texted through satellite-based device requesting for evacuation stating his back has been injured and he is unable to move. The sailor in distress was spotted by the Indian Navy Reconnaissance aircraft and has been rescued by French vessel Osiris on September 24.</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-GB\" >It may be noted that Tomy</span><span lang=\"EN-GB\"> is the first Indian and second Asian to complete a solo non-stop circumnavigation around the world on a boat that began on November 1, 2012, and ended on March 31, 2013.</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-GB\"><b>GOLDEN GLOBE RACE 2018</b></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-GB\">The 2018 Golden Globe Race is a sailing race around the world which started on 1 July 2018 with 18 sailors who do not have any outside assistance from Les Sables-d\'Olonne, France. The race organised after the&nbsp;</span>fifty years existence of&nbsp;Sunday Times Golden Globe Race, allows yachts similar to those used at that time, with no modern technology permitted.&nbsp;The entrants belonged to 13 different countries. Out of them, six have chosen the class compliant but relatively modern yacht called Rustler 36.</p>', '1'),
(141, 5, 'normal', 'Proud moment! CIAL bags UN’s environment award', '', 'Cochininternationalairportterminal.jpg', '', '', '', 'Db Correspondent', '', '2018-10-02', '<div class=\"Section1\">\r\n\r\n<div class=\"Section1\">\r\n\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span lang=\"EN-GB\">&nbsp;</span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span >World’s first solar airport, Cochin\r\nInternational Airport Ltd (CIAL) has bagged the United </span><span >Nation\'s</span><span >\r\nhighest environmental accolade, ‘Champion of the Earth’ award (2018). The award\r\n</span><span >was</span><span > presented on the sidelines of the UN\r\ngeneral assembly in New York on September 26.</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-GB\" >The </span><span lang=\"EN-GB\">UN environment executive director Erik Solheim info<a name=\"_GoBack\"></a>rmed\r\nCIAL MD VJ Kurien through a letter which read, “</span><span lang=\"EN-GB\" >This is the UN\'s highest environmental accolade and it reflects your\r\nleadership in the use of sustainable energy.”</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-GB\" >Solheim and his UN team had\r\nvisited the international airport earlier this year to applaud on the use of\r\nsolar energy to meet the airport’s needs, calling it a leading example among\r\nglobal airports.</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-GB\" >In 2005, the UN established the\r\n‘Champions of the Earth’ awards to honour environmental leaders of society.</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\">\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n</p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><a name=\"_GoBack2\"></a><span lang=\"EN-GB\" >The award is the\r\nUnited Nations highest environmental honour recognizing visionary people and\r\norganisations all over the world that exemplify leadership and advocate action\r\non sustainable development, climate change and a life of dignity for all. The\r\naward supports this process by illustrating, through the examples of the\r\nlaureates, that the transition to a low-carbon, resource-efficient, inclusive\r\nand sustainable world is not just possible, but already in progress.</span></p></div></div>', '1'),
(142, 1, 'normal', 'Renowned filmmaker Shaison talks to students at St. Albert’s HSS', 'Ernakulam', 'IMG20181212WA0090.jpg', '', '', '', 'Db correspondent', '', '2018-12-13', '<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span lang=\"EN-IN\">Renowned filmmaker Shaison talks to students at St.Albert’s HSS</span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-IN\">St.Albert’s HSS Ernakulam had a wonderful occasion when the renowned documentary filmmaker, editor and cameraman, Shaison P Ouseph visited the school last day. The programme starts with the welcome speech by School Captain proceeded with a seminar on “Mass media and Youth” by the English club of the school. During the seminar, Shaison shared his experience in photography to a group consisting of 100 club members. The crowd was facilitated with different aspects of photography and frames.<sub> </sub>Slide presentation of famous photographs turned out to be an inspiration for the children. The session turned out to be a great learning opportunity for students and teachers.</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-IN\">He also urged them to come up with the art exhibitions, workshops, theatre, musical events and many other cultural events according to their taste. He also suggested them to have a glance at highly innovative programmes like the Kochi Muziris Biennale.</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-IN\">His video presentation showcased his public service campaigns promoting literacy, women empowerment and against child exploitations which had won him many national and international accolades including United Nations International Labour Organization and US Embassy awards. The General Manager, Rev.Fr. Michael Dcruz and HM,&nbsp;N J Francis was present during the auspicious event.</span></p>', '1'),
(143, 4, 'normal', 'ISRO\'s GSAT-7A brings strategic boost for Indian Air Force', 'Ernakulam, Kerala', 'rsz21.jpg', '', '', '', 'Db Correspondent', '', '2018-12-20', '<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-IN\" > </span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\">ISRO launches its 35th communication satellite nicknamed ‘Angry Bird’ and the 13th flight of GSLV rocket to Earth’s orbit on December 20, 2018, from Andhra Pradesh’s Sriharikota. GSAT-7A will give a boost to the strategic communication and networking capabilities of the Indian Air Force.</p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><br></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-IN\"><b>Know GSAT-7A and its launch<o:p></o:p></b></span></p><p class=\"MsoListParagraphCxSpFirst\" ><!--[if !supportLists]--><span lang=\"EN-IN\" >·<span >         </span></span><!--[endif]--><span lang=\"EN-IN\">ISRO’s GSLV-F11 launched communication satellite GSAT-7A from the Satish Dhawan Space Centre in Sriharikota at 4.10pm on December 20, 2018. <o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoListParagraphCxSpMiddle\" ><!--[if !supportLists]--><span lang=\"EN-IN\" >·<span >         </span></span><!--[endif]--><span lang=\"EN-IN\">GSLV-F11 is the 7th flight carrying a satellite to outer space and this is the 7th launch from the space station in 2018.<o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoListParagraphCxSpMiddle\" ><!--[if !supportLists]--><span lang=\"EN-IN\" >·<span >         </span></span><!--[endif]--><span lang=\"EN-IN\">The 2,250 kg GSAT-7A has a life span of eight years.<o:p></o:p></span></p><p>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n</p><p class=\"MsoListParagraphCxSpLast\" ><!--[if !supportLists]--><span lang=\"EN-IN\" >·<span >         </span></span><!--[endif]--><span lang=\"EN-IN\">This is the 39th Indian communications satellite which will provide a secure mode of communication, exclusively to be used by Indian Air Force. <o:p></o:p></span></p>', '1'),
(144, 4, 'normal', 'Bees just need 4 brain cells to count!', '', '', '', '', '', 'Db Correspondent', '', '2019-01-03', '<p class=\"MsoNormal\">Having minimal nerve cells in their brain, bees showed immense intelligence in counting with small numbers. To understand their counting ability, the researchers of the Queen Mary University of London reconstructed a very simple miniature \'brain\' on a computer with just four nerve cells, a number fewer than the number a real bee has.</p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-IN\"><b>The result of the experiment<o:p></o:p></b></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-IN\">Researchers found that the simulated ‘brain’ could count accurately small numbers when closely inspecting, the same way bees count. The result showed that the clever counting behaviour of bees makes complex mathematical counting much easier, proving that bees have impressive cognitive abilities with limited brain power.</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-IN\"><b>Earlier experiments<o:p></o:p></b></span></p><p>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n</p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-IN\">Previous studies had already proved that bees could count up to a maximum of five items when putting on display. Brain size matters a lot when it comes to bees. As they have to implement efficient computational algorithms to solve mathematical counting with only one million nerve cells in total. <o:p></o:p></span></p>', '0'),
(145, 4, 'normal', 'Bees just need 4 brain cells to count!', '', 'bee2373914960720.jpg', '', '', '', 'Db Correspondent', '', '2019-01-04', '<p class=\"MsoNormal\">Having minimal nerve cells in their brain, bees showed immense intelligence in counting with small numbers. To understand their counting ability, the researchers of the Queen Mary University of London reconstructed a very simple miniature \'brain\' on a computer with just four nerve cells, a number fewer than the number a real bee has.</p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-IN\"><span >The result of the experiment<o:p></o:p></span></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-IN\">Researchers found that the simulated ‘brain’ could count accurately small numbers when closely inspecting, the same way bees count. The result showed that the clever counting behaviour of bees makes complex mathematical counting much easier, proving that bees have impressive cognitive abilities with limited brain power.</span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-IN\"><span >Earlier experiments<o:p></o:p></span></span></p><p></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-IN\">Previous studies had already proved that bees could count up to a maximum of five items when putting on display. Brain size matters a lot when it comes to bees. As they have to implement efficient computational algorithms to solve mathematical counting with only one million nerve cells in total. </span></p>', '1'),
(146, 4, 'normal', 'For the first time ever a spacecraft lands on the far side of the moon', '', '201809126258TPSTPR2018Q3180904p14legacy.png', '', '', 'The Chinese lunar exploration mission, Chang\'e-4, successfully soft-landed its lunar rover into the darker hemisphere of moon\'s surface for the first time ever in history. So far humans have made 6 manned and 17 robotic successful landings on our natural satellite but were all on the visible hemisphere. Thus the Chinese exploration could be a game changer for human enquiry into the mysteries of our universe. ', 'Db correspondent', '', '2019-01-05', '<p class=\"MsoNormal\" >On Thursday, with much surprise to the scientific community around the world, Chinese space agency CNSA announced the successful landing of its lunar rover under the mission Chang\'e-4 on the far side of the moon at around 4.00 am (IST) January 03, 2019. Though the vehicle is no better than any other lunar rover, the mission is expected to dig deep into mysteries of the origin of moon, earth or may even the solar system itself as the region with so many geological peculiarities has never been explored before.&nbsp;</p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" >The robotic spacecraft which landed on the Aitken Basin of the moon was launched on December 07, 2018 and entered the orbit of the moon on December 12, 2018. Aitken Basin is the largest known impact crater in the entire solar system situated in the lunar south pole. With a diameter of 25000 km and a depth of 13 km, the giant circular depression which exposed the lunar crust and even the mantle might have caused due to an ancient collision. The site is a perfect place to study the changes happened on the face of the moon.&nbsp;</p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" >The far side of the moon is the hemisphere of the moon that always faces away from earth and is not&nbsp;observable from our planet. Due to a phenomenon called tidal locking the same side of the moon is always facing the earth known as the near side of the earth. Because of which the other side came to know as the far side of the earth.&nbsp;</p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" >The spacecraft named after the Chinese moon goddess, Chang\'e-4 started sending photographs of the far side of moon via Queqiao, a rely satellite launched on May 20, 2018, ahead of the lunar mission, as no communication is possible to earth from the far side of the moon.&nbsp;</p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" >The lunar mission will also be a boost to human inhabitants to colonize moon as it contains a small biosphere with symbiotic life forms such as cotton, rapeseed, potato, fruit fly, yeast and rockcress. The test is to find if plants could perform photosynthesis and respiration in the lunar&nbsp;surface.&nbsp;</p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" ><o:p></o:p></p><p>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n</p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></p>', '1');
